<DIV1 N="1" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000018.tif" N="[errata sheet]">

<PB REF="00000019.tif" N="[1]">
<HEAD>I. De septem sacramentis. De psalmo,<MILESTONE N="150a" UNIT="folio"> Exercitatus sum et defecit spiritus.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="part">
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1">SOnderliche his man astoned</L>
<L>In his owene mende,</L>
<L>Wanne he not<SUP>e</SUP> neuer wannes he com&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="4">Ne wider he schel wende;</L>
<L>And more,<NOTE PLACE="foot">In the MS. the 'bob' of every stanza is written in the margin to the right of the first line, a curved line running down from the rime-word of the 'bob' to the corresponding one of the last line.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;et al his lyf his here imengde</L>
<L N="7">Wi&thorn;e sorwe and eke wi&thorn;e sore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="8">&para; And wanne he dei&thorn;e, ne mey me wite</L>
<L>Woder he come&thorn; to wisse;</L>
<L>Bote as a stock &thorn;er li&thorn;e &thorn;et body,</L>
<L N="11">Wi&thorn;e-&thorn;oute alle manere blisse.</L>
<L>Wat &thorn;enkeste?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;enkeste</I> [: <I>lengeste</I>], phonetically <I>&thorn;engste</I> [: <I>lengste</I>].</NOTE></L>
<L>And hondred winter &yogh;ef a leue&thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And hondred</I> for <I>An h</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="14">&THORN;at his lyf mid &thorn;e lengeste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="15">&para; Onne&thorn;e creft eny &thorn;at stat,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="2"></L>
<L>Ac some crefte&thorn; &thorn;at halue;</L>
<L>And for siknesse lechecreft,</L>
<L N="18">And for &thorn;e goute sealue</L>
<L>Me make&thorn;e;</L>
<L>For wanne man drawi&thorn; in-to oldeward,</L>
<L N="21">Wel ofte his bones ake&thorn;.
<PB REF="00000020.tif" N="2"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="22">&para; And be a man neuer so sprind,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef he schel libbe to elde,</L>
<L>Be him wel siker, &thorn;er-to he schel,</L>
<L N="25">And his de&thorn;es dette &yogh;elde;<NOTE PLACE="foot">In <I>de&thorn;es, y</I> is written over the first <I>e</I> in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L>To gile</L>
<L>&YOGH;et meni &yogh;ong man wene&thorn; longe leue,</L>
<L N="28">And leue&thorn; wel litle wyle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="29">&para; &THORN;os we be&thorn; al awey-ward,</L>
<L>&THORN;at scholde her byleue;</L>
<L>And &yogh;et me sei&thorn; ydemyd we be&thorn;e</L>
<L N="32">In Adam and ine Eue</L>
<L>Te helle :<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>helle</I>, MS. <I>telle</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wa&yogh;t hope his here of sauuement<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sauuement</I>, above it <I>soule</I> sauacioun, written with pencil by a later hand.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="150b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="35">Now time his for to telle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="36">&para; Me sei&thorn;e &thorn;e ri&yogh;te wone&yogh;yng</L>
<L>Ine heuene hyt his to manne;</L>
<L>Ac heuene his hei&yogh;e, and we be&thorn; heuy,</L>
<L N="39">Howe scholde we &thorn;ider &thorn;anne?</L>
<L>Bi leddre.</L>
<L>Howe mey &thorn;at be? wo dar &thorn;er-oppe stei&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="42">For dou&yogh;te of fotes bleddre?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="43">&para; Man, &thorn;y laddre nys nau&yogh;t of wode<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;y</I>, read <I>&thorn;ys</I>?</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="3"></L>
<L>&THORN;at may to heuene leste;</L>
<L>Ac on &thorn;er his, &thorn;at iakob isei&yogh;e</L>
<L N="46">&THORN;er he sleppe inne hys reste.</L>
<L>Now schewe &thorn;is:</L>
<L>&THORN;is ilke laddre is charite,</L>
<L N="49">&THORN;e stales gode &thorn;eawis.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="50">&para; Her-on ihesus stawe vppe bi-fore,</L>
<L>Al for to teche ous sty&yogh;e;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sty&yogh;e</I>, MS. <I>stey&yogh;e</I>.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000021.tif" N="3"></L>
<L>Nowe hy&yogh;e, man, and folwe wel,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>folwe</I>, MS. <I>ffolwe</I>, with a faint &yogh; over the <I>w</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="53">A-doun &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne sy&yogh;e</L>
<L>By-weyled;</L>
<L>For yf &thorn;ou nelt nau&yogh;t climme &thorn;os,</L>
<L N="56">Of heuene &thorn;ou hest yfayled.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="57">&para; And &thorn;at man louye god and man,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I>, read <I>&thorn;a&yogh;</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L>Ase charite hyt hote&thorn;;</L>
<L>&THORN;at he so wel y&thorn;eawed be,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I>, read <I>&thorn;a&yogh;</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">&THORN;at alle men hit note&thorn;e:</L>
<L>Wat &thorn;anne?</L>
<L>&YOGH;et senne-les ne may he nau&yogh;t be,</L>
<L N="63">Ac a dey&thorn;e, and he not wanne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="64">&para; Of brokele kende his &thorn;at he dei&thorn;e,</L>
<L>For hy ne mo&yogh;e nau&yogh;t dury;</L>
<L>And aldey he to senne falle&thorn;,</L>
<L N="67">Her ne mo&yogh;e nau&yogh;t pury<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mo&yogh;e</I>, <I>o&yogh;</I> on erasure.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of serewnessche.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>w</I> over <I>en;</I> see note.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;et hope &thorn;ou wel, man, for al &thorn;is,<MILESTONE N="151a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="70">&THORN;at go&yogh;de lyf wole &thorn;e wessche.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The &yogh; in <I>go&yogh;de</I> small and indistinct.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="71">&para; For de&thorn;e ne fall nau&yogh;t into wanhope,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>into</I>.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="4"></L>
<L>For god him self for &thorn;e deide;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde day he aros a&yogh;eyn</L>
<L N="74">Of &thorn;e &thorn;rou&yogh; &thorn;er men hine leyde,</L>
<L>Ine tokene</L>
<L>&THORN;at, man, &thorn;i body arise schel</L>
<L N="77">Of dei&thorn;e, nan more to blokne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="78">&para; &THORN;e bible sey&thorn;e &thorn;at mannys blod<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>blod</I>, MS. <I>blodis</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hys ry&yogh;t &thorn;er saule giste;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;er</I> on erasure.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000022.tif" N="4"></L>
<L>And water wassche&thorn; &thorn;e felthe a-wey,</L>
<L N="81">&THORN;er me wessche&thorn; by liste</L>
<L>&THORN;e on-sounde:</L>
<L>To wesschen ous cryst schedde his blod</L>
<L N="84">And water out of hys wonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="85">&para; Here-of spronge &thorn;e sacremens</L>
<L>Of holy chyrche digne;</L>
<L>And his to segge sacrement</L>
<L N="88">Of holy &thorn;ynge signe.</L>
<L>For gode,</L>
<L>Hou my&yogh;te fayrer signe be</L>
<L N="91">&THORN;ane of &thorn;e water and blode?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="92">&para; Man, &thorn;orwe &thorn;at blod &thorn;i soule his bou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Fram &thorn;e fendes powere;</L>
<L>And &thorn;orwe &thorn;at water iwessche &thorn;art</L>
<L N="95">Of &thorn;yne sennes here.</L>
<L>Nou loke,</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure Cristendom his tokene &thorn;rof<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;oure, ur</I> in a smaller handwriting, evidently a later addition to what looks more like <I>&yogh;a</I> than <I>&yogh;o</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="98">Of criste &thorn;at we toke.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="99">&para; For, &yogh;ef &thorn;ou uangest &thorn;ane cristendom,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="5"></L>
<L>And for &thorn;an bi-lef[s]t clene,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schelt be marked to &thorn;et stede<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>stede</I>, in a later hand on erasure.</NOTE></L>
<L N="102">To wichen heuen his ymene;</L>
<L>To so&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Wanne &thorn;e bisschop bisschope&thorn; &thorn;e,<MILESTONE N="151b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="105">Tokene of marke he set to &thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>too&thorn;e</I>, second <I>o</I> inserted by a later hand.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="106">&para; Ac cristendom hys sacrement</L>
<L>Of so grete powere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit &thorn;orwe wassche&thorn; &thorn;ane man</L>
<L N="109">Of senne alle manere;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>in alle manere, in</I> later addition, above the line.</NOTE></L>
<L>And glorie
<PB REF="00000023.tif" N="5"></L>
<L>Hit scheppe&thorn;, &yogh;ef man dey&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="112">And schilt fram purgatorie.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="113">&para; And&mdash;for we be&thorn; of nonn power</L>
<L>To weryen ous fram schame&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;er der no fend acombry ous,</L>
<L N="116">Crist is mid ous to-same(s);</L>
<L>And neade:</L>
<L>Tokene &thorn;er-of his goddes bodi</L>
<L N="119">At cherche ine forme of brede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="120">&para; And &yogh;et,&mdash;for man his so brotel</L>
<L>Ine his owene kende&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; he torni to senne a&yogh;en</L>
<L N="123">&THORN;orwe fondyng of &thorn;e feende,</L>
<L>By chaunce</L>
<L>&THORN;at he may come to stat a-&yogh;eyn</L>
<L N="126">&THORN;orwe bare repentaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="127">&para; Her-of we habbe&thorn; tokene gode,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="6"></L>
<L>Wanne we fange&thorn; penaunce</L>
<L>For sennes &thorn;at we habbe&thorn; idon,</L>
<L>To pynes allegaunce</L>
<L N="130">Ine fere;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. first <I>pynes, s</I> nearly gone.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;er we scholde hit vnder-go,</L>
<L N="133">Bote we pinede hit here.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Bote</I>, MS. <I>Sote</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="134">&para; &THORN;at man ne falle ine wanhope</L>
<L>A-last wi&thorn;-oute bote,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bote, te</I> on erasure.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al &thorn;at he he&thorn; iseneged her</L>
<L N="137">Wi&thorn; honden and wi&thorn; fo&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Wy&thorn; &thorn;oute,</L>
<L>Mou&thorn;e, nase, and earen, and wi&thorn; si&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>earen</I>, MS. <I>ey&yogh;en;</I> see note.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="152a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="140">Eliinge brenge&thorn; hit to nou&yogh;te.
<PB REF="00000024.tif" N="6"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="141">&para; &YOGH;et some he&thorn;e suche deuocioun,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hym &thorn;ing&thorn;e he his al ydel</L>
<L>For to libbe commun lif,</L>
<L N="144">Bote &yogh;ef he hedde a brydel;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Bote</I>, MS. <I>Dote</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wet &thorn;inge</L>
<L>Of harder stat god graunte&thorn;,</L>
<L N="147">Wel tokne &thorn;row&yogh; his ordini[n]ge.<NOTE PLACE="foot">See note.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="148">&para; &YOGH;et, &thorn;a&yogh; man mowe nau&yogh;t lecherie<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;a&yogh;</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;at</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Forbere to donne ine dede,</L>
<L>&YOGH;et ne schal he nau&yogh;t be for-lore,</L>
<L N="151">For god &yogh;ef&thorn;e hym to rede<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>hi</I> (underdotted) after <I>god</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Spousynge;</L>
<L>Tokene &thorn;rof his &thorn;e wedding</L>
<L N="154">At cherche, and biterew&thorn;ing.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>bitere wying</I>, which may mean <I>bitrewying</I>. For the parasitic <I>e</I>, cp. <I>scherewen</I> ( = <I>schrewen</I>), Sh. p. 143, l. 380; <I>cleregye</I>, Ay. 81; <I>chereche</I>, KS. 31.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="155">&para; Cristendom, and bisschoppying,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="7"></L>
<L>Penauns, and eke spousinge,</L>
<L>Godes body ine forme of bred,</L>
<L N="158">Ordre, and Aneliinge,</L>
<L>&THORN;es seuene</L>
<L>He&thorn; holicherche sacremens,</L>
<L N="161">&THORN;at be&thorn; tokenen of heuene.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="162">&para; God wescht, and marke&thorn;, and for&yogh;ef&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and for&yogh;ef&thorn;</I> begins next line in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ioyne&thorn; men an wyues,</L>
<L>And freuere&thorn; &thorn;orwe his body man,</L>
<L N="165">And grace sent, and lyues.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e, wanne?</L>
<L>Wanne we take&thorn; &thorn;e sacremens,</L>
<L N="168">&THORN;ar we se&thorn; hit &thorn;anne.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>se&thorn;</I> on erasure.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000025.tif" N="7"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="169">&para; &THORN;a&yogh; we ne mowe hyt nau&yogh;t ise,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;a&yogh;</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;at</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne for&thorn;e ine bodie iurede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>iurede</I>, MS. <I>inrede</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>We se&thorn;e hit wel ine oure fey,</L>
<L N="172">And frede&thorn; hit at nede</L>
<L>Wel e&yogh;a&thorn;e:</L>
<L>God &thorn;orwe miracles ke&thorn;e&thorn; hit<MILESTONE N="152b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="175">A lyue and eke a de&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="176">&para; And bote he &thorn;orwe hys sacremens</L>
<L>Ous &thorn;os bi-redde,</L>
<L>Ne scholde we of his grace wite</L>
<L N="179">Wanne we hit toke and hedde<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hedde</I>, MS. <I>hadde</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>To wisse;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore, he &thorn;at bi-lefe&thorn; hit nau&yogh;t</L>
<L N="182">Ri&yogh;t wyt ne&thorn; of blisse.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Ri&yogh;t wyt ne&thorn; he of none blisse, he</I> and <I>none</I> written by a later hand above the line, the former between <I>ne&thorn;</I> and <I>of</I>, the latter after <I>blisse</I>, with a mark before it, and a corresponding one before <I>blisse</I>, to indicate the place of insertion.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="183">&para; Al hit be&thorn; cherche sacremens<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>be&thorn; in cherche &thorn;ese sacremens, in</I> and <I>&thorn;ese</I> in a later hand above the line; <I>&thorn;ese</I> is written in the margin after <I>sacremens</I>, but marked for insertion before it.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="8"></L>
<L>&THORN;et tokene&thorn; holi &thorn;ynges,</L>
<L>As hali water, and haly bred,</L>
<L N="186">Li&yogh;t, and belryngynges<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>s</I> in <I>belryngynges</I> added by a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L>To leste;</L>
<L>And of alle o&thorn;er sacremens</L>
<L N="189">&THORN;es seuene be&thorn; &thorn;e greste.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>(1) [D]E baptismo.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>in margin</I>]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="190">CRistendom his &thorn;at sacrement</L>
<L>&THORN;at men her ferst fonge&thorn;;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>ous to</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hit opene&thorn; to ous &thorn;e heuene blisse,</L>
<L N="193">&THORN;at many man after longe&thorn;</L>
<L>Wel sore;
<PB REF="00000026.tif" N="8"></L>
<L>For who &thorn;at entre&thorn; &thorn;er</L>
<L N="196">He his sauff euere more.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="197">&para; Nou ferst ich wille telle &yogh;ou</L>
<L>Wet may be &thorn;e materie</L>
<L>Wer-inne cristning may be mad,</L>
<L N="200">&THORN;at bringe&thorn; ous so merie</L>
<L>To honoure:</L>
<L>Hi&yogh;t mo&yogh;t be do ine kende water,</L>
<L N="203">And non o&thorn;er licour[e].</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="204">&para; &THORN;er-fore ine wine me ne may,</L>
<L>Inne si&thorn;ere, ne inne pereye,</L>
<L>Ne ine &thorn;ing &thorn;at neuere water nes</L>
<L N="207">&THORN;or&yogh; cristning man reneye;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>may</I> in a later hand above the line, between <I>man</I> and <I>reneye</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne inne ale,</L>
<L>For, &thorn;ie hi&yogh;t were water ferst,<MILESTONE N="153a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="210">Of water ne&thorn; hit tale.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="211">&para; Ne mede, ne for&thorn;e no o&thorn;er licour<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="9"></L>
<L>&THORN;at chaunge&thorn; wateres kende,</L>
<L>Ne longe&thorn; nau&yogh;t to cristendom,</L>
<L N="214">&THORN;a&yogh;t some foles hit wende<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;a&yogh;t, originally <I>&thorn;at</I>, as it seems, &yogh; inserted by a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L>For wete;</L>
<L>For suich is kendeliche hot,</L>
<L N="217">&THORN;a&yogh;t &thorn;er no feer hit ne hete.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hete</I> (from <I>h&aelig;tan</I>), MS. <I>hente</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="218">&para; Ac water is kendeliche cheld,</L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; hit be warmd of fere;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;a&yogh;</I> corrected from <I>&thorn;at</I>.&mdash;<I>d</I> in <I>warmd</I> in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore me mey cristni &thorn;er-inne,</L>
<L N="221">In whaut time fal&thorn;e a &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Of yse;</L>
<L>So mey me nau&yogh;t in ewe ardaunt,</L>
<L N="224">&THORN;at ne&thorn; no wateris wyse.
<PB REF="00000027.tif" N="9"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="225">&para; Al-so me may inne sealte se</L>
<L>Cristny wel mitte beste,</L>
<L>And eke inne o&thorn;ere sealte watere,</L>
<L N="228">Bote me in to moche kes(ch)te</L>
<L>Of sealte;</L>
<L>For &yogh;ef &thorn;at water his kende lest,</L>
<L N="231">&THORN;at cristning stant te tealte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="232">&para; Ac &yogh;yf &thorn;er were ymengd licour</L>
<L>O&thorn;er wid kende wetere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wetere</I>, MS. <I>watere</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ich wo&yogh;t wel, &thorn;rinne to cristnye</L>
<L N="235">Hit nere nefur &thorn;e betere,</L>
<L>Ac wonde;</L>
<L>For bote &thorn;at water his kende haue,</L>
<L N="238">&THORN;at cristnynge may nau&yogh;t stonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="239">&para; In water ich wel &thorn;e cristny her,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="10"></L>
<L>As gode him self hyt di&yogh;te;</L>
<L>For mide to wessche nis no&thorn;ynge</L>
<L N="242">&THORN;at man come&thorn; to so li&yogh;te;</L>
<L>In londe</L>
<L>Nis non &thorn;at habben hit ne may:<MILESTONE N="153b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="245">&THORN;at habbe hit wile, founde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>founde</I> = <I>fonde</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="246">&para; &THORN;is be&thorn;e &thorn;e wordes of cristnyng</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;yse englissche costes:&mdash;</L>
<L>"Ich cristni &thorn;e ine &thorn;e uader name,</L>
<L N="249">And sone, and holy gostes;"</L>
<L>And more,</L>
<L>"Amen!" Wane hit his ised &thorn;er-toe,</L>
<L N="252">Conferme&thorn; &thorn;et to-fore.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;et</I> (<I>&thorn;er</I>) <I>to-fore, &thorn;er</I> added in the margin above <I>fore</I>, a caret being put between <I>&thorn;et</I> and <I>to</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="253">&para; &THORN;e wordes scholle be ised</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;e-oute wane and eche;
<PB REF="00000028.tif" N="10"></L>
<L>And onderstand, hi mo&yogh;e bi sed<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mo&yogh;e</I>, MS. <I>more</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="256">In alle manere speche</L>
<L>Ine lede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euerich man hi sigge mo&yogh;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mo&yogh;e</I>, MS. <I>more</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="259">And cristny for nede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="260">&para; Ac &yogh;if man scholde icristnid be</L>
<L>&THORN;at ne&thorn; none dea&thorn;es signe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e pope for te cristny hyne</L>
<L N="263">So nere nau&yogh;t te digne</L>
<L>&THORN;e leste;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore hi be&thorn; in cherche brou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="266">To cristny of &thorn;e preste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="267">&para; Ac he &thorn;at &yogh;if so large water<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he, h</I> in a later hand on erasure.&mdash;<I>&yogh;if</I>, read <I>&yogh;if&thorn;</I>? or <I>&yogh;ef</I>? cf. l. 270.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="11"></L>
<L>&THORN;e fend fram ous te reaue,</L>
<L>In nede for to cristny men</L>
<L N="270">&YOGH;ef alle men ileaue</L>
<L>At felle;</L>
<L>Olepi mot hym ine &thorn;e water,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Olepi (me) mot hym (depe) ine &thorn;e water, me</I> and <I>depe</I> added above the line; see note.</NOTE></L>
<L N="273">And eke &thorn;e wordes telle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="274">&para; And wanne hi cristne&thorn; ine &thorn;e foun&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;e prestes so &thorn;ries depe&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&THORN;e so prestes</I>, with marks of transposition. The <I>e</I> in <I>&thorn;e</I> seems to have been altered from original <I>i</I>, the stroke over it being still visible. The original reading may possibly have been <I>&thorn;ise prestes</I>.&mdash;<I>depe&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>duppe&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e honur of &thorn;e trinite,</L>
<L N="277">Ac gode &yogh;eme kepe&thorn;</L>
<L>&THORN;e ned</L>
<L>On time a clo&thorn;e &thorn;at water ikest,<MILESTONE N="154a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="280">Ac ope &thorn;e heuede te bede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">278-280. See note.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="41" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="281">&para; Ac water ikest an o&thorn;er leme<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>leme</I> (limb), MS. <I>lone</I> (or <I>loue</I>).</NOTE></L>
<L>Cristne&thorn; &thorn;e man alyue,
<PB REF="00000029.tif" N="11"></L>
<L>Ac hit his sikerest in &thorn;e heeued,</L>
<L N="284">&THORN;er be&thorn; &thorn;e wittes fyue.</L>
<L>Wel, bro&thorn;er,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>b</I> and &thorn; in <I>bro&thorn;er</I> on erasure, in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne non ne may icristned be</L>
<L N="287">Ar he his boren of moder.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he</I>, MS. &yogh;e.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="42" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="288">&para; &YOGH;et gret peryl hy vndergo&thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at cristne&thorn; twyes enne,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er to &yogh;eue asent &thorn;er-to,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>O&thorn;er</I>, MS. <I>Orer.&mdash;to &yogh;eue</I>, read <I>&yogh;eue&thorn;</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L N="291">O&thorn;er for loue of kenne</L>
<L>For-hede&thorn;</L>
<L>Wanne child ari&yogh;t cristnyng he&thorn;,</L>
<L N="294">And &thorn;at o&thorn;er nau&yogh;t for-bede&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="43" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="295">&para; Bote hi &thorn;is conne, hit his peril<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Bote</I>, MS. <I>Dote</I>.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="12"></L>
<L>To &thorn;ise medewyues;</L>
<L>For ofte children scheawi&thorn; quike,</L>
<L N="298">Ibore to schorte lyues,</L>
<L>And deye&thorn;:</L>
<L>Bote hi ari&yogh;t icristned be,</L>
<L N="301">Fram heuene euere hi weye&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="44" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="302">&para; Ac &yogh;if &thorn;at child icristned his,</L>
<L>Ac me fot at me hit wene&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>me</I> looks like <I>ine</I>, the tail of the &yogh; in <I>&yogh;if</I> of the preceding line stand|ing directly over the first stroke of the <I>m</I>. In the space between <I>fot</I> and <I>at</I> there is in the MS. a sign resembling a rider, with a small bar at the top of it (<GAP>), and over it something like an <GAP> or &yogh;, all half blotted.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ise habbe&thorn; forme &thorn;er-of</L>
<L N="305">A latin &thorn;at ham genie&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota</NOTE></L>
<L>To depe;</L>
<L>And ich schel seggen hit an englisch,</L>
<L N="308">Nou &thorn;er-of neme &yogh;e kepe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="45" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="309">&para; &THORN;e prest take&thorn; &thorn;at ilke child</L>
<L>In his honden by-thuixte,
<PB REF="00000030.tif" N="12"></L>
<L>And sei&thorn;: "ich ne cristni &thorn;ei nau&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota</NOTE></L>
<L N="312">&YOGH;ef &thorn;ou ert icristned;"</L>
<L>Eft sone:&mdash;</L>
<L>"Ac &yogh;yf &thorn;ou nart, ich cristni &thorn;e;"<NOTE PLACE="foot">Over <I>nart</I> there is another <I>nart</I> (for <I>na&yogh;t</I>?) written in a later hand with pale ink, and after it a caret in red ink.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="154b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="315">And de&thorn; &thorn;at his to donne.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>de&thorn;, e</I> erased after the &thorn;.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="46" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="316">&para; Ac &yogh;et &thorn;er be&thorn; cristnynges mo,</L>
<L>Ac no man ne may di&yogh;tti;</L>
<L>For hi be&thorn; godes grace self,</L>
<L N="319">Men of gode wil to ri&yogh;ti<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Men of gode (ine) wil to ri&yogh;ti, ine</I> written by a later hand in the margin, a little above <I>ri&yogh;ti</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And, wynne,</L>
<L>Wanne hi wolde icristned be,</L>
<L N="322">And mo&yogh;e mid none ginne.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mo&yogh;e</I>, MS. <I>more</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="47" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="323">&para; &THORN;at on his cleped cristning of blode,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="13"></L>
<L>Wanne suche blede&thorn; for criste;</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er of &thorn;e holy gost,</L>
<L N="326">&THORN;at mo&yogh;e mid none liste</L>
<L>Be icristned,</L>
<L>And deye&thorn; so: wanne hi be&thorn; deede,</L>
<L N="329">Ine heuene hi be&thorn; igistned.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="48" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="330">&para; &THORN;e children atte cherche dore</L>
<L>So be&thorn; yprimisined;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at hi bee&thorn;e eke atte fount</L>
<L N="333">Mid oylle and creyme alyned</L>
<L>Al faylle&thorn;;</L>
<L>Hi&yogh;t wor&thorn;e&thorn; cristnyng, and &thorn;at child<NOTE PLACE="foot">A later hand has added <I>worche&thorn;</I> in the margin of the MS.&mdash;<I>and &thorn;at child</I> begins the following line in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="336">&THORN;er-to hit auaille&thorn;.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000031.tif" N="13">
<HEAD>(2) [D]E confirmatione.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>in margin</I>]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG N="49" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="337">COnfermyng his a sacrement,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er &thorn;at we founge&thorn;;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>founge&thorn;</I>. The author probably wrote <I>fonge&thorn;</I> [: <I>stronge&thorn;</I>].</NOTE></L>
<L>And wanne a man hit onderuange&thorn;,</L>
<L N="340">Ine saule hit hine strange&thorn;,</L>
<L>Wel li&yogh;tte;</L>
<L>For wanne a man yma[r]ked his,</L>
<L N="343">&THORN;e stronger he his to fy&yogh;te.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>stronger, r</I> written over <I>o</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="50" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="344">&para; And be &thorn;ou siker &thorn;at mannes lyf</L>
<L>Is ri&yogh;t a kni&yogh;t-hod ine londe;</L>
<L>And so sey&thorn;e iob, &thorn;e holy man.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sey&thorn;e, y</I> above the line.</NOTE></L>
<L N="347">Now mote we &thorn;anne stonde<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mote</I>, MS. <I>wote</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>To fi&yogh;te :</L>
<L>&THORN;e feend, &thorn;at flesch, and eke &thorn;e wordle,<MILESTONE N="155a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="350">Ageins ous be&thorn; idi&yogh;te.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="51" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="351">&para; &THORN;e feend wi&thorn; prede acombre&thorn; ous,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="14"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wre&thorn;e, and wi&thorn; enuie;</L>
<L>&THORN;at fleisch wi&thorn; sleu&thorn;e and glotonie,</L>
<L N="354">And eke wi&thorn; lecherie,<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;oun-wyse;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;o&umacr; wysc</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e wordle, wi&thorn; here fal&yogh;se scheawinge,</L>
<L N="357">Schent ous wi&thorn; coueytise.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="52" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="358">&para; Ac he &thorn;at ine saule is strang,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>is</I> above the line.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he wi&thorn;-stent hi alle,</L>
<L>And hardeliche hert o&thorn;re men,</L>
<L N="361">A-doun &thorn;at hi ne falle,</L>
<L>Ac stonde,
<PB REF="00000032.tif" N="14"></L>
<L>So his ihert &thorn;or&yogh; conferming,<NOTE PLACE="foot">In the margin, after <I>conferming</I>, is written in a later hand <I>of gode</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="364">&THORN;at for de&thorn;e nele nau&yogh;t wonde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&THORN;at for</I> on erasure. Over the first <I>e</I> in <I>de&thorn;e</I> there is a half-blotted letter resembling <I>a</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="53" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="365">&para; Nou ich mot of &thorn;is sacrement</L>
<L>&YOGH;ou telle &thorn;e materie,</L>
<L>&THORN;at make&thorn; man so hardiliche</L>
<L N="368">To stonde, and so merie<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I>, MS. <I>an;</I> but the stroke may as well be disregarded.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ine goste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne may nau&yogh;t yweid be</L>
<L N="371">Wi&thorn; blanding ne wi&thorn; boste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="54" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="372">&para; Hit his &thorn;e oyle and baume ymeng</L>
<L>Iblessed, and wi(le), lestne:<NOTE PLACE="foot">In the MS. there is a flourish attached to the final <I>d</I> of <I>and</I>, which seems to permit the reading <I>and &yogh;e wile lestne</I>. But the <I>e</I> in <I>wile</I> is apparently a later addition; see note.</NOTE></L>
<L>For oyle smere&thorn; &thorn;ane champion,</L>
<L N="375">&THORN;at me [ne] schel him festne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">The MS. has&mdash;<I>&THORN;at me</I> (<I>ne</I>) <I>schel</I> (<I>on</I>) <I>him</I> (<I>euel</I>) <I>festne</I>, the words in parentheses being written in a later hand above the line.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne presse;</L>
<L>And baume his riche and tokened looz<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>looz</I>, MS. <I>loe&yogh;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="378">Of &thorn;are holy prowesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="55" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="379">&para; A prince longe&thorn; for te do<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="15"></L>
<L>&THORN;e gode kni&yogh;tes dobbynge;</L>
<L>And so a prince of godes ost</L>
<L N="382">Schel do &thorn;e confermynge,</L>
<L>Nonn lo&yogh;er;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Non;</I> the writing <I>nonn</I> occurs p. 5, l. 113.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore hit mot a bisschopp be,<MILESTONE N="155b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="385">Nis non &thorn;er-to y o&yogh;er.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>y o&yogh;er</I>, see note.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="56" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="386">&para; &THORN;at me wasche men ouer &thorn;e fant</L>
<L>After confirmement,
<PB REF="00000033.tif" N="15"></L>
<L>Nis nau&yogh;t do bote for &thorn;at honour</L>
<L N="389">Of &thorn;ilke sacrement</L>
<L>Soe here;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore me wescht and kerf&thorn; &thorn;ane clout,</L>
<L N="392">And berne&thorn; him in &thorn;e fere.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fere</I>, MS. <I>fure</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="57" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="393">&para; &THORN;e bisschop &thorn;ese wordes se&thorn;&mdash;</L>
<L>And be&thorn; wordes of sel&thorn;e:&mdash;</L>
<L>"Ich signi &thorn;e wi&thorn; signe of croys,</L>
<L N="396">And wi&thorn; &thorn;e creme of hel[&thorn;]e</L>
<L>Confermi."</L>
<L>Ine &thorn;e foreheued &thorn;e crouche a set,</L>
<L N="399">Fel&thorn;e of fendes to bermi.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bermi, b</I> on erasure; see note.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="58" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="400">&para; Ine &thorn;e foreheued he crouche&thorn; hine,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>crouche&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>crouthe&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at him ne schamie boute<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>hine be aschamed, hine</I> altered from <I>him; be</I> in a later hand on erasure, as well as the <I>a</I> and final <I>d</I> in <I>aschamed</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>(Bote) for to bi-knowe cristes name<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omission of <I>Bote</I> suggested by Varnhagen; see note.</NOTE></L>
<L N="403">Wi&thorn;-oute alle manere doute;</L>
<L>And binne<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>binne</I>, MS. <I>wi&thorn; ginne</I>, in a later hand; see note.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;orwe creymie anoynt strange he bi-com&thorn;e</L>
<L N="406">His sauuement to winne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="59" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="407">&para; Ac hou his hit, &thorn;er be&thorn;e so fele<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="16"></L>
<L>Confermed of mankenne,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er so feawe stonde&thorn; styf<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>styf, y</I> on erasure.</NOTE></L>
<L N="410">To fytte a&yogh;enis senne</L>
<L>Maligne?</L>
<L>For hi ne fonge&thorn; nou&yogh;t &thorn;at &thorn;ing,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ing, e</I> seems erased at the end.</NOTE></L>
<L N="413">Bote &thorn;e bare signe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="60" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="414">&para; &THORN;e signe his of &thorn;is sacrement</L>
<L>Mid creyme &thorn;e markynge;
<PB REF="00000034.tif" N="16"></L>
<L>Ac &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;er bi-tokned his,</L>
<L N="417">Streng&thorn;e his &thorn;at god schel bringg</L>
<L>Amonge;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-oute god fey and god wil<MILESTONE N="156a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="420">Mey non &thorn;is &thorn;ing foenge.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. ounder <I>foenge, o&umacr;der</I> written in a later hand above the line. The original reading may possibly have been <I>auonge</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="61" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="421">&para; Ac nou &thorn;at wil &thorn;at is to gode</L>
<L>His al iset bi-hinde;</L>
<L>And &thorn;i bileaue of ihesu crist</L>
<L N="424">His nou al weuerinde:</L>
<L>Vndigne</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore ne habbe&thorn; nau&yogh;t &thorn;at &thorn;ing,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nau&yogh;t</I> begins next line in MS. The adopted reading proposed by K&ouml;lbing.</NOTE></L>
<L N="427">Bote &thorn;e bare signe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="62" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="428">&para; Ac &thorn;are children take &thorn;at &thorn;ing<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;are, read <I>&thorn;a&yogh;</I>, or <I>&thorn;a&yogh; &thorn;at</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L>In hare childhod so p(o)ure,</L>
<L>Hit lese&thorn; wanne hi come&thorn; to wit<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Hit</I>, MS. <I>hy Hit, hy</I> written in the margin by a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L N="431">&THORN;our&yogh; hare misauenture</L>
<L>Of senne:</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;e foend fonde&thorn; hy so,</L>
<L N="434">And he ne spare&thorn; nenne.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nenne</I>, MS. <I>nanne</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="63" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="435">&para; &THORN;at de&thorn; &thorn;at hi nastonde&thorn; nou&yogh;t,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="17"></L>
<L>Ac ech o&thorn;ren aschrenche&thorn;;</L>
<L>Ac &yogh;et, hy mowe &yogh;et stonde bet,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;et</I>, MS. <I>&yogh;if;</I> see note. For <I>Ac</I> we ought probably to write <I>And</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="438">Wanne hi ham bet bi-&thorn;enche&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bi-&thorn;enche&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>bi &thorn;enke&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>To leue,</L>
<L>And do ham to deuocioun,</L>
<L N="441">&YOGH;ef god ham streng&thorn;e &yogh;iue.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;eue</I>, MS. <I>&yogh;iue</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="64" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="442">&para; And &thorn;anne gode, &thorn;at his so god,</L>
<L>Anon hi stronge make&thorn;,
<PB REF="00000035.tif" N="17"></L>
<L>As hi habbe&thorn; deuocioun,</L>
<L N="445">And hie god fey take&thorn;,</L>
<L>Reuersed;</L>
<L>And al his &thorn;or&yogh; &thorn;at sacrement,</L>
<L N="448">&THORN;ei&yogh;e hit ne be nau&yogh;t rehersed.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="65" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="449">&para; For wanne me take&thorn; &thorn;is sacrement,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>me</I>, MS. <I>we</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>His soule prente take&thorn;;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at hi nefermo for-lest,</L>
<L N="452">Nau&yogh;t hi &thorn;at god for-sake&thorn;,</L>
<L>Ac healde&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>ac hine healde&thorn;, hine</I> in a later hand above the line. <I>ac</I> seems originally to have been <I>&thorn;at</I>, the initial &thorn; and part of the cross-stroke of the final <I>t</I> having been erased. See note.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ine stat &thorn;at sacrement ine man,<MILESTONE N="156b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="455">Wanne he ine gode byalde&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he</I>, MS. <I>&yogh;e</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="66" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="456">&para; And as &thorn;ys ylke sacrement</L>
<L>He&thorn; &thorn;yng and toke hijs signe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>He&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>Her.&mdash;toke</I>, read <I>eke</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L>So habbe&thorn; &thorn;e o&thorn;ere sacremens</L>
<L N="459">Syx&yogh;e &thorn;at be&thorn;e so digne:</L>
<L>Crystnynge</L>
<L>Her signe, droppinge in &thorn;e water,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Her</I>, read <I>He&thorn;</I>?&mdash;<I>droppinge</I>, read <I>depinge</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L N="462">And &thorn;yng hijs for-&yogh;euynge.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for-&yogh;euynge</I>, MS. <I>for-&yogh;emynge</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="67" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="463">&para; &THORN;ys ylke sygne, and eke &thorn;ys &thorn;yng,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="18"></L>
<L>In oure child-hode we hyt toke;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hyt</I>, MS. <I>&yogh;yt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac after-ward we lore &thorn;at &thorn;yng,</L>
<L N="466">&THORN;o we to senne toke</L>
<L>By wylle.</L>
<L>Amend[e] we, &thorn;e prente lef&thorn;</L>
<L N="469">Ine oure saule wel stille.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="68" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="470">&para; Hym selue no man hebbe schel</L>
<L>To &thorn;e bischoppynge;
<PB REF="00000036.tif" N="18"></L>
<L>Ine tokne of feblesce of hijs goste<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>feblesce</I>, MS. <I>febleste</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="473">An o&thorn;er schel him brynge</L>
<L>And lefte,</L>
<L>Ase he ne mi&yogh;te nau&yogh;t hym self</L>
<L N="476">To confermynge crefte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="69" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="477">&para; Ac her ich segge aperteliche,</L>
<L>&THORN;ys men and eke &thorn;is wyues,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hi ne hebbe hare o&yogh;e child</L>
<L N="480">By hare quicke lyues,</L>
<L>And rede;</L>
<L>For &yogh;ef hy do&thorn;e, man and hys wyf</L>
<L N="483">&THORN;er drawe&thorn; god-sibrede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="70" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="484">&para; Of seue sacremens &thorn;re</L>
<L>Prente ine herte make&thorn;;</L>
<L>&THORN;at be&thorn; cristnyng, and confermyng,</L>
<L N="487">And ordre &thorn;at men take&thorn;</L>
<L>Wel bli&thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;at hijs, for no man hy ne take&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;at (hy) hijs (ne take) for no man hy ne take&thorn;, hy ne take&thorn;</I> having been crossed out, and the words in parentheses added by a later hand over the line.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="157a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="490">Bote onelepy sy&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>(3) [D]E sacramento Altaris.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>in margin</I>]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG N="71" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="491">NOu hy&yogh;t by-ual&thorn; to telle &yogh;ou&mdash;<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="19"></L>
<L>And so ich mo&yogh;t wel nede&mdash;</L>
<L>Of godes flesch and eke hys blode</L>
<L N="494">At cherche ine forme of brede</L>
<L>And wyne;</L>
<L>&THORN;at freuere&thorn; ous in oure exil,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at, t</I> above the line.</NOTE></L>
<L N="497">And ly&thorn;e&thorn; oure pyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="72" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="498">&para; H&yogh;e bli&thorn;e my&yogh;ten hy be</L>
<L>&THORN;at folwede cryst in londe,
<PB REF="00000037.tif" N="19"></L>
<L>&THORN;at my&yogh;te hyne eche day yse,</L>
<L N="501">Hijs swete loue to fonde</L>
<L>Ine ke&thorn;&thorn;e!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ke&thorn;&thorn;e</I> altered from <I>ke&thorn;e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>So mowe we be, for ous ne&thorn; he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ne&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>ner</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="504">Hy-faylled neuer se&thorn;&thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Hy-faylled = yfaylled</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="73" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="505">&para; For &thorn;o hijs tyme was ycome</L>
<L>No leng to dwelle here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wete brede and honde he toke,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and honde = an honde</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="508">&THORN;er he set atte sopere,</L>
<L>And seyde:</L>
<L>"Take&thorn; and ete&thorn;, &thorn;ys hijs my body";</L>
<L N="511">Of so&thorn;e he ham aueyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="74" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="512">&para; For-wy hy&yogh;t moste nedes be</L>
<L>Al so&thorn;e &thorn;at he sede;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>se&thorn;e</I>, with indistinct <I>e</I>; read <I>so&thorn;e</I>? or <I>se&thorn;e &thorn;at</I> = since?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;yng his ase he sei&thorn;</L>
<L N="515">&THORN;y resoun wole &thorn;e rede.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;y</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;ys</I>, the <I>s</I> being written over the line in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lo dede:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Lo</I>, distinctly so in MS. (Wr. <I>To</I>).</NOTE></L>
<L>He seyde to al &thorn;e worlde, "be,"</L>
<L N="518">And al was ase he sede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="75" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="519">&para; Nammore maystrye nys hi&yogh;t to hym<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="20"></L>
<L>To be ine bredes lyche,</L>
<L>&THORN;ane hym was ine &thorn;e liche of man,</L>
<L N="522">To ke&thorn;en ous hijs ryche;</L>
<L>&THORN;et make&thorn;</L>
<L>&THORN;at hy be&thorn; alle mis-by-leued</L>
<L N="525">&THORN;at o&thorn;er &thorn;rof for-sake&thorn;.<MILESTONE N="157b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="76" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="526">&para; &THORN;e fend hym-self him maky mey</L>
<L>Wel dyuerse liknynges,
<PB REF="00000038.tif" N="20"></L>
<L>Of best, of men, and of wymmen,<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota</NOTE></L>
<L N="529">And mani o&thorn;er &thorn;ynges,</L>
<L>To nusy:</L>
<L>Wel bet may god to oure prou</L>
<L N="532">Dyuerse formes vsy.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="77" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="533">&para; &THORN;o &thorn;at &thorn;e bred ytourned was</L>
<L>In to hys body selue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>selue</I>, MS. <I>sylue</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>He toke &thorn;e coppe wi&thorn; &thorn;e wyne and water,<NOTE PLACE="foot">K&ouml;lbing omits <I>&thorn;e</I> before <I>wyne</I>. I rather suspect that the words <I>and water</I> are a later addition. See note.</NOTE></L>
<L N="536">And seide eft to &thorn;e twelue<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota</NOTE></L>
<L>Yuere:</L>
<L>"Take&thorn; and drynke&thorn; euerech on</L>
<L N="539">Of &thorn;is chalice here.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="78" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="540">&para; &THORN;ys hys &thorn;e chalis of my blode,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e chalis</I> (K&ouml;lbing), MS. <I>my chalis</I>. K&ouml;lbing also proposes to read <I>in</I> (for <I>of</I>) <I>my blode</I>, with reference to Luke xxii. 20.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of testament newe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>newe</I>, MS. <I>nywe</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at schal be schad for manye men";</L>
<L N="543">And&mdash;ase we sey&yogh;e&thorn; gode and trewe<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota</NOTE></L>
<L>And kende&mdash;</L>
<L>"And do&thorn; &yogh;e &thorn;os, wanne &yogh;e hyt do&thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot">543-545. See note.</NOTE></L>
<L N="546">Do&thorn; hyt in mine mende."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mine</I>, MS. <I>&yogh;oure. &yogh;our</I> is written in a later hand on erasure, only the final <I>e</I> is original. Another <I>youre</I>, written with pencil, is faintly discernible in the margin to the left.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="79" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="547">&para; &THORN;o &thorn;at he sede: "do&thorn; &yogh;e &thorn;os,"<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="21"></L>
<L>&THORN;e hey&yogh;e kyng of heuene,</L>
<L>He &yogh;af ham power to don hyt,</L>
<L N="550">And for&thorn; power to &yogh;euene<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for&thorn;</I>, &thorn; in a different hand.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel wer&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; he ne toke iudas out,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;a&yogh;</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;at</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="553">&THORN;e worste man on er&thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000039.tif" N="21"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="80" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="554">&para; And nou &thorn;at power hys y&yogh;iue<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nou</I> and <I>hys</I> on erasure, the former very indistinct.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fram bysschoppe to preste,</L>
<L>And so schel al so longe be,</L>
<L N="557">Ase cristyndom schel leste;</L>
<L>Ymete,<MILESTONE N="158a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e crist four ous an or&thorn;e come,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Se&thorn;&thorn;e</I>, &thorn;&thorn; on erasure.</NOTE></L>
<L N="560">He nolde ous nau&yogh;t for-lete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="81" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="561">&para; &THORN;a&yogh; he were inne hys manhode<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;a&yogh;</I>, &yogh; altered from some other letter, probably <I>t</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Amanges ous to flotie,</L>
<L>&YOGH;et nere he nau&yogh;t &thorn;anne ous so ne&yogh;,</L>
<L N="564">Ase nou we mowe hym notye</L>
<L>In vode:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vode</I>, MS. <I>gode, g</I> altered from original <I>v</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>We honorie&thorn; hyne al iholliche</L>
<L N="567">Ine flesch and eke ine blode.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>blode</I>, a letter (probably <I>u</I>) erased between <I>o</I> and <I>d</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="82" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="568">&para; Wat may amounti &thorn;at he wyle</L>
<L>So by-come oure fode?</L>
<L>Chaunge&thorn; he au&yogh;t, ase o&thorn;ere mete,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>au&yogh;t</I>, MS. <I>nau&yogh;t, n</I> over <I>a</I> in a later hand.&mdash;<I>mete</I>, MS. <I>mote</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="571">In-to oure flesch and blode</L>
<L>By kende?</L>
<L>Nay, ac he chaunge&thorn; ous in hym,</L>
<L N="574">To maky ous gode and hende.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="83" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="575">&para; And ase gode &thorn;er his hole mete,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="22"><NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>hole men mete, men</I> written above the line in a later hand. The original reading of the MS. seems to have been <I>holen</I>, and in l. 576 <I>siken;</I> the final <I>n</I> is erased, but some faint traces of it are still discernible in <I>sike</I>. For a possible emendation of the corrupt passage see note.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sike hyt by-swike&thorn;,</L>
<L>So his &thorn;e mete dampnacion</L>
<L N="578">To hem &thorn;at senne like&thorn;</L>
<L>To holde;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>holde</I> [: <I>solde</I>] = Kt. <I>healde</I> [: <I>sealde</I>].</NOTE></L>
<L>So he hyt tok and his lore,</L>
<L N="581">Iudas, &thorn;at ihesus solde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>holde</I> [: <I>solde</I>] = Kt. <I>healde</I> [: <I>sealde</I>].</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000040.tif" N="22"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="84" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="582">&para; &THORN;er-fore ich segge a godes half</L>
<L>To alle cristyne folke</L>
<L>&THORN;at, wanne hy scholle yhouseled be,</L>
<L N="585">&THORN;at hy ne be a-bolke</L>
<L>In prede;</L>
<L>Let ounde and wre&thorn;e and coueytyng,</L>
<L N="588">Sleu&thorn;e and lestes on-lede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="85" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="589">&para; Nys none of wymman beter ibore</L>
<L>To seint Iohan &thorn;e baptyste;</L>
<L>And &yogh;et he quakede wel ar&yogh;</L>
<L N="592">&THORN;o he touchede crist</L>
<L>Ine &thorn;e flomme:</L>
<L>&THORN;anne au&yogh;te we wel ary&yogh;t to be<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>au&yogh;te</I>, &yogh; above the line.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="158b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="595">To fange hym on-tromme.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="86" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="596">&para; &THORN;er-fore, &yogh;ef &thorn;at &yogh;e frede&thorn; &yogh;ou</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e ne be nau&yogh;t digne<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;e</I>, MS. <I>he.&mdash;d</I> in <I>digne</I> on erasure, apparently altered from <I>s</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For te be housled wy&thorn; &thorn;ys body</L>
<L N="599">Ine &thorn;issre holy signe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;issre</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;is&thorn;re</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wy&thorn;-drawe&thorn;;</L>
<L>For, wo &thorn;at hy&yogh;t take&thorn; ondygneliche,</L>
<L N="602">Hys iugement he gna&yogh;e&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="87" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="603">&para; May somman segge:&mdash;hou schal me so<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="23"></L>
<L>Fram &thorn;er houslyng dwelle?</L>
<L>Wanne god self aperteliche</L>
<L N="606">Sei&thorn; ous in &thorn;e gospelle&mdash;</L>
<L>Wel mende:&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Wel to mende, to</I> above the line in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Who &thorn;at ete&thorn; my flesch and drynke&thorn; my blod</L>
<L N="609">He&thorn; lyf wi&thorn;-oute ende."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="88" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="610">&para; &THORN;a&yogh; &thorn;ou [ne] take hy&yogh;t wy&thorn; &thorn;e mou&thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;a&yogh;</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;at</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne myd te&thorn; &thorn;er-on ne werche,
<PB REF="00000041.tif" N="23"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou takest hyt, man, &yogh;ef &thorn;at &thorn;ou art</L>
<L N="613">A lyme of holy cherche,</L>
<L>To blysse,</L>
<L>Wanne eny prest his messe synge&thorn; :</L>
<L N="616">Ilief hyt myd ywysse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="89" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="617">&para; For on hys godes flesch to nemme</L>
<L>Ase mou&thorn;e &thorn;e mete take&thorn;,</L>
<L>An-o&thorn;er ase &thorn;e mete y&yogh;ete<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota</NOTE></L>
<L N="620">In-to &thorn;e membres take&thorn;;</L>
<L>Ac here,</L>
<L>Crist hys &thorn;at heued, &thorn;e prest &thorn;e mou&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="623">&THORN;e lymes &thorn;at folke i-vere.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>i-vere, v</I> in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="90" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="624">&para; And ase &thorn;e bred to-gadere com&thorn;e</L>
<L>Of menye greynys to bake,</L>
<L>And ase &thorn;e wyne to-gadere flou&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota</NOTE></L>
<L N="627">Of manye grapes ytake,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>grapes</I>, MS. <I>greyns</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ilyke,</L>
<L>Cryst and hijs membrys, men,<MILESTONE N="159a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="630">O body be&thorn;e ine mystyke.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="91" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="631">&para; Wet hys mystyke ne mey non wete<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wete</I> on erasure. After <I>n&omacr;</I> there is a half-blotted letter resembling <I>b</I>.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="24"></L>
<L>Be no &thorn;ynge a-founde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>afounde</I> = <I>afonde</I>, OE. <I>&amacr;fondian</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bote wanne &thorn;er hys o &thorn;yng yked,</L>
<L N="634">An o&thorn;er to onder-stonde</L>
<L>&THORN;er-inne;</L>
<L>Hy &thorn;at arede&thorn; &thorn;yse redeles</L>
<L N="637">Werche&thorn; by &thorn;ilke gynne.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ilke</I> altered from <I>&thorn;uke</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="92" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="638">&para; So wane &thorn;at body hym hys ked</L>
<L>Of swete ihesu cryst[e],</L>
<L>Me may wel onder-stonde &thorn;er</L>
<L N="641">By &thorn;ulke selue lyste</L>
<L>An o&thorn;er :
<PB REF="00000042.tif" N="24"></L>
<L>Cryst and eke alle holy men</L>
<L N="644">O body, my leue bro&thorn;er.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>be&thorn; O body, be&thorn;</I> written in the margin in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="93" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="645">&para; &THORN;er-fore god he&thorn; &thorn;is sacrement<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>god</I>, MS. <I>guod, u</I> over <I>o.&mdash;he&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>be&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ymad of suiche &thorn;ynges</L>
<L>&THORN;at my&yogh;te of manye mak on,</L>
<L N="648">As cryst and hys derlynges</L>
<L>Imonge;</L>
<L>&THORN;enne scholde hy at one be</L>
<L N="651">In loue &thorn;at scholde hyt fonge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="94" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="652">&para; Nou onderstand : &thorn;e signe her,</L>
<L>Fourme hys of wyne and brede;</L>
<L>Doble hys &thorn;at &thorn;yng, ry&yogh;t cristes body,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Doble</I> MS. (Wr. <I>Noble</I>).</NOTE></L>
<L N="655">And body of quike and dede.</L>
<L>Ac bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L>&YOGH;et ry&yogh;te body &thorn;a&yogh; hyt be &thorn;yng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Read&mdash;<I>&thorn;et &thorn;yng, ry&yogh;t body &thorn;a&yogh; hyt be</I>? See note.</NOTE></L>
<L N="658">Hy&yogh;t hys signe of &thorn;at o&thorn;er.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="95" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="659">&para; Vor ase &thorn;e ry&yogh;te bodyes lemes<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="25"></L>
<L>Habbe&thorn; dyuerse wyke,</L>
<L>So habbe&thorn; ry&yogh;t membrys eke</L>
<L N="662">Of &thorn;e body ine mystyke :</L>
<L>&THORN;at welde&thorn;</L>
<L>Hys honden, men be&thorn; &thorn;at wel do&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Colon after <I>honden</I> in MS.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="159b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="665">&THORN;e fet, &thorn;at wel op-helde&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="96" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="666">&para; Alle take&thorn; &thorn;at ry&yogh;t body</L>
<L>&THORN;yse men at hare houslyng,</L>
<L>Ac some to prou, and some to lere,</L>
<L N="669">Ine wyl of sene&yogh;ynge</L>
<L>To derye;</L>
<L>Ac one gode ary&yogh;t hyt nome&thorn;,</L>
<L N="672">&THORN;at body ine hys mysterye.
<PB REF="00000043.tif" N="25"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="97" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="673">&para; Ac &thorn;a&yogh; we be tokned &thorn;er</L>
<L>Ine oure sauueoure,</L>
<L>Ne lef &thorn;ou nau&yogh;t &thorn;e[t] we be &thorn;er,</L>
<L N="676">Ne for&thorn;e nau&yogh;t of oure</L>
<L>&THORN;at were;</L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; &thorn;er be tokned &thorn;ynges two,</L>
<L N="679">&THORN;er nys bote o &thorn;yng &thorn;ere;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="98" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="680">&para; And &thorn;at hys swete ihesu cryst</L>
<L>Ine flesche and eke ine bloude,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;olede pyne and passyoun,</L>
<L N="683">And dia&thorn; opone &thorn;e roude,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>opone</I>, MS. <I>opene</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel soure;</L>
<L>Ne lef non o&thorn;er, crysteman,</L>
<L N="686">For safour ne coloure.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="99" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="687">&para; For &thorn;at colour, ne &thorn;at sauour,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="26"></L>
<L>Ne be&thorn; nau&yogh;t &thorn;er inne cryste,</L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; he &thorn;er-inne schewe hym</L>
<L N="690">By hys my&yogh;te-folle lyste,</L>
<L>So cou&thorn;e;</L>
<L>Ne my&yogh;te elles bet be se&yogh;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>my&yogh;te = my&yogh;te he</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="693">Ne beter yured inne mou&thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>yured</I>. Over the <I>u</I> there is in the MS. a faint sign, which might be read as &yogh;.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="100" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="694">&para; For &yogh;ef he schewed hym in flesch,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;ef, f</I> in a later hand on erasure.</NOTE></L>
<L>O&thorn;er ine blody &thorn;ynge,</L>
<L>Hydous hy&yogh;t were to &thorn;e sy&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="697">And to &thorn;e tast wlatynge<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>tast</I>, MS. <I>cast</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And pyne</L>
<L>&THORN;anne hys hyt betere in fourme of brede,<MILESTONE N="160a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="700">And eke in forme of wyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="101" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="701">&para; For bred strenge&thorn; &thorn;e herte of man,</L>
<L>And wyn hys herte glede&thorn;;
<PB REF="00000044.tif" N="26"></L>
<L>And streng&thorn;e longe&thorn; &thorn;e body,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>longe&thorn; &thorn;e body</I>, read <I>longe&thorn; to &thorn;. b</I>.?</NOTE></L>
<L N="704">And blice &thorn;e saule vede&thorn;:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vede&thorn;</I> or <I>sede&thorn;</I>, with a round <I>s</I>, is the reading of the MS., certainly not <I>fede&thorn;</I> as printed by Wright.</NOTE></L>
<L>And nede</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore hys double sacrement,</L>
<L N="707">Of wyne, and eke of brede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="102" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="708">&para; For he ybout he&thorn; oure body,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ybout, b</I> altered from some other letter; after it a faint stroke, which cannot, however, be read as <I>r</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>In-to os he let hys sinke;</L>
<L>And uor &thorn;e saule ine &thorn;e blod,</L>
<L N="711">Hys blod he let os drynke.</L>
<L>Nou woste<NOTE PLACE="foot">The final <I>e</I>'s in <I>woste</I> and <I>goste</I> very indistinct.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wy &thorn;er hys double sacrement:</L>
<L N="714">For note of body and goste.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The final <I>e</I>'s in <I>woste</I> and <I>goste</I> very indistinct.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="103" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="715">&para; Ac wen nau&yogh;t &thorn;at cryst be to-schift,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="27"></L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; he schewe&thorn; ine bo&thorn;e;</L>
<L>To wene hys body wy&thorn;-oute blod,</L>
<L N="718">By &thorn;a weye ne go&thorn;e</L>
<L>To &thorn;ryfte;</L>
<L>For &thorn;er he hys, he hys al yhol,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A dot is put in MS. after the first <I>hys</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="721">Ne mey me hym to-schifte.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>me</I>, MS. <I>ine</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="104" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="722">&para; &THORN;e&yogh; &thorn;er te-breke a&yogh;t ine &thorn;e mou&thorn;,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er ine &thorn;yne honden,</L>
<L>Hyt nas nau&yogh;t he &thorn;at hys to-broke;</L>
<L N="725">Ensample &thorn;ou my&yogh;t fonden:</L>
<L>To-slyfte</L>
<L>A[l &thorn;y] myrour &thorn;ou my&yogh;t fol wel,<NOTE PLACE="foot">After <I>A</I> three letters erased, but traces of them are still visible; the first letter was probably <I>l</I>, the last certainly <I>y</I>. By the side of <I>A</I>, in the margin of the line, is written <I>in</I>, and in the margin of the following line <I>&thorn;i selue se</I>, all in a later hand and in smaller characters. See note.</NOTE></L>
<L N="728">Bote nau&yogh;t &thorn;e ymage schifte.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>schifte</I>, MS. <I>schefte</I>.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000045.tif" N="27"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="105" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="729">&para; By &thorn;yse ensample &thorn;ou my&yogh;t yse</L>
<L>He hys ine ech autere<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>echautere</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Y-hol; &thorn;e prest hys messe synge&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">The MS. has a colon after <I>Y-hol</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="732">&THORN;e&yogh; he ne be nau&yogh;t yhere,</L>
<L>Ac wykke,</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;er be&thorn; foles suiche fele,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>suiche, u</I> altered to <I>w</I> in a later hand.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="160b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="735">Ysawe al to &thorn;ykke.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="106" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="736">&para; Ac &thorn;a&yogh; &thorn;e prest hys messe do</L>
<L>Inne dedleche senne corse,</L>
<L>&THORN;et sacrement, man, be &thorn;ou syker,</L>
<L N="739">For hym nys na &thorn;e worse;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>na &thorn;e</I>, MS. <I>nase</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For loke,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sacrement nys na &thorn;e wors,</L>
<L N="742">&THORN;a&yogh; &thorn;at Iudas hyt toke.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="107" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="743">&para; Ac &thorn;a&yogh; hyt be neuer &thorn;e wors,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="28"></L>
<L>&THORN;at sacrement an honde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bone &thorn;at swych prest &thorn;er by&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>by&yogh;t</I> = <I>byt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="746">No stel ne schel hym stonde,</L>
<L>Ac derye;</L>
<L>For he despyse&thorn; ihesu cryst,</L>
<L N="749">Wanne he hym scholde herye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="108" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="750">&para; Ac &yogh;yf &thorn;ou wylt tak hyt to prou<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>tak hyt</I> for <I>take hyt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;e and &thorn;yne freende,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t repentaunt and ry&yogh;t deuout</L>
<L N="753">Take hys dea&thorn; in &thorn;y meende;</L>
<L>Naut ly&yogh;t[e]:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ly&yogh;t</I>[<I>e</I>] = <I>lyte</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e more &thorn;ou &thorn;enkest so on hys dea&thorn;,</L>
<L N="756">&THORN;e more hys &thorn;y meryte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="109" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="757">&para; Manne, wanne &thorn;yt takest, ase o&thorn;er mete<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;yt</I> = <I>&thorn;e</I> (for <I>&thorn;ou</I>) <I>hyt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>In-to &thorn;y wombe hy&yogh;t sedly&thorn;;
<PB REF="00000046.tif" N="28"></L>
<L>Ac ne defi&thorn; nau&yogh;t, ase &thorn;y mete</L>
<L N="760">Wy&thorn; &thorn;yne flesch medly&thorn;,</L>
<L>Ac keuere&thorn;</L>
<L>Al o&thorn;er wyse, and so &thorn;y body</L>
<L N="763">And &thorn;y saule hy&yogh;t freuere&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="110" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="764">&para; Nabyd hy&yogh;t nau&yogh;t, ase o&thorn;er mete,</L>
<L>Hys tyme of defyynge,</L>
<L>And ry&yogh;t anon hy&yogh;t freuere&thorn;</L>
<L N="767">In &thorn;are oundervanginge;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ounderv. or onnderv., but the <I>n</I>-stroke seems to be erased.</NOTE></L>
<L>Destresse</L>
<L>Of syke men, &thorn;a&yogh; hy hyt keste op,<MILESTONE N="161a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="770">Ne help&thorn; hyt nau&yogh;t &thorn;e lesse.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lesse</I>, MS. <I>lasse</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="111" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="771">&para; For yf &thorn;e syke man hys gode<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="29"></L>
<L>In &thorn;e leue of holy cherche,</L>
<L>&THORN;e&yogh; he hy&yogh;t cast op, hyt bylef&thorn;</L>
<L N="774">Sauuacion to werche</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>For al at ones he mey be<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>he mey be god, god</I> above the line in a later hand, evidently meant to gloss <I>he</I>, to which it is referred by the mark //.</NOTE></L>
<L N="777">&THORN;er and elles-were.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="112" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="778">&para; He soffre&thorn; wel to be kest op,</L>
<L>And &yogh;et to be honoured;</L>
<L>Ac he soffre&thorn; (no&yogh;t) to be to-trede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">(<I>no&yogh;t</I>) above the line in a later hand. See note.</NOTE></L>
<L N="781">And of bestes deuoured:</L>
<L>And neade,</L>
<L>Ase he by-leue assay&thorn; in flesch,</L>
<L N="784">He assay&thorn; ine forme of brede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="113" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="785">&para; &THORN;at body hy&yogh;t nys (na&yogh;t) &thorn;at &thorn;er com&thorn;e op,<NOTE PLACE="foot">(<I>na&yogh;t</I>) above the line in a later hand.&mdash;<I>nys, n</I> on erasure, probably altered from original <I>h</I>. See note.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;ef &thorn;at a man hy&yogh;t keste;
<PB REF="00000047.tif" N="29"></L>
<L>For al so longe hyt hys &thorn;at body,</L>
<L N="788">Ase forme of brede schel leste;</L>
<L>Ine manne,</L>
<L>&YOGH;et &thorn;a&yogh; &thorn;e fourme of brede to-go,</L>
<L N="791">&THORN;at body by-lef&thorn; &yogh;et &thorn;anne.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;et</I>, Wr. <I>h&yogh;et</I>, but the <I>h</I> is underdotted in MS.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="114" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="792">&para; And &yogh;yf he passe&thorn; nau&yogh;t fram ous,</L>
<L>Wanne wey ary&yogh;tt hym healde&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wey = we;</I> three letters erased between <I>ary&yogh;tt</I> and <I>hym</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wat ned hys for to take hym efte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Wat</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;at;</I> the <I>e</I> in <I>ned</I> looks very much like <I>o</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="795">&THORN;er wyle he ous so wealde&thorn;?</L>
<L>For mende</L>
<L>Of hys de&thorn;e and hys passyon,</L>
<L N="798">Ase he het atte hys ende.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>het</I>, MS. <I>he&thorn; hit;</I> &thorn; in <I>he&thorn;</I> on erasure, <I>hit</I> above the line in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="115" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="799">&para; Of pure wete hyt mot be,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="30"></L>
<L>And eke of pure wyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;et schel be to &thorn;ys sacrement</L>
<L N="802">Ry&yogh;t of &thorn;e grape of wyne</L>
<L>I-lete;</L>
<L>For iesus sey&thorn; &thorn;e vygne he hys,<MILESTONE N="161b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="805">And eke &thorn;e greyn of wete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="116" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="806">&para; And &yogh;ef mannes deuocioun slake&thorn;,</L>
<L>Wanne he by-healde&thorn;&mdash;</L>
<L>For hyt &thorn;ink&thorn; bote o&thorn;er bred</L>
<L N="809">An hea&yogh; &thorn;at &thorn;e prest healde&thorn;&mdash;</L>
<L>By-&thorn;enche hym</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e uertue &thorn;at &thorn;er hys,</L>
<L N="812">&THORN;at non errour adrenche hym;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Some letter (<I>n</I>?) erased before the initial <I>a</I> in <I>adrenche</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="117" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="813">&para; And tak en-saumple of &thorn;at he kneu&thorn;,</L>
<L>&THORN;e preciouse stone:</L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; he lygge amang o&thorn;ere ylyche,</L>
<L N="816">Me honoure&thorn; hym alone;</L>
<L>So swete
<PB REF="00000048.tif" N="30"></L>
<L>Mid al &thorn;y wyl &thorn;er uertue hys,</L>
<L N="819">God self ine sacrement (ymete).<NOTE PLACE="foot">The MS. has a dot after <I>sacrement; ymete</I> is a later addition. See note.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="118" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="820">&para; Na more ne greue&thorn; hyt ihesus</L>
<L>&THORN;ane sonne itrede in fel&thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; eny best deuoured hyt,</L>
<L N="823">O&thorn;er eny o&thorn;er onsel&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Ech screade</L>
<L>&YOGH;et al so longe hys godes body,</L>
<L N="826">Ase lest &thorn;e fourme of breade.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="119" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="827">&para; And al so longe hyt hys blod,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="31"></L>
<L>Ase lest &thorn;e forme of wyne;</L>
<L>Nau&yogh;t of fynegre kende chald,</L>
<L N="830">Ne offe water droppyng of wyne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>waterdroppymg</I> or -<I>droppying</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac trye:</L>
<L>So lyte water schel be me[<I>n</I>]gd,</L>
<L N="833">&THORN;at wyne habbe &thorn;e maystrye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="120" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="834">&para; For water self nys nau&yogh;t &thorn;at blod,</L>
<L>Ac hyt hys an-ylyke</L>
<L>To &thorn;e folke &thorn;at torne&thorn; al to cryst<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>To &thorn;e folke</I>, MS. <I>Ine folke</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="837">Ine &thorn;e body of mystyke.</L>
<L>Nou, bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L>I-lef al &thorn;ys ine gode fey,</L>
<L N="840">For may no &thorn;yng be so&thorn;er.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>(4) [D]E penitencia.<MILESTONE N="162" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<LG N="121" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="841">WAne man after hys crystendom<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Wane</I>, MS. <I>Ane</I>, with what seems to be a small runic <I>w</I> before it, intended for the rubricator.</NOTE></L>
<L>He&thorn; au&yogh;t ido wy&thorn; wronge,</L>
<L>Penaunce hyt hys, a sacrement</L>
<L N="844">&THORN;at men scholde fonge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>men scholde</I>, MS. <I>scholde men</I>, with the mark // before and after <I>scholde</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And mote.
<PB REF="00000049.tif" N="31"></L>
<L>Penaunce he&thorn; maneres &thorn;re,</L>
<L N="847">&THORN;or&yogh; sor&yogh;e, schryfte, and edbote.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="122" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="848">&para; &THORN;y sorwe for &thorn;yne senne, man,</L>
<L>Mot be ine gode wylle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hy ne be nau&yogh;t ine wanhope,</L>
<L N="851">&THORN;at made Iudas to spylle;</L>
<L>Ac crye</L>
<L>Mercy to swete ihesu cryst,</L>
<L N="854">Mid wyl to lete folye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="123" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="855">&para; And &yogh;et &thorn;y wylle mot be so gret,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="32"></L>
<L>And ine so gode faye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou wenst &thorn;ou noldest sene&yogh;i eft,</L>
<L N="858">&THORN;er-fore &thorn;e&yogh; &thorn;ou scholdest deye</L>
<L>Ine wytte;</L>
<L>For &yogh;ef &thorn;ou woldest for dea&thorn; hyt do,</L>
<L N="861">&THORN;y sor&yogh;e hys al to lyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="124" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="862">&para; &THORN;e&yogh; sor&yogh;e hele man a-non</L>
<L>Of vel&thorn; of sennes slyme,</L>
<L>&YOGH;et &thorn;anne were hyt nau&yogh;t inou&yogh;</L>
<L N="865">&THORN;e for [t]e sorwy on tyme,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for te</I> = for to.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac euere,</L>
<L>Ase longe ase, man, &thorn;y lyf ylest,</L>
<L N="868">Elles senne may keuere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="125" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="869">&para; For so, man, senne greue&thorn; in &thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>greue&thorn;</I>, grows; cp. <I>kneu&thorn;</I>, p. 29, l. 813; <I>fleu&thorn;</I>, p. 97, l. 343. It is difficult to decide whether the MS. has <I>greue&thorn;</I> or <I>groue&thorn;</I>, and in l. 871 <I>grewen</I> or <I>growen</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And eke in alle &thorn;yne,</L>
<L>Ase wed schel growen ouer &thorn;e corn,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ase</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;at</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="872">Wy&thorn;-oute medicyne</L>
<L>Of sor&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Nou her-on &thorn;enche, man, day and ny&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="164b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="875">An euen and a morwe.
<PB REF="00000050.tif" N="32"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="126" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="876">&para; &THORN;ench, &thorn;our&yogh; &thorn;y senne &thorn;ou hest ilore</L>
<L>&THORN;y blys of heuene ryche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;y</I>, read <I>&thorn;e</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L>And hest iwre&thorn;ed &thorn;ane kyng<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hest</I>, MS. <I>he&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="879">&THORN;at non hys yliche;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Read&mdash;<I>&thorn;at non hys hys</I> (or <I>hym</I>) <I>yliche</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L>And here</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hest of-serued dygnelyche</L>
<L N="882">&THORN;e pyne of helle vere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="127" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="883">&para; Dra&yogh; into mende &thorn;et hydous si&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hydous</I>, the final <I>s</I> altered from some other letter, probably <I>r.&mdash;si&yogh;t</I> added by a later hand.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="33"></L>
<L>Of deade men a bere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at nadde neuer deade ibe,</L>
<L N="886">&YOGH;ef senne of adam nere;</L>
<L>Bye drytte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>drytte</I>, MS. <I>drytte&yogh;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;et &thorn;ou a&yogh;test habbe more hydour</L>
<L N="889">Of &thorn;yne o&yogh;ene vn-ry&yogh;te.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="128" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="890">&para; Myd sucher sor&yogh;e schryfte, man,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>schryfte</I> = <I>schryf &thorn;e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel stylle, and no &thorn;yng loude;</L>
<L>For repentaunce onde&thorn; &thorn;e hel,</L>
<L N="893">And schreft hyt mot out-croude<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>croude</I>, suggested by Stratmann; MS. <I>treude</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al clene:</L>
<L>For &yogh;ef a&yogh;t lef&thorn; &thorn;at croude my&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>croude</I>, suggested by Stratmann; MS. <I>treude</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="896">God so &thorn;ou schelt ywenne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>guod</I> (or <I>goud</I>), <I>u</I> written over <I>o</I>; in the margin <I>uo</I> in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="129" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="897">&para; Ne non ne may hym schryue ary&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Bote &yogh;ef he hym by-&thorn;o&yogh;te</L>
<L>Of sennes &thorn;at he he&thorn; ydo,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>be&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="900">And hys lyf al &thorn;or&yogh;-so&yogh;te</L>
<L>To kenne;
<PB REF="00000051.tif" N="33"></L>
<L>Ac manie desper to &thorn;e prest<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>manie, i</I>-stroke wanting in MS.&mdash;<I>desper</I> (Wr. <I>dosper</I>), the first <I>e</I> looking very much like <I>o</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="903">Al one by se&yogh;e of senne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Al hou</I> (underdotted) <I>one</I>. See note.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="130" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="904">&para; And vnderstand &thorn;at al ihol</L>
<L>Mot be &thorn;y schryfte, bro&thorn;er;</L>
<L>Na&yogh;t &thorn;ar-of a kantel to a prest,</L>
<L N="907">And a kantel to an-o&thorn;er;</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne</L>
<L>Tele, &yogh;ef &thorn;ou my&yogh;t by-&thorn;enche &thorn;e,<MILESTONE N="163a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="910">Wet, hou, and wer, And wanne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dots in MS. after <I>Wet, hou</I>, and <I>wer</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="131" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="911">&para; And &yogh;ef &thorn;ou wylt, man, &thorn;or&yogh; &thorn;y schryft<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="34"></L>
<L>Lat &thorn;y senne al a-drou&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Ne wynd &thorn;ou naut &thorn;y senne ine selke,</L>
<L N="914">Ac telle out al &thorn;at rou&yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>, MS. <I>At</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tys la&yogh;e;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Tys</I> = <I>To hys</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;ef &thorn;ou wenst deie, and nast no prest,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>deie</I>, the initial <I>d</I> not quite distinct, resembling <I>s</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="917">Schryf &thorn;e to ano&thorn;er felawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="132" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="918">&para; Ac &thorn;at ne schalt &thorn;ou neuere do,</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;e wantrokye of lyue;</L>
<L>And &yogh;ef &thorn;ou comste to lyue a&yogh;en,</L>
<L N="921">Eft &thorn;rof &thorn;ou most &thorn;e scryue</L>
<L>To preste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he&thorn; power to assoyly &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="924">&THORN;or&yogh; power of &thorn;e greste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="133" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="925">&para; &THORN;a&yogh; man on tyme ihealde be<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;a&yogh;</I>, MS. <I>&yogh;a&yogh;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>To schryue hym a &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>To schryue hym wanne he sene&yogh;ed he&thorn;,</L>
<L N="928">Wel syker &thorn;yng hyt were,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>syker</I>, read <I>sykerer</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L>And mete,</L>
<L>Wald &yogh;ef he sodeynlyche dei&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota [<I>later</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L N="931">And wald he hyt for-&yogh;ete.
<PB REF="00000052.tif" N="34"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="134" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="932">&para; For wanne man sodeynleche dei&thorn;,</L>
<L>Hys &thorn;o&yogh;t &thorn;e sor&yogh;e trouble&thorn;;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>trouble&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>tumble&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And senne ony-schryue wanne he uor-&yogh;et,</L>
<L N="935">Hys senne &thorn;er-be double&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;er-be</I> = <I>&thorn;er-by</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>To nusy;</L>
<L>For mytter senne &thorn;at he dede</L>
<L N="938">&THORN;e sleu&thorn;e hine wyle acusy.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="135" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="939">&para; Man, schryf &thorn;e, and wonde none schame,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="35"></L>
<L>For-wy hyt hys to donne;</L>
<L>A lytel schame hys betere her,</L>
<L N="942">&THORN;ane ouer-moche eft-sone</L>
<L>To crefte</L>
<L>By-uore god a domesday,<MILESTONE N="163b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="945">Amang al godes schefte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="136" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="946">&para; For &thorn;a&yogh; man mo&yogh;e isauued be</L>
<L>&THORN;or&yogh; bare repentaunce,</L>
<L>Wanne he ne may to schryfte come,</L>
<L N="949">&YOGH;ef hym valle&thorn; &thorn;at chaunce</L>
<L>So holde,</L>
<L>&YOGH;et ne may he nau&yogh;t y-sauued be,</L>
<L N="952">Be he hym schriue wolde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Be</I>, read <I>Bote</I> ( = but)? Cf. however Zupitza's note to l. 7853 of the <I>Romance of Guy of Warw</I>., 15th cent. version.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="137" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="953">&para; &THORN;er-fore &thorn;y schryfte, man, schel be</L>
<L>Wy&thorn;-oute stoneynge,</L>
<L>Myd herte lo&yogh;, and, &yogh;ef &thorn;ou my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="956">Myd &thorn;yn e&yogh;ene wepynge;<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota [<I>later</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>In treu&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;et &thorn;er be non ypocrysye,</L>
<L N="959">Bote repentaunce and reu&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="138" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="960">&para; And &yogh;yf &thorn;at &thorn;ou to schryfte comst<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>comst</I>, MS. <I>comff</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ine &thorn;yse manere to fa[y]re,
<PB REF="00000053.tif" N="35"></L>
<L>&THORN;e schryft-uader &thorn;at uar&thorn; ary&yogh;t</L>
<L N="963">Schal be wel de-bonayre</L>
<L>And lo&yogh;e;</L>
<L>He schel wystlyche &thorn;y senne hele,</L>
<L N="966">Bet &thorn;ane he wolde hys owe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="139" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="967">&para; &YOGH;ef he &thorn;e schel anoye a&yogh;t,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="36"></L>
<L>Hyt wyle of-&thorn;enche hym sore;</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er-wyl anoye he mot,</L>
<L N="970">Wanne he schewe&thorn; &thorn;e lore</L>
<L>Of hel&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Ase mot &thorn;e leche ine uoule sores,</L>
<L N="973">Wanne he royne&thorn; &thorn;e fel&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="140" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="974">&para; &THORN;er-fore &yogh;e mote &thorn;olyen hyt</L>
<L>Wy&thorn;-oute alle manere tole,</L>
<L>And do &thorn;er-by ententyflyche,</L>
<L N="977">&YOGH;yf &yogh;e wolle&thorn; be hole</L>
<L>To liue;</L>
<L>And to a betere be leaue go&thorn;,<MILESTONE N="164a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="980">&YOGH;ef &yogh;oure prest can nau&yogh;t schryue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="141" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="981">&para; Te [&thorn;e] mo prestes &thorn;at &thorn;art ischryue<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Te</I> [<I>&thorn;e</I>] = <I>To</I> [<I>&thorn;e</I>].</NOTE></L>
<L>Myd alle y-hole schryfte,</L>
<L>&THORN;e clenner &thorn;ert a-&yogh;ens god,</L>
<L N="984">And of &thorn;e more &thorn;ryfte;</L>
<L>Nau&yogh;t nyce,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef hyt ne be nau&yogh;t to &thorn;y prest</L>
<L N="987">Malice ne preiudice.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="142" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="988">&para; Wanne man hys repentaunt ischriue,</L>
<L>He scholde don ed-bote;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e ferste hys, &thorn;at he by-fle</L>
<L N="991">Chypeans, of sennes rote;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Chypeans</I>, or <I>Chypeaus</I>, is the reading of the MS., which is evidently corrupt. So is also <I>by-flek</I> in l. 993. For a possible emendation of the whole passage, see note.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ase quances,
<PB REF="00000054.tif" N="36"></L>
<L>He &thorn;at by-flek wel lecherye</L>
<L N="994">Bi-ulek&thorn; foule continaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="143" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="995">&para; Edbote hys dede after god conseyl<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="37"></L>
<L>Of gosslich medicine,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>gosslich</I>, MS. <I>gofflich = gostlich</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wanne senne sor y-clensed hys,</L>
<L N="998">To &thorn;olye a lytel pyne</L>
<L>&THORN;et frete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne be &thorn;er-uore iwrete<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>iwrete</I> for <I>iurete, ifrete</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1001">In purgatoryes hete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="144" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1002">&para; &THORN;re maner peyne man a-fange&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a-fange&thorn;</I>, <I>a</I> dotted out in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>For hys senne nede;</L>
<L>Bene hys &thorn;at on, &thorn;at o&thorn;er fastyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Bene</I>, MS. <I>Senne</I>.&mdash;<I>&thorn;at o&thorn;er</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;</I><SUP>t</SUP><I>o&thorn;er</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="1005">&THORN;e &thorn;rydde hys almesdede;</L>
<L>Ac woste,</L>
<L>Bene hys and edbote yset<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Bene</I>, MS. <I>Sene.&mdash;and</I>, read <I>ase</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L N="1008">For senne do ine goste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="145" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1009">&para; For senne in flesch</L>
<L>vestyng he&thorn; &thorn;e flesch lo&thorn;e;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he&thorn;</I> might be read <I>be&thorn;</I> in MS.; see note.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac elmesdede senne bet</L>
<L N="1012">Of gost and flesche bo&thorn;e;</L>
<L>For &thorn;enche&thorn;</L>
<L>&THORN;et almesdede senne quenke&thorn;,<MILESTONE N="164b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1015">Ase water &thorn;at fer a-quenche&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="146" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1016">&para; To byddyng contemplacion<NOTE PLACE="foot">In MS. there are dots after <I>byddyng, contempl., wryte, predic</I>. and <I>won</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Longe&thorn; rede and wryte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">In MS. there are dots after <I>byddyng, contempl., wryte, predic</I>. and <I>won</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>To here predicacioun won,<NOTE PLACE="foot">In MS. there are dots after <I>byddyng, contempl., wryte, predic</I>. and <I>won</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1019">Lore, and herte smyte,</L>
<L>And werche<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>werche</I>, MS. <I>wreche</I>.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000055.tif" N="37"></L>
<L>Dedes to &yogh;yue deuocioun</L>
<L N="1022">To men ine holy cherche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="147" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1023">&para; Knewelyng, trauayl, baruot go,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="38"></L>
<L>Wolle-ward and wakynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Wolle, o</I> very much like <I>e</I> in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Discipline and lyte mete,</L>
<L N="1026">&THORN;es longe&thorn; to vestynge;</L>
<L>And here,</L>
<L>Pelgrymage and beddyng hard,</L>
<L N="1029">Flesch fram lykynge te arere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="148" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1030">&para; &YOGH;eue, and lene, and conseil,</L>
<L>Clo&thorn;yng, herber&yogh;, and fede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dots in MS. after <I>Clo&thorn;yng</I> and <I>syke</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vysyty syke and prysones,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dots in MS. after <I>Clo&thorn;yng</I> and <I>syke</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1033">And helpe pouere at nede,<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota [<I>later</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>Muknesse</L>
<L>For to uor-&yogh;euene trespas,</L>
<L N="1036">Tak dedes of elmesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="149" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1037">&para; And seue &yogh;er &thorn;ou scholdest, man,</L>
<L>O dea[d]lyche senne pyny;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pyny</I>, MS. <I>peyny</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er-uore al &thorn;at &thorn;e prest &thorn;e hat<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hat</I>, MS. <I>hast</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1040">To done schalt &thorn;ou nau&yogh;t fyny,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fyny</I> in a later hand. Immediately after <I>fyny</I>, there follow in the MS. the concluding lines of the next stanza&mdash;<I>For &yogh;yf &thorn;ou to lyte peyne hest</I>, and so on. The wanting portion of this, and the beginning of the following stanza are written at the bottom of the next page, and are marked with an .a. and bb. Corresponding letters after <I>fyny</I> show where the lines are to be inserted.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac more,</L>
<L>For onnea&thorn;e hys &thorn;er eny prest<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>onnea&thorn;e</I>, MS. <I>onmea&thorn;e</I> (for <I>onnica&thorn;e</I>?).</NOTE></L>
<L N="1043">&THORN;at peyne set so sore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="150" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1044">&para; For hy habbe&thorn; uisyk of men,<MILESTONE UNIT="foot folio" N="165"></L>
<L>Hy more sette &thorn;e lesse;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>more</I>, read <I>mo&yogh;e</I>? or <I>mote</I>?</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000056.tif" N="38"></L>
<L>And betere hys forte apeched be<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for</I>, MS. <I>ffor.&mdash;te</I> on erasure.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1047">Of more for&yogh;efnesse</L>
<L>&THORN;ane wreche;</L>
<L>For &yogh;yf &thorn;ou to lyte peyne hest,<MILESTONE UNIT="foot folio" N="164b"></L>
<L N="1050">Purgatorye hyt schal eche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="151" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1051">&para; And &yogh;et &thorn;er hys ano&thorn;er cas<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="39"></L>
<L>&THORN;at prestes &yogh;yuet so lyte</L>
<L>Penaunce: &thorn;a&yogh; me telle ham</L>
<L N="1054">Ry&yogh;t moche of sennes wyte,</L>
<L>Ine mone,</L>
<L>Me mot ham legge lytel on,<MILESTONE N="165a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1057">O&thorn;er hy nolde do none.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="152" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1058">&para; Beter hys &thorn;at hy a lyte do<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Beter</I>, MS. <I>Seter</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Her ine obedience,</L>
<L>And foluelle &thorn;at remenaunt</L>
<L N="1061">Ine purgatoryes tense</L>
<L>Eft-sone;</L>
<L>Nys nau&yogh;t god to uor-lete a man</L>
<L N="1064">&THORN;at eny-&thorn;ing hys wyl bone.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>eny-&thorn;ing</I>, MS. <I>eny ying.&mdash;wyl bone</I>? See note.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="153" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1065">&para; &THORN;e bydde ich, bro&thorn;er, be nau&yogh;t lo&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lo&thorn;</I>, &thorn; on erasure.</NOTE></L>
<L>To do penaunce here;</L>
<L>For &yogh;et &thorn;er hys here som reles,</L>
<L N="1068">So nys nau&yogh;t ine &thorn;e uere</L>
<L>Areyned,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;or&yogh; &thorn;e ry&yogh;t-uolnesse of god</L>
<L N="1071">Nys no sen onipeynid.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>onipeynid, ouipeynid</I> MS.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="154" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1072">&para; Man, wane &thorn;ou sene&yogh;yst, &thorn;re &thorn;ou dest,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wre&thorn;est god almy&yogh;ty,</L>
<L>To holy cherche on-bouxam &thorn;art,</L>
<L N="1075">Makest &thorn;y selue on-ry&yogh;ty:</L>
<L>&THORN;os mote<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;os &yogh;e mote, &yogh;e</I> in a later hand above the line.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000057.tif" N="39"></L>
<L>Make &thorn;y pes wy&thorn; alle &thorn;re</L>
<L N="1078">Sorwe, schryfte, and edbote.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="155" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1079">&para; Man[y] take&thorn; &thorn;ys sacrement,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="40"></L>
<L>And ge&thorn; a-wey on-digne,</L>
<L>For he ne schryf&thorn; nau&yogh;t of &thorn;et &thorn;yng,</L>
<L N="1082">Bote of &thorn;e bare signe</L>
<L>To wynne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e signe hys &thorn;at hys boute ydo,<MILESTONE N="165b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1085">&THORN;at &thorn;ynge hys grace bynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="156" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1086">&para; Two &thorn;ynges her-wy&thorn;-ynne be&thorn;,</L>
<L>For-&yogh;ef&thorn;e, and repentynge;</L>
<L>Ac repentaunce hys signe also</L>
<L N="1089">Of sennys for-&yogh;euyng:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for-&yogh;euyng</I>, MS. <I>forheuyng</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Certayne,</L>
<L>For so may man repenti hym,</L>
<L N="1092">&THORN;at &thorn;er uol&yogh;e&thorn; no peyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="157" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1093">&para; &THORN;at was iked wel inne &thorn;e &thorn;ef</L>
<L>Ope caluaryes felde,</L>
<L>&THORN;o he escusede ihesu cryst,</L>
<L N="1096">And hym gelty gan &yogh;elde</L>
<L>Mid sourwe;</L>
<L>He deide and come to paradys,</L>
<L N="1099">Na-bod he nau&yogh;t fort a morwe.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>(I. 5) [D]E uncione extrema.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>in margin</I>]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG N="158" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1100">SAcrement of an-Eliing</L>
<L>Nou her ich wolle telle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at man uange&thorn; wane he ne wen&thorn;</L>
<L N="1103">No lenge he my&yogh;te dwelle</L>
<L>A lyue;</L>
<L>&THORN;e bodyes euel &thorn;at libbe mey,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>libbe mey</I>, MS. <I>libbe ne mey, ne</I> in a later hand above the line.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1106">And sone, hit mey to-dryue.
<PB REF="00000058.tif" N="40"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="159" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1107">&para; Many for de-faute dei&thorn;e<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="41"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;er anelyynge;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf hys saule after hys de&thorn;e</L>
<L N="1110">Soffrey harde pynynge<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Soffrey</I>, read <I>Soffre&thorn;</I>, or <I>Soffry</I> (subjunct.).</NOTE></L>
<L>In fere,</L>
<L>So scholde hy nau&yogh;t, hedde he ihed</L>
<L N="1113">Ry&yogh;t elyynge here.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="160" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1114">&para; For seint iames, in hys bok,</L>
<L>Wysse&thorn; wyd gode mende</L>
<L>&THORN;at, &yogh;yf eny by-fal&thorn;e ry&yogh;t syke,</L>
<L N="1117">&THORN;e prest he scholde of-sende</L>
<L>To hys ende;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ende</I>, read <I>ynne</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L>And he schel elye hym wy&thorn; ele,<MILESTONE N="166a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1120">Hys sauement to wynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="161" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1121">&para; Seynt iame sey&thorn;e &thorn;at orysoun</L>
<L>Of &thorn;er holy by-leue</L>
<L>Of hijs siknesse hel&thorn;e wyn&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="1124">&THORN;at no fend schal reue</L>
<L>&THORN;e hel&thorn;e;</L>
<L>And &yogh;ef &thorn;at he ine sennys be,</L>
<L N="1127">For-&yogh;eue hys him &thorn;at fel&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="162" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1128">&para; &THORN;ys his, bro&thorn;er, and gret confort</L>
<L>For for-&yogh;etene sennes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A later hand has written <I>fer</I> over <I>for</I> in <I>for-&yogh;etene.&mdash;sennes</I>, MS. <I>synnes</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at oure foman aredy haue&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>foman, fo</I> above the line in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1131">A&yogh;eynys &thorn;at we go&thorn; hennes,</L>
<L>Ta-tuite;</L>
<L>Ac &yogh;ef we ary&yogh;t anelede be&thorn;,</L>
<L N="1134">Hy&yogh;t gayne&thorn; ham wel lyte.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lyte</I>, MS. <I>lytel</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="163" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1135">&para; Ac &thorn;anne hys man ary&yogh;t aneled,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="42"></L>
<L>Wanne he myd wyl hyt take&thorn;,
<PB REF="00000059.tif" N="41"></L>
<L>Myd by-leue of deuocioun,</L>
<L N="1138">And repentaunce make&thorn;</L>
<L>So digne;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf he hyt o&thorn;ere wyse fange&thorn;,</L>
<L N="1141">Ne take&thorn; ha bote &thorn;e syngne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="164" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1142">&para; For &thorn;e sygne of &thorn;ys sacrement</L>
<L>&THORN;e elyyng ys boute;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;yngge hys alleggaunce of euel,</L>
<L N="1145">To lyf &yogh;ef he schel loute;<NOTE PLACE="foot">In the margin, by the side of <I>To lyf</I>, is written in a later hand <I>o&thorn;er dia&thorn;</I>, to be inserted after <I>lyf</I>, as indicated by the usual marks of insertion.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hennes</L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; he wende, &thorn;at &thorn;yng is eke</L>
<L N="1148">Alleggaunce of hys sennes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="165" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1149">&para; And &yogh;et me schal anelye a man,</L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; &thorn;at he lese hys speche;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;a&yogh;</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;ar</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For wet he &thorn;enche&thorn; in hys mod</L>
<L N="1152">Ne may ous no man teche;</L>
<L>Ac stronge</L>
<L>He mot habbe deuocioun,<MILESTONE N="166b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1155">&THORN;et schel a-ry&yogh;t hyt fonge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="166" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1156">&para; &THORN;er-fore &thorn;is children ele&thorn; me nau&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ne for&thorn;e none wode,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Ne none</I> (expuncted).</NOTE></L>
<L>For hy ne conne mende haue</L>
<L N="1159">Of &thorn;ilke holy gode;</L>
<L>Ac fonge</L>
<L>&THORN;e wode mey &thorn;at sacrement,</L>
<L N="1162">Wane reles come&thorn; amonge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="167" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1163">&para; A prest mot do &thorn;ys sacrement,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="43"></L>
<L>For-why hy&yogh;t hys wel wer&thorn;e;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wer&thorn;e</I>, MS. <I>wor&thorn;e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at seyde seynt Iames wel,</L>
<L N="1166">&THORN;er-wyle he &yogh;ede an er&thorn;e;</L>
<L>&yogh;e hit hedde
<PB REF="00000060.tif" N="42"></L>
<L>&THORN;o ich a lite her a-boue</L>
<L N="1169">&THORN;es holye wordes redde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="168" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1170">&para; &THORN;e matyre of &thorn;is sacrement<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>matyre, y</I> written on original <I>e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hys ry&yogh;t &thorn;e oylle allone;</L>
<L>And wanne &thorn;e bisschop blesse&thorn; hyt,</L>
<L N="1173">Baume ne me[<I>n</I>]g&thorn; he none<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Baume &thorn;er wi&thorn; ne, &thorn;er wi&thorn;</I> being written over the line in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er-inne;</L>
<L>For baume tokne&thorn; lyues loos,</L>
<L N="1176">Oyle, mercy to wynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="169" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1177">&para; For wanne man dei&thorn;, he let his lyf</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;e god los by-houe&thorn;;</L>
<L>Ac senne, &yogh;ef he far&thorn;e ary&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1180">To bi-reusy he proue&thorn;;</L>
<L>To oure lorde</L>
<L>Mercy he cry&thorn;, and bidde&thorn; hym</L>
<L N="1183">Mercy and misericorde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="170" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1184">&para; &THORN;e wordes &thorn;at &thorn;er be&thorn; ised,</L>
<L>Hyt be&thorn; wordes of seal&thorn;e,</L>
<L>For hy bidde&thorn; &thorn;e sike man</L>
<L N="1187">Of alle his sennes hel&thorn;e;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>heal&thorn;e</I>, the <I>a</I> being dotted out.</NOTE></L>
<L>In mende</L>
<L>&THORN;er-to me an-ele&thorn; &thorn;e wyttes fy&yogh;f,<MILESTONE N="167a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1190">And fe&yogh;et, and breste, and lenden.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="171" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1191">&para; And for &thorn;e lecherye sy&yogh;t<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="44"></L>
<L>In lenden of &thorn;e manne,</L>
<L>And, ase &thorn;e bok ous sey&thorn;, hy sit</L>
<L N="1194">Inne nauele of &thorn;e wymman[e]:</L>
<L>To hele,</L>
<L>Me schel &thorn;e mannes lenden anelye,</L>
<L N="1197">&THORN;e nauele of &thorn;e femele.
<PB REF="00000061.tif" N="43"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="172" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1198">&para; &THORN;ys be&thorn; &thorn;e wordes wane me anele&thorn;:&mdash;</L>
<L>"By &thorn;isse an-eliinge,</L>
<L>And be hijs milse, for-&yogh;yue &thorn;e god<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota [<I>later</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L N="1201">Al &thorn;ine senne&yogh;ynge</L>
<L>Mid eyen";</L>
<L>And so he sey&thorn; be al hys lymes</L>
<L N="1204">&THORN;at scholle &thorn;e oyle dre&yogh;en.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="173" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1205">&para; Caracter, &thorn;et is prente ycliped,</L>
<L>Nys non of eliinge,</L>
<L>Ne fur&thorn; of penaunce ne &thorn;e mo,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fur&thorn;</I> on erasure in a later hand.&mdash;<I>ne</I> added over the line by a later scribe.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1208">Nof housel, nof spousynge,</L>
<L>In &thorn;ede;</L>
<L>For man ofter &thorn;ane ones take&thorn;</L>
<L N="1211">&THORN;e sacremens for nede.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="6" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>(I. 6) [D]E ordinibus ecclesiasticis.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>in margin</I>]</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<LG N="174" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1212">NOu her we mote, ine &thorn;is sarmon,</L>
<L>Of ordre maky sa&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;et was by-tokned sui&thorn;e wel<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;et</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;er</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1215">Wylom by &thorn;e ealde lawe</L>
<L>To agynne,</L>
<L>&THORN;o me made godes hous,</L>
<L N="1218">And ministres &thorn;er-inne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="175" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1219">&para; God ches folk specialliche<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="45"></L>
<L>Hys holy folk amonge;</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e kenred of leuy,</L>
<L N="1222">Offyce for to fonge</L>
<L>Ase bro&thorn;eren,</L>
<L>For to seruy ine godes house<MILESTONE N="167b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1225">By-fore alle &thorn;e no&thorn;eren.
<PB REF="00000062.tif" N="44"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="176" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1226">&para; To segge hys 'leuy' an englysch,</L>
<L>'Fram &thorn;e no&thorn;eren ytake';</L>
<L>So be&thorn; of ordre itake men,</L>
<L N="1229">Ase wyte fram &thorn;e blake</L>
<L>Of lyue :</L>
<L>Gode &yogh;eue al yordrede men</L>
<L N="1232">Wolde ary&yogh;t her-of schryue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="177" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1233">&para; Ase &thorn;er be&thorn; of &thorn;e holy gost</L>
<L>&YOGH;eftes ry&yogh;t folle seuene,</L>
<L>So &thorn;er be&thorn; ordres folle seuene,</L>
<L N="1236">&THORN;at made cryst of heuene</L>
<L>An er&thorn;e,</L>
<L>And hedde hys ek ine hys monhe&thorn;,</L>
<L N="1239">To ke&thorn;en hy wel wer&thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. : <I>&thorn;t wer' To ke &thorn;en hy : wel wer&thorn;e</I>. The words <I>&thorn;t wer</I>' are written in the margin in a later hand. They are to be inserted after <I>hy</I>, as the scribe has intimated by putting a colon before <I>&thorn;t</I>, and a corresponding one after <I>hy</I>. The space between <I>ke</I> and <I>&thorn;en</I> is a little wider than that between <I>To</I> and <I>ke</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="178" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1240">&para; &THORN;e ferste hys 'doreward' ycleped,</L>
<L>&THORN;e secunde 'redynge,'</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;rydde hys icleped 'coniurement'</L>
<L N="1243">A&yogh;enys &thorn;e foule &thorn;ynge</L>
<L>to werie &thorn;e;<NOTE PLACE="foot">The original reading of the MS. was <I>&thorn;e greste</I>, which is really the bob-verse of the next stanza, erroneously anticipated by the scribe. A later revisor struck it out, or found it already struck out, and wrote above it what I read <I>to werie &thorn;e</I>. Mr. Wright has printed <I>wersiexe</I>; but this is an error, evidently owing to the fact that the protracted upward stroke of the long s of <I>greste</I> happens to come in between the letters <I>r</I> and <I>i</I> in <I>werie</I>, while the oblique tag attached to the top of the long s crosses the &thorn; of <I>&thorn;e</I>. For the true reading see note.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e fer&thorn;e 'acolyt' hys to segge y-wys,</L>
<L N="1246">Tapres to bere wel wor&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="179" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1247">&para; &THORN;e ordre fifte ycleped hys<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="46"></L>
<L>&THORN;e ordre of 'sudeakne,'
<PB REF="00000063.tif" N="45"></L>
<L>And hys &thorn;e syxte al-so ycleped</L>
<L N="1250">&THORN;e holy ordre of 'dekene';</L>
<L>(And) &thorn;e greste<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omit <I>And</I> (see preceding footnote). The bob-verse left out here by the original scribe has been supplemented by the later revisor.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e seuen[d]e hys, and hys yclyped</L>
<L N="1253">&THORN;e holy ordre of 'prest[e].'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="180" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1254">&para; Ine &thorn;e elde lawe synagoge ferst<NOTE PLACE="foot">ff. See note.</NOTE></L>
<L>God let the ordres werche,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at was sched of &thorn;at hys ly&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1257">Nou wro&yogh;t ine holy cherche;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wro&yogh;t</I>, MS. <I>wryt</I>; Zupitza <I>wor&yogh;t</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Iuere</L>
<L>Ich schel telle hou hyt was &thorn;er,<MILESTONE N="168a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1260">And hou hyt hys now here.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>(I. 6. i) [D]E hostiariis.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>in margin</I>]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG N="181" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1261">INe &thorn;e ealde lawe dore-ward</L>
<L>Lokede dore and gate,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;er ne scholde on-clene &thorn;yng</L>
<L N="1264">Ry&yogh;t non entry &thorn;er-ate,</L>
<L>Wel cou&thorn;e:</L>
<L>So do&thorn; &thorn;es dore-wardes ek</L>
<L N="1267">Ine holy cherche nou&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="182" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1268">&para; And &yogh;ef eny o&thorn;er hyt do&thorn;,</L>
<L>Nys hyt ordre, ac ileaue<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dot in MS. after <I>ordre</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>To helpe, wane &thorn;er nede iual&thorn;;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>helpe</I>, MS. <I>hel&thorn;e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1271">Ac me ne schal nau&yogh;t reaue</L>
<L>&THORN;e office,</L>
<L>Wy&thorn;-oute leue to don hyt :</L>
<L N="1274">Ne be no man so nice.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="183" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1275">&para; &THORN;e bisschop, wanne he ordre&thorn; &thorn;es,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="47"><NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;es clerekes (clerekes</I> added in margin by a later scribe).</NOTE></L>
<L>Tak&thorn; hym &thorn;e cherche key&yogh;e,
<PB REF="00000064.tif" N="46"></L>
<L>And sey&thorn; :&mdash;"take&thorn; and do&thorn; fol wel,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>do&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>do&thorn;e&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1278">Ase, wane &yogh;e scholle deye,</L>
<L>Scholde &yogh;elde</L>
<L>Acounte of &thorn;et hys &thorn;er-onder clos :"</L>
<L N="1281">Hardyst &thorn;et, wo-so hyt felde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Hardyst</I>, read <I>Hard ys</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="184" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1282">&para; Ine &thorn;e temple swete ihesus</L>
<L>&THORN;yse ordre tok at ones,</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at he makede a baleys,</L>
<L N="1285">And bet out for &thorn;e nones,</L>
<L>Ymene,</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at bou&yogh;te and sealde ine godes hous,</L>
<L N="1288">&THORN;at hys a hous of bene.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>(I. 6. ii) [D]E lectoribus<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>in margin</I>]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG N="185" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1289">NOu ich habbe of &thorn;e ferste yteld,</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er wyl ich trye.</L>
<L>Ine &thorn;e alde la&yogh;e &thorn;e redere</L>
<L N="1292">Rede &thorn;e prophessye,</L>
<L>By wokke;</L>
<L>So schulle &thorn;e rederes now<MILESTONE N="168b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1295">Hyrede, and conne on-lowke.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Hy</I>, MS. <I>By</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="186" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1296">&para; &THORN;er-fore, ere hy &thorn;ys ordre haue,</L>
<L>Me schel hy wel assaye,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at hy rede&thorn; &thorn;at hy wel</L>
<L N="1299">Ham conne aueye;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ham</I>, MS. <I>Ram</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For-bede</L>
<L>O&thorn;e-ren to reden schal me no&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1302">Ac soffry hyt for nede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="187" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1303">&para; &THORN;yse ordre swete ihesu cryst<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="48"></L>
<L>Kedde wel &thorn;at he hadde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Read <I>hedde, redde</I>.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000065.tif" N="47"></L>
<L>&THORN;o he toke ysaies bok</L>
<L N="1306">Ine &thorn;e synagoge, and radde<NOTE PLACE="foot">Read <I>hedde, redde</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wet welle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">See note.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wet he &thorn;er redde, &thorn;ou my&yogh;t se</L>
<L N="1309">Ine seynt lukes god-spelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="188" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1310">&para; &THORN;e bysschop, wenne he ordre&thorn; &thorn;es,</L>
<L>&THORN;e redyng bok hym take&thorn;,</L>
<L>And sey&thorn; :&mdash;"tak and by-come redere</L>
<L N="1313">Of word &thorn;at of god smake&thorn;;</L>
<L>And blice</L>
<L>Schelt habbe ase god prechour,</L>
<L N="1316">&YOGH;ef &thorn;ou wolt do &thorn;yne offyce."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>do</I> over the line in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>(I. 6. iii) [D]E exorcistis.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>in margin</I>]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG N="189" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1317">&THORN;E &thorn;rydde ordre [hys] coniurement,</L>
<L>And was ine &thorn;e ealde la&yogh;e</L>
<L>To dryue out deuelyn out of men</L>
<L N="1320">Fram god &thorn;at were dra&yogh;e</L>
<L>Alyue;</L>
<L>&THORN;anne he mot habbe a clene gost,</L>
<L N="1323">&THORN;at schal &thorn;e on-clene out-dryue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="190" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1324">&para; &THORN;e bisschop, wane he ordre&thorn; &thorn;es,</L>
<L>Tak&thorn; ham bok of Cristnynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Tak&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>Take</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>O&thorn;er of o&thorn;er coniuremens</L>
<L N="1327">A&yogh;eyns &thorn;e foule &thorn;ynge,</L>
<L>And segge&thorn; :&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>segge&thorn;</I> [: <I>bigge&thorn;</I>], see note.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Take&thorn; power to legge hand<MILESTONE N="169a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1330">Ouer ham &thorn;at fendes op bigge&thorn;."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>segge&thorn;</I> [: <I>bigge&thorn;</I>], see note.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="191" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1331">&para; &THORN;yse ordre, swete ihesu cryst<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="49"></L>
<L>kedde Wel &thorn;at he hedde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kedde</I> in MS. at the end of the preceding line, with a dot before it and another one after it.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000066.tif" N="48"></L>
<L>&THORN;o he drof deuelen out of men</L>
<L N="1334">&THORN;at hym wel sore dredde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e apryse</L>
<L>Ine &thorn;e elde la&yogh;e hyt ferst by-gan<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>la&yogh;e</I>, MS. <I>le&yogh;e</I>, added over the line.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1337">Kyng salomon, &thorn;e wyse.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>(I. 6. iv) [D]E accolitis.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>in margin</I>]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG N="192" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1338">&THORN;E Ordre fer&thorn;e, accolyt hys,</L>
<L>To bere tapres aly&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>aly&yogh;te</I> is Varnhagen's emendation of the MS. reading <I>aboute</I>, to which a later hand has added <I>wi&yogh;t ri&yogh;t</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wanne me schel rede &thorn;e gospel,</L>
<L N="1341">O&thorn;er offry oure dryte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>offry to oure dryte</I> ( = <I>dry&yogh;te</I>), <I>to</I> added over the line.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;enche</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;et ly&yogh;t by-tokne&thorn; &thorn;at ly&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1344">&THORN;et no&thorn;yng may quenche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="193" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1345">&para; And wanne &thorn;at he yordred hys,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bisschop schel hym teche</L>
<L>Hou he schel lokke cherche ly&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1348">And wyne and water areche</L>
<L>To synge;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>synge</I>, see note.</NOTE></L>
<L>In tokne, taper and crowet</L>
<L N="1351">To hand me schal hym brynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="194" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1352">&para; &THORN;et &thorn;ys ordre hedde ihesus</L>
<L>We habbe&thorn; wel a-founde,</L>
<L>By &thorn;et he seyde :&mdash;"ich [a]m &thorn;at ly&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1355">Of alle &thorn;er wordle rounde</L>
<L>A-boute;</L>
<L>Wo-so loke&thorn;, ne ge&thorn; he nau&yogh;t derk,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>so</I> added over the line.&mdash;<I>ne</I> altered from <I>me</I>, the first stroke having been erased.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1358">Ac ly&yogh;t ine lyues route."
<PB REF="00000067.tif" N="49"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="195" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1359">&para; Ine &thorn;e elde temple tokne was<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="50"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e ordre of acolytes,</L>
<L>&THORN;o certeyne men ly&yogh;te &thorn;at ly&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1362">Ase &thorn;e la&yogh;e &yogh;ef &thorn;e rytes</L>
<L>So brode;</L>
<L>Of weche ly&yogh;t hys ywryte<MILESTONE N="169b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1365">Ine &thorn;e boke of exode.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="5" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>(I. 6. v.) [D]E subdiaconis.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>in margin</I>]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG N="196" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1366">&THORN;E ordre fifte, sudeakne hys,</L>
<L>&THORN;at chastete en-ioy[n]e&thorn;;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>enioyne&thorn;</I> [: <I>aloyne&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>aolyne&thorn;</I>] suggested by Zupitza.</NOTE></L>
<L>For sudeakne bere&thorn; &thorn;e chalys</L>
<L N="1369">To &thorn;e auter and aloyne&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>enioyne&thorn;</I> [: <I>aloyne&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>aolyne&thorn;</I>] suggested by Zupitza.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ande welde&thorn;</L>
<L>Al bare, and eke &thorn;e corperaus</L>
<L N="1372">Onder &thorn;e deakne uealde&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="197" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1373">&para; Ine &thorn;e alde lawe y-hote hyt hys,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hy ham scholde clensy</L>
<L>&THORN;at bere &thorn;at uessel of god,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bere</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;ere</I>, &thorn; in a different hand, altered from some other letter.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1376">And myd water bensy :</L>
<L>By ry&yogh;tte,</L>
<L>Clenne schel he in herte be</L>
<L N="1379">&THORN;at schal &thorn;e chalys di&yogh;te.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="198" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1380">&para; And wanne &thorn;at he yordred hys,</L>
<L>He take&thorn; &thorn;e chalys bare,</L>
<L>And he auange&thorn; a crowet eke,</L>
<L N="1383">And a towaylle nare</L>
<L>Iuere;</L>
<L>For he schel honden helde weter</L>
<L N="1386">&THORN;at serue&thorn; to &thorn;e autere.
<PB REF="00000068.tif" N="50"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="199" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1387">&para; &THORN;o hym wy&thorn; a schete ihesus<NOTE PLACE="foot">In the margin of the MS., above <I>ihesus</I>, a later hand has written <I>touwayle</I>, to be inserted before <I>schete</I>, but evidently meant to replace or gloss it.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="51"></L>
<L>After soper bygerte,</L>
<L>And water in ta bacyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">The verb is wanting here; perhaps, we may supply <I>keste. in ta = in to a</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1390">Myd a wel mylde herte,</L>
<L>And wesschte</L>
<L>Al hys apostlene ueet,</L>
<L N="1393">&THORN;os ordre for&thorn;e he lesschte.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="6" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>(I. 6. vi.) [D]E diaconis.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>in margin</I>]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG N="200" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1394">NOu of &thorn;e sixte telle ich schel,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hys &thorn;e ordre of deakne,</L>
<L>&THORN;et hys of more perfeccioun</L>
<L N="1397">&THORN;ane hys ordre of sudeakne;</L>
<L>He brynge&thorn;</L>
<L>To honde &thorn;et &thorn;e prest schel haue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>haue</I> written twice in MS., the second crossed out.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="170a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1400">Wanne he &thorn;e masse singe&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="201" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1401">&para; Ine &thorn;e ealde lawe beren hy</L>
<L>&THORN;e hoche of holy crefte,</L>
<L>And nou &thorn;e stole a-fonge&thorn; hy</L>
<L N="1404">Ope here scholder lefte,</L>
<L>To agynne,</L>
<L>And so for &thorn;ane trauaylle her</L>
<L N="1407">&THORN;e ry&yogh;t half for to wynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="202" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1408">&para; And at ordres auange&thorn; hy</L>
<L>&THORN;e bok of &thorn;e godspelle,</L>
<L>For &thorn;an, to rede &thorn;e gospel,</L>
<L N="1411">And sarmoun for to telle,</L>
<L>Ta-wak<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ta-wak</I> for <I>Ta-waky = to awaky</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hy &thorn;et slepe&thorn; ine senne slep,</L>
<L N="1414">Amendement to maky.
<PB REF="00000069.tif" N="51"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="203" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1415">&para; &THORN;yse ordre swete ihesu cryst<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="52"></L>
<L>Ine hys trauayle kedde,</L>
<L>&THORN;o he prechinde &thorn;et folk</L>
<L N="1418">To ry&yogh;tte weye ledde;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ridde</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;redde</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was, &thorn;o he wakede hym self</L>
<L N="1421">&THORN;e apostles for to bydde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="7" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>(I. 6. vii.) [D]E presbiteris.</HEAD>
<LG N="204" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1422">&THORN;E seuende ordre hys of &thorn;e prest,</L>
<L>An hys icleped &thorn;e ealde,</L>
<L>Bote nau&yogh;t of &yogh;eres, ac of wyt,</L>
<L N="1425">Ase holy wryt ous tealde;</L>
<L>For &yogh;eres</L>
<L>Ne make&thorn; so nau&yogh;t &thorn;ane prest ald,</L>
<L N="1428">Ac sadnesse of maneres.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="205" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1429">&para; And wanne he y-ordred hys,</L>
<L>Hym fal&thorn; an holy gyse :</L>
<L>Hys honden be&thorn; anoynte bo&thorn;e</L>
<L N="1432">&THORN;or&yogh;-out a crowche wyse,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>crowche:</I> in the MS. there is a stroke discernible between the letters <I>c</I> and <I>r</I>, which led Mr. Wright to print <I>cirowche</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ta-fonge</L>
<L>&THORN;er-inne godes o&yogh;en flesch,<MILESTONE N="170b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1435">&THORN;at fode is to &thorn;e stronge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="206" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1436">&para; He tak&thorn; &thorn;e helye inne of ey&thorn;er half<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>helye inne</I>, see note.</NOTE></L>
<L>Yioyned atte breste,</L>
<L>&THORN;et no god hap ne he&yogh;i hyne,</L>
<L N="1439">Ne non harm hyne don deste</L>
<L>In mode,</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;enche on hym &thorn;at &thorn;olede dea&thorn;</L>
<L N="1442">For ous op-one &thorn;e roude.
<PB REF="00000070.tif" N="52"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="207" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1443">&para; He tak&thorn; &thorn;e chalys wy&thorn; &thorn;e wyne,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="53"></L>
<L>And brede of &thorn;e pateyne;</L>
<L>He he&thorn; power to sacry hyt,</L>
<L N="1446">And &thorn;et &thorn;rof hys &thorn;er seyne<NOTE PLACE="foot">See note.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel trewe.</L>
<L>Inne &thorn;e elde lawe &thorn;e ordre agan,</L>
<L N="1449">Ine tokne of &thorn;yssere newe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="208" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1450">&para; Cryst kedde &thorn;at he hys a prest</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t in double manere :</L>
<L>&THORN;at on, &thorn;o he sacrede hys body,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sacrede</I>, MS. <I>sacreded</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1453">&THORN;er he set atte sopere;</L>
<L>&THORN;et o&thorn;er,</L>
<L>&THORN;o he an rode offrede hys body<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>an rode</I>, MS. <I>&amacr; ro de, u</I> erased between <I>o</I> and <I>d</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1456">For ous, my leue bro&thorn;er.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>[D]E prima tonsura.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>in margin</I>]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG N="209" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1457">TO &thorn;ys ordre crounebet<NOTE PLACE="foot">Read <I>To &thorn;yse ordres?&mdash;crounebet</I>, read <I>crounement</I>? See note.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ys an apparyllyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>apparyllyng</I>, MS. <I>apparyblyng</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at hys in holy cherche y-cleped wel</L>
<L N="1460">&THORN;e furste scherynge<NOTE PLACE="foot">1459-1460. Read <I>&thorn;at hys in holy cherche wel Ycleped &thorn;e f. sch</I>.?</NOTE></L>
<L>Of clerke;</L>
<L>Clerke hys to segge an englysch,</L>
<L N="1463">'Eyr of godes werke.'<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>werke</I>, MS. <I>worke</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="210" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1464">&para; Ac godes werk an er&thorn;e was</L>
<L>&THORN;e puple for to teche;</L>
<L>And also &thorn;our&yogh; hys holy de&thorn;e</L>
<L N="1467">Of sennes he was leche :</L>
<L>&THORN;es werkes</L>
<L>Men take&thorn; after ihesu cryst,<MILESTONE N="171a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1470">Wanne hy by-come&thorn; clerkes.
<PB REF="00000071.tif" N="53"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="211" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1471">&para; And &yogh;yf hy dou&thorn; wel hare deuer<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="54"></L>
<L>Ine &thorn;ysse heritage,</L>
<L>Ne may hem falle after &thorn;ys lyf</L>
<L N="1474">Non oun-wor&thorn; desparage;</L>
<L>To wysse,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t ymarissched schelle hy be</L>
<L N="1477">In heuene-ryche blysse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="212" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1478">&para; &THORN;e croune of clerke y-opened hys,</L>
<L>Tokne&thorn; &thorn;e wyl to heuene,</L>
<L>&THORN;et habbe mot &thorn;at entri schel</L>
<L N="1481">Into eny of &thorn;e seuene;</L>
<L>And sedder</L>
<L>Tokne&thorn;, ase he ine ordre aryst,</L>
<L N="1484">&THORN;et hys &thorn;e croune breddour.<NOTE PLACE="foot">1482-84. See note.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="213" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1485">&para; &THORN;er drof bischop hys dignete</L>
<L>To maky &thorn;ulke seuene;</L>
<L>And hyt by-tokne&thorn; &thorn;ane bisschop</L>
<L N="1488">In &thorn;e bisschopriche of heuene</L>
<L>So werthe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>wrethe</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was vicary &thorn;e pope hys<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Was and hys &thorn;e pope vicary,&mdash;and</I> added over the line by a later hand; after <I>hys, po</I> is dotted out.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1491">I-maked here an er&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<LG N="214" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1492">&para; &THORN;yse ordres to &thorn;ys sacrement<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;yse</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;y&thorn;e;</I> for this and the following lines see note.</NOTE></L>
<L>By ry&yogh;te longi scholle,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at mo be &thorn;at gode be&thorn;,</L>
<L N="1495">&THORN;es make&thorn; al &thorn;at folle</L>
<L>Be astente;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore ich abbe ondo &yogh;ou &thorn;os<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;os</I>, read <I>&thorn;ys</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L N="1498">For &thorn;yse sacrement[e].
<PB REF="00000072.tif" N="54"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="215" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1499">&para; And nou ich wolle ondo &thorn;ys eft<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="55"></L>
<L>By &thorn;e wey of mystyke;</L>
<L>For crystene man hys godes hous:</L>
<L N="1502">Hye mote habbe wyke<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Hye</I>, see note.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er-inne,</L>
<L>Nou lestlich schel ich on-louke &thorn;ys,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lestlich</I> altered from <I>lett ich</I>, which is still quite distinct in MS.&mdash;<I>ich</I> (written i<SUP>c</SUP>) after <I>schel</I> added over the line. See note.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1505">Ase god wyle grace &yogh;yue.<MILESTONE N="171b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="216" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1506">&para; &THORN;et ine-wyt hys &thorn;e dore-ward,</L>
<L>&THORN;e doren wyttes fyue;</L>
<L>He schel loky wel bysylyche,</L>
<L N="1509">&THORN;at no lykynge in dryue</L>
<L>&THORN;at stenche&thorn;;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>stenche&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>stenke&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;et inwyt hys &thorn;e reddere eke</L>
<L N="1512">&THORN;at holy lore &thorn;enche&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="217" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1513">&para; &THORN;et inne-wyt dryf&thorn; &thorn;e fend a-wey</L>
<L>Myd meende of crystes pyne;</L>
<L>&THORN;et inwyt ly&yogh;t &thorn;er saule ly&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1516">Myd &thorn;eawes gode and fyne;</L>
<L>To hele,</L>
<L>&THORN;et inwyt wescht &thorn;e fel&thorn;e awey,</L>
<L N="1519">And greyde&thorn; &thorn;e fessele.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="218" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1520">&para; &THORN;et inwyt rede&thorn; &thorn;at gospel,</L>
<L>Wane hyt here&thorn; crystes lore;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>here&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>herere&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;et &thorn;er-to hys charge hyt ber&thorn;</L>
<L N="1523">Of left half swy&thorn;e sore,</L>
<L>To abyde</L>
<L>After &thorn;ys lyf &thorn;e heuene blys,</L>
<L N="1526">And krefte &thorn;e ry&yogh;t[e] syde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="219" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1527">&para; &THORN;at inwyt hys &thorn;e masse prest,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="56"></L>
<L>&THORN;at ine &thorn;e herte slake&thorn;
<PB REF="00000073.tif" N="55"></L>
<L>&THORN;ane auter of deuocioun,</L>
<L N="1530">Wane man hys bene make&thorn;;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bene</I>, first <I>e</I> resembling <I>o</I> in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>No lesse</L>
<L>Nys hyt, wane man stedeuast by-lef&thorn;,</L>
<L N="1533">Sacrement of &thorn;e messe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="220" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1534">&para; On inwyt mey al &thorn;ys wel do,</L>
<L>And ine &thorn;e manne werche,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Between <I>manne</I> and <I>werche, to</I> added over the line by a later hand; the <I>r</I> in <I>werche</I> on erasure.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ase on may al &thorn;ys ordres haue</L>
<L N="1537">Ryt wel in holy cherche;</L>
<L>Ase here,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef her nys suiche mynystre non,<MILESTONE N="172a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1540">&THORN;ys temple stent iuere.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>iuere</I> ( = <I>i</I>[<I>n</I>] <I>f&emacr;re</I>), MS. <I>euere</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="221" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1541">&para; &THORN;er-fore ech man &thorn;at crystene hys,</L>
<L>Hys wyttes loky fyue,</L>
<L>And &thorn;enche op-an &thorn;e lore of god,</L>
<L N="1544">And fendes fram hym dryue,</L>
<L>And ly&yogh;te</L>
<L>Myd gode &thorn;ewes al hys lyf,</L>
<L N="1547">And &thorn;er-to do hys my&yogh;te;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>do, d</I> altered from <I>t</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="222" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1548">&para; And wessche and greydy hys fessel,</L>
<L>And do trewlyche hys charge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>do</I> altered from <I>to</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And make offrynge of hys beden,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>make</I>, MS. <I>maked</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1551">Myd wil do elmesse large:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wil do</I>, MS. <I>wel to</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ys wyke</L>
<L>By &thorn;ys &yogh;e iseo&thorn; how ech mey do</L>
<L N="1554">Ine manere of mystyke.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="223" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1555">&para; &THORN;e signe hys of &thorn;ys sacrement<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="57"></L>
<L>&THORN;e bisschopes blessynge,
<PB REF="00000074.tif" N="56"></L>
<L>For&thorn; myd &thorn;e admynystracioun</L>
<L N="1558">&THORN;at he de&thorn; atte ord[r]ynge;</L>
<L>And grace</L>
<L>Of wyt and of auctoryte</L>
<L N="1561">&THORN;et &thorn;yng hys ine &thorn;e place.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="7" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>(I. 7) [D]E matrimonio.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>in margin</I>]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG N="224" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1562">HEr longe&thorn; nou to &thorn;ys sarmon</L>
<L>Of spousyng for to werche,</L>
<L>&THORN;et hys &thorn;e tokne of &thorn;e ioynyng</L>
<L N="1565">of Gode and holy cherche;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I> in MS. at the end of the preceding line.</NOTE></L>
<L>And woste,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t holy cherche ycleped hys</L>
<L N="1568">&THORN;at holy folk ine goste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="225" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1569">&para; And ase &thorn;er mot atter spousyng</L>
<L>Be ry&yogh;t a-sent of bo&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Of man and of &thorn;er wymman ek,</L>
<L N="1572">Yn loue and nau&yogh;t y lo&thorn;e,</L>
<L>I-lyche</L>
<L>By-tuixe god and holy folk<MILESTONE N="172b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1575">Loue hys wel trye and ryche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="226" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1576">&para; &THORN;anne a&yogh;te men here wyues loue,</L>
<L>Ase god do&thorn; holy cherche;</L>
<L>And wyues nau&yogh;t a&yogh;ens men</L>
<L N="1579">Non on-wrestnesse werche,</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;o-lye,</L>
<L>And nau&yogh;t onwrest op-sechen hy,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>onwrest, e</I> hardly to be distinguished from <I>o. &mdash; sechen</I>, MS. <I>sechem</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1582">Ne tounge of hefede holye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="227" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1583">&para; Ine wlessche ioyne&thorn; man and wyf,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="58"></L>
<L>Children to multeplye;
<PB REF="00000075.tif" N="57"></L>
<L>And god ha&thorn; taken oure flesch</L>
<L N="1586">Of &thorn;e mayde marye;</L>
<L>Wel ferren</L>
<L>&THORN;erof springe&thorn; &thorn;et holye stren<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>springe&thorn;</I>, the <I>r</I> added above the <I>i</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1589">I-lykned to &thorn;e sterren.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="228" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1590">&para; Wel fayr &thorn;anne hys &thorn;ys sacrement,</L>
<L>And marye was by-gonne</L>
<L>&THORN;o hyt by-gan ine paradys,</L>
<L N="1593">Are adam were y-wonne</L>
<L>To senne;</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;o changede to uylenye<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;o</I>, altered to <I>so</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1596">&THORN;at stat of man-kenne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="229" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1597">&para; For &yogh;ef he hedde ihealde hym,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he</I> written above the line (in a later hand?).</NOTE></L>
<L>Ase god hym hedde y-maked,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>y-maked, y</I> added above the line by a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L>He hedde y-brout for&thorn;e hys bearm-team</L>
<L N="1600">Wy&thorn;-oute senne ismaked.</L>
<L>Wet &thorn;anne?</L>
<L>&YOGH;et holy stren by-tokned hys</L>
<L N="1603">By strenyng of &thorn;e mane.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="230" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1604">&para; Hyt was god self &thorn;at spousyng ferst<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dots in MS. before and after <I>ferst</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>In paradys[e] sette;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend hyt was &thorn;at schente hyt al</L>
<L N="1607">Myd gyle and hys abette,</L>
<L>Wrancheuel:</L>
<L>Spouso&thorn; scheawy&thorn; wet god &thorn;er dede;<MILESTONE N="173a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1610">Hordom, wat dede &thorn;e deuel.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Hordom</I>, MS. <I>Hourdom</I>, but the <I>u</I> seems to have been crossed out.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="231" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1611">&para; For wanne man dra&yogh;&thorn; to hordom,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="59"></L>
<L>He let hys ry&yogh;t[e] spouse;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>He</I> crossed out in MS., and the abbreviation for <I>and</I> written in the margin.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000076.tif" N="58"></L>
<L>So dede adam ine paradys</L>
<L N="1614">Hys ry&yogh;t[e] lord of house,</L>
<L>Of heuene:</L>
<L>&THORN;e gode forhorede &thorn;e fend</L>
<L N="1617">Wy&thorn; hys blaundynge steuene.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="232" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1618">&para; &THORN;at de&thorn; &thorn;at god menteyne&thorn; wel<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wel</I> in MS. at the beginning of the following line.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t spousyng her an er&thorn;e,</L>
<L>And euer mo schel go to schame</L>
<L N="1621">Hordom, and &thorn;et hys wer&thorn;e;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wer&thorn;e</I>, MS. <I>wor&thorn;e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>I-lome</L>
<L>&YOGH;het some wene&thorn; ligge in spousho&thorn;,</L>
<L N="1624">And li&thorn;e ine hordome.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="233" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1625">&para; &THORN;er-fore ich wylle telle &yogh;ou</L>
<L>&THORN;e lore of ry&yogh;t spousynge,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e ne take horedom,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;e</I>, MS. <I>he</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1628">Wanne take&thorn; weddynge.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Read&mdash;<I>Wanne</I> &yogh;e <I>t. w</I>.?</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">notabile</NOTE></L>
<L>Nou lestne&thorn;</L>
<L>&THORN;e lore al of &thorn;e la&yogh;e y-wryte</L>
<L N="1631">&THORN;at holy cherche festne&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="234" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1632">&para; Ase to god, hyt were y-now</L>
<L>&THORN;at bare assent oof bo&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Wy&thorn;-oute speche and by-treu&thorn;ynge,</L>
<L N="1635">And alle manere o&thorn;e.&mdash;</L>
<L>And speche?</L>
<L>&THORN;er mote be speche, of hare assent</L>
<L N="1638">Holy cherche to teche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="235" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1639">&para; And &yogh;ef &thorn;e man o&thorn;er &thorn;at wyf<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="60"></L>
<L>By cheaunce doumbe were,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef [me] may wyten hare assent</L>
<L N="1642">By soum o&thorn;er abere,</L>
<L>And deaue,
<PB REF="00000077.tif" N="59"></L>
<L>Hy mowe be wedded wel &yogh;eng<MILESTONE N="173b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1645">By holy cherche leue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="236" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1646">&para; Two manere speches be&thorn; iwoned</L>
<L>&THORN;er two men for to nomene,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;er two</I>, read <I>&THORN;er-to</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at one of &thorn;yng &thorn;at hys nou,</L>
<L N="1649">&THORN;at o&thorn;er of te comene,</L>
<L>Wel cou&thorn;e:</L>
<L>"Her ich &thorn;e take" wordes be&thorn;</L>
<L N="1652">Of &thorn;yng &thorn;at hijs nou&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="237" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1653">&para; And &yogh;ef me sey&thorn;e :&mdash;"ich wille &thorn;e haue,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-to treu&thorn;e ply&yogh;te,"</L>
<L>He speke&thorn; of &thorn;yng &thorn;at his to come,</L>
<L N="1656">&THORN;at scholde be myd ry&yogh;te</L>
<L>Of treu&thorn;e;</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;at ferste ne faylle&thorn; nau&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1659">&THORN;at o&thorn;er may for sleu&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="238" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1660">&para; And &yogh;yf an o&thorn;er treu&thorn;e&thorn; se&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">Between <I>treu&thorn;e&thorn;</I> and <I>se&thorn;e</I> there is a blank in MS.; <I>&thorn;e</I> in <I>se&thorn;e</I> is written in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wy&thorn; word of &thorn;at hys nou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ferste dede halte be&thorn;,</L>
<L N="1663">Ne be hy nase cou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>As none,<NOTE PLACE="foot">1662-64. See note.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bote &yogh;ef &thorn;er fol&yogh;ede &thorn;at treu&thorn;yng</L>
<L N="1666">A ferst flesch ymone.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>flesch ymone</I>, read <I>flesches ymone</I>, or <I>fleschlich ymone;</I> but cp. also p. 62, l. 1747.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="239" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1667">&para; For &thorn;et comple&thorn; &thorn;et spoushod<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="61"></L>
<L>After &thorn;e by-treu&thorn;yng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hyt ne may [nau&yogh;t] be ondon</L>
<L N="1670">Wy&thorn; none wy&thorn;-seggynge,</L>
<L>By ry&yogh;te;</L>
<L>And &thorn;a&yogh; hyt were her ondo,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;a&yogh;</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;at</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1673">Hy&yogh;t halt wy&thorn; oure dry&yogh;te.
<PB REF="00000078.tif" N="60"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="240" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1674">&para; And her may treu&thorn;yng be ondo</L>
<L>&THORN;orwe fal[s]nesse of partye,</L>
<L>And for de-faute of witnessyng,</L>
<L N="1677">Wy&thorn; wrang and trycherye;</L>
<L>I-lome</L>
<L>Me wedde&thorn; suyche, and ligge&thorn; so<MILESTONE N="174a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1680">For &thorn;an ine hordome.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Between <I>&thorn;an</I> and <I>ine</I> the space of two or three letters left empty in MS.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="241" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1681">&para; Ne hy&yogh;t ne may no man ondo</L>
<L>By lawe none kennes,</L>
<L>And so by-leue&thorn; euer-mo<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>by-leue&thorn;</I>, read <I>by-lef&thorn; hyt</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L N="1684">Fort o&thorn;er wende&thorn; hennes:</L>
<L>&THORN;on-wyse</L>
<L>So brynge&thorn; hem in suche peryl,</L>
<L N="1687">&THORN;at hy ne mowe aryse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="242" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1688">&para; Ac &yogh;ef eny hys ine &thorn;e cas,</L>
<L>Redich &thorn;at he be chaste;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf hys make mone craue&thorn;,</L>
<L N="1691">Ine leyser o&thorn;er in haste,</L>
<L>Lykynde,</L>
<L>He mo&yogh;t hy&yogh;t do wy&thorn; sorye mod</L>
<L N="1694">And&mdash;skyle wert&mdash;wepynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="243" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1695">&para; &YOGH;yt he mot gret penaunce do<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="62"></L>
<L>&THORN;e dayes of hys lyue,</L>
<L>And &yogh;et &thorn;e more, &yogh;ef [he] ha&thorn; maked</L>
<L N="1698">An hore of hys wyf[e],<NOTE PLACE="foot">The spelling <I>wyfe</I> [: <I>lyue</I>] occurs, p. 67, l. 1899.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at ere</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef &thorn;at he hedde y-wedded hy,</L>
<L N="1701">A goud wymman hyt were.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="244" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1702">&para; For suche la&yogh;e is &thorn;at manye be&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>be&thorn;</I>, read <I>be</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L>Men o&thorn;er wymmen of elde,
<PB REF="00000079.tif" N="61"></L>
<L>&THORN;ar suche contra&yogh;t y-maked hys,</L>
<L N="1705">&THORN;at mo&yogh;e ry&yogh;t proue &yogh;elde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mo&yogh;e</I>, MS. <I>more</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And scholle;</L>
<L>And &yogh;et of no lees &thorn;ane of tuo</L>
<L N="1708">Nys proue to &thorn;e folle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="245" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1709">&para; And &yogh;yf ry&yogh;t contract ys ymaked</L>
<L>Wy&yogh;&thorn;-oute wytnessynge,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef hy by-knowe&thorn; openlyche</L>
<L N="1712">By-fore men of trewynge,</L>
<L>Te take</L>
<L>To-gidere y-hoten scholle hy be,<MILESTONE N="174b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1715">&THORN;a&yogh; o&thorn;er eft for-sake.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;a&yogh;</I>, &yogh; altered, it seems, from <I>t</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="246" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1716">&para; &THORN;at hys, bote hy wedded be</L>
<L>To o&thorn;ren er hy hy&yogh;t by-knewe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>by-knewe</I>, MS. <I>byknowe</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;a&yogh; hy by-knowe hyt,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;a&yogh;</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;ar</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1719">Ne hys nau&yogh;t y-helde trewe</L>
<L>By lawe;</L>
<L>For &yogh;ef hy were, hyt scholde be</L>
<L N="1722">&THORN;ese spousebrechene sawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="247" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1723">&para; Of ham &thorn;at scholde ywedded be<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Of &thorn;at</I> (crossed out) <I>ham</I> &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP>.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="63"></L>
<L>Her &thorn;e age &thorn;ou my&yogh;t lerne:</L>
<L>&THORN;et knaue child for-tene &yogh;er<NOTE PLACE="marg">notabile</NOTE></L>
<L N="1726">Schel habbe, ane tuel &thorn;e &thorn;erne.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ane = and; tuel = tuelf;</I> same form, p. 129, l. 70.</NOTE></L>
<L>Spousynge</L>
<L>At seue &yogh;er me maky may,</L>
<L N="1729">Ac none ry&yogh;t weddynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="248" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1730">&para; For &thorn;e&yogh; hy were by assent</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t opelyche ywedded,</L>
<L>And, ase &thorn;yse childre ofte be&thorn;,</L>
<L N="1733">To-gadere ry&yogh;t y-bedded,</L>
<L>By ry&yogh;te,
<PB REF="00000080.tif" N="62"></L>
<L>Bote &yogh;ef hy &yogh;yue ine tyme assent,</L>
<L N="1736">Departed be y my&yogh;te.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>y = hy</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="249" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1737">&para; And &thorn;e tyme is, wane a&thorn;er can<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a&thorn;er = ay&thorn;er;</I> see note to p. 34, l. 961.</NOTE></L>
<L>O&thorn;er fleschlyche yknowe;</L>
<L>For wanne hy habbe&thorn; &thorn;et ydo,</L>
<L N="1740">Ne mowe hi be to-&thorn;rowe.</L>
<L>In sa&yogh;e</L>
<L>Hy be&thorn; icliped puberes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>puberes</I>, MS. <I>pukeres</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1743">&THORN;at hys a word of lawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="250" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1744">&para; Ne no treu&thorn;yng stonde ne schel</L>
<L>Wy&thorn; stren&thorn;e ymaked ine mone,</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;er fol&yogh;y by assent</L>
<L N="1747">Ry&yogh;t flesch y-mone<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>flesch</I>, read <I>fleschlich</I>? cf. p. 59, l. 1666.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ine dede;</L>
<L>For &thorn;et foluelle&thorn; &thorn;at spousho&thorn;,<MILESTONE N="175a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1750">As ich before sede.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>y</I> erased between <I>e</I> and <I>d</I> in <I>sede</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="251" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1751">&para; And &yogh;yf hy bo&thorn;e by assent<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="64"></L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;rydde treu&thorn;e leyde,</L>
<L>Her ey&thorn;er o&thorn;er for to haue,</L>
<L N="1754">O&thorn;er word to asenti seyde,</L>
<L>O&thorn;e[r] swore,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef hy soffre&thorn; hym mone of flesch,</L>
<L N="1757">Hys wyf and nau&yogh;t hys hore.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Hys = Hy is</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="252" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1758">&para; And &yogh;ef &thorn;er hys condicioun</L>
<L>Yset atter treu&thorn;ynge,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef hyt hys goud wy&thorn;-oute qued,</L>
<L N="1761">Hyt lette&thorn; &thorn;e weddynge</L>
<L>On-healde,</L>
<L>Bote &yogh;ef &thorn;er ulesches ymone be</L>
<L N="1764">Fol&yogh;ynde, ase ich ear tealde.
<PB REF="00000081.tif" N="63"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="253" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1765">&para; And hit is wykked condicioun,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>t</I> in <I>hit</I> possibly altered from original <I>s</I>; <I>is</I> added over the line by a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L>Couenaunt of schreawed-hede;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>schreawed-hede</I>, MS. <I>schrewead hede</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ase &yogh;ef he sey&thorn;:&mdash;"ich wille &thorn;e haue</L>
<L N="1768">&YOGH;ef &thorn;ou deist suche a dede</L>
<L>Of queade;"</L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; &thorn;et couenant be nau&yogh;t y-do,</L>
<L N="1771">Hy scholle hem weddy nede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="254" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1772">&para; Bote &thorn;at quead be a&yogh;eins spousho&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>spousho&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>spou&thorn;ho&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ase ich schel here teche:</L>
<L>And &yogh;ef man sey&thorn;:&mdash;"ich wolle &thorn;e haue</L>
<L N="1775">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou wilt be spousbreche,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er wealde<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wealde</I>, the <I>e</I> added over the <I>a</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For te destruwen oure stren,"</L>
<L N="1778">&THORN;at treu&thorn;yng darf nau&yogh;t healde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>d</I> in <I>darf</I> written on erasure in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="255" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1779">&para; Sudeakne mey be ywedded nau&yogh;t,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="65"></L>
<L>Monek, muneche, ne no frere,</L>
<L>Ne no man of religion,</L>
<L N="1782">Profes &yogh;ef &thorn;at he were</L>
<L>To leste:</L>
<L>Of chaste[te] professioun<MILESTONE N="175b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1785">Hys solempne by-heste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="256" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1786">&para; Ac &yogh;ef man of religion</L>
<L>Be hys ryt fre wille</L>
<L>Ouer tyme of professioun<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>professioun</I>, read <I>probacioun;</I> see note.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1789">Helde&thorn; hym &thorn;rynne stylle,</L>
<L>Relessed</L>
<L>Schel hym nau&yogh;t be religioun,</L>
<L N="1792">&THORN;a&yogh; he be nau&yogh;t professed.
<PB REF="00000082.tif" N="64"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="257" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1793">&para; Ac &yogh;ef &thorn;er were ry&yogh;t treu&thorn;yng</L>
<L>&THORN;at may nau&yogh;t be relessed,</L>
<L>Ere hye in-to suche ordre came,</L>
<L N="1796">And here hi be professed,</L>
<L>To so&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Hy scholde a&yogh;en to &thorn;e spousyng,</L>
<L N="1799">And lete al &thorn;at to no&thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to no&thorn;e</I> added by a later hand.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="258" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1800">&para; Hye &thorn;at &thorn;e man for-leyen he&thorn;e</L>
<L>Vnder hys ry&yogh;t[e] wyf[e],</L>
<L>O&thorn;er &yogh;yf hy hosebonde he&thorn;</L>
<L N="1803">Ine &thorn;et spousbreche alyue,</L>
<L>Bi dome,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Bi</I>, MS. <I>Si</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;et hi my&yogh;te be wedded eft,</L>
<L N="1806">&YOGH;ef hy sengle by-come.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="259" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1807">&para; Bote &yogh;ef hy by-treu&thorn;ede hem<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="66"></L>
<L>Wy&thorn; worde of nou&thorn;e itake,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nou&thorn;e, u</I> written over <I>o</I> in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L>O&thorn;er bote hy by-speke his de&thorn;e</L>
<L N="1810">In hare senuolle sake,</L>
<L>To sla&yogh;e;</L>
<L>For &thorn;anne scholde hy weddi nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1813">By none ry&yogh;t[e] lawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="260" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1814">&para; Meseles mowe y-wedded be,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>mowe &thorn;a</I>, the latter underdotted.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;ef hi asenti wylle,</L>
<L>An, &thorn;a&yogh; o&thorn;er bicome mesel,</L>
<L N="1817">To-gadere healde hem stylle;</L>
<L>To nomene,</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;e treu&thorn;inge bare be<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>treu&thorn;inge</I>, MS. <I>treu&thorn;ege</I>, the second <I>e</I> on erasure; <I>ge</I> added by a later hand.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="176a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1820">Wy&thorn; wordes of to comene.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I> on erasure in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="261" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1821">&para; For &yogh;ef &thorn;et hy by-treu&thorn;ed be</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; worde of nou ytake,
<PB REF="00000083.tif" N="65"></L>
<L>O&thorn;er wyd wordes of to come,</L>
<L N="1824">Wi&thorn; dede of flesches sake,</L>
<L>&THORN;er, bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L>Scel be renoueled &thorn;et a-gonne hijs,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>re</I> in <I>renoueled</I> (which may as well be read <I>uoueled</I>) above the line in a later hand. I suppose the original reading to have been <I>uolueld</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1827">And ay&thorn;er fol&yogh;y o&thorn;er.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="262" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1828">&para; Bote &thorn;e syke in-to a spytel hous</L>
<L>Entry, &thorn;er be&thorn; museles,</L>
<L>&THORN;anne der &thorn;e hole nau&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1831">&THORN;er-ine folwy hijs meles,</L>
<L>Ne hijs gyfte;<NOTE PLACE="foot">1831-2. See note.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fal&thorn;e ham nau&yogh;t in such compaigni</L>
<L N="1834">To-gadere be any&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="263" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1835">&para; And ine &thorn;e weddynge ne gaynet nou&yogh;t<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="67"></L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; &thorn;on &thorn;e o&thorn;er by-swyke,</L>
<L>Wanne &thorn;on wene&thorn; &thorn;e o&thorn;er be hol,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;on</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;em</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1838">And wedded &thorn;ane syke,</L>
<L>Ne-tinde :</L>
<L>Ne be&thorn; no &thorn;ynges bote two</L>
<L N="1841">&THORN;at oundo&thorn; &thorn;e weddyng :<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>oundo&thorn;</I>, MS. -<I>de&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="264" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1842">&para; &THORN;at on hys, wanne he wedde&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;ral,</L>
<L>And wene&thorn; &thorn;e frye take;</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er, wanne he wedde&thorn; one o&thorn;er</L>
<L N="1845">&THORN;ane hys ry&yogh;te make,</L>
<L>By-gyled :</L>
<L>&THORN;e lawe of god ne sente&thorn; nou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1848">&THORN;at man be so by-wyled.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="265" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1849">&para; And &yogh;yf &thorn;et one wedde&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;ral,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&yogh;yf one</I> (underdotted) <I>&thorn;et one</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wene&thorn; &thorn;e frye weddy;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf a spyet &thorn;at so&thorn;e &thorn;rof,</L>
<L N="1852">And wonde&thorn; nau&yogh;t to beddy</L>
<L>Ine mone,
<PB REF="00000084.tif" N="66"></L>
<L>&YOGH;ef he by wyl serue&thorn; &thorn;at flesch,<MILESTONE N="176b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1855">Ry&yogh;t partyng worthe hym none.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="266" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1856">&para; And &yogh;yf &thorn;y wyf hebbe&thorn; a child,</L>
<L>Wane &thorn;ou he hest for-leye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he=hy</I>, accus. fem.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne my&yogh;t [&thorn;ou] nau&yogh;t weddy &thorn;at childe<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota [<I>later</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L N="1859">Eft, &thorn;a&yogh; &thorn;at &thorn;y wyf deye,</L>
<L>By lawe;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>By</I>, MS. <I>Sy</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne for&thorn;e &thorn;e moder &thorn;et hyt beer,</L>
<L N="1862">Ne woldest &thorn;ou nase y-fa&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="267" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1863">&para; And &yogh;yf &thorn;ou hebbest so a child,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="68"></L>
<L>&THORN;e lawe y-wryte hyt sede,</L>
<L>&THORN;y wyf, &thorn;at his &thorn;yn o&yogh;e flesch,</L>
<L N="1866">Dra&yogh;e&thorn; eke &thorn;e godesybred[e],</L>
<L>Y-mete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hy ne may weddy &thorn;at child,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>.n. = nota</I>: this and the others are later.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1869">Ne fade[r] &thorn;et hyt bi&yogh;ete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="268" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1870">&para; &THORN;et ilke &thorn;at y-crystned hys</L>
<L>Ne may weddy by la&yogh;e</L>
<L>Him &thorn;at hym crystne&thorn;, ne hys child,</L>
<L N="1873">Ne wolde nase ua&yogh;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wolde = wolde he</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac lete,</L>
<L>And eke hem &thorn;at hym hebbe&thorn; so,<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota [<I>later</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L N="1876">And alle hare bi&yogh;ete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="269" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1877">&para; And for&thorn;e, fader and moder<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>for &thorn;e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at hyne fleschlyche for&thorn; wyse&thorn;</L>
<L>Gostlyche for hym by-sebbe be&thorn;</L>
<L N="1880">To ham &thorn;at hine bapti&yogh;e&thorn;;</L>
<L>And heuen</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore, &thorn;a&yogh; hy ham wedded eft,<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1883">Ne myt[e hy] so by-leuen.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="270" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1884">&para; And ase &thorn;e gossybrede dra&yogh;&thorn;</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t to ous after crystnynge,
<PB REF="00000085.tif" N="67"></L>
<L>So gossibrede dra&yogh;e&thorn; ek</L>
<L N="1887">Ry&yogh;t after confermynge</L>
<L>By lawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at so ne mo&yogh;e hy weddy nau&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="177a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1890">Ne wolde hy nase y-ua&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="271" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1891">&para; More godsibrede nys &thorn;er nau&yogh;t<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="69"></L>
<L>&THORN;ane hys y-mene&yogh;ed here,</L>
<L>Godfader wedded godsones child</L>
<L N="1894">Fol wel, my leue fere;<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L>No senne</L>
<L>Ne&thorn; man and wyf &thorn;at wedde&thorn; ham,</L>
<L N="1897">Godfader &thorn;e&yogh; he habbe enne.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he = hy</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="272" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1898">&para; And &yogh;yf a man hebbe&thorn; &thorn;y child,</L>
<L>And nau&yogh;t bye &thorn;yne wyfe,</L>
<L>&THORN;y wyf may weddy &thorn;ane man</L>
<L N="1901">Wel after &thorn;yne lyue,<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L>And libbe;</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at cas &thorn;ou my&yogh;t weddy</L>
<L N="1904">To &thorn;yne wyfes gossibbe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="273" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1905">&para; And [&thorn;a&yogh;] &thorn;at lawe for-bede nau&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for-bede</I>, MS. <I>for-bode</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at man and wyf ymene</L>
<L>Toe-hebbe a child, &yogh;et scholdy nau&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>scholdy = scholde hy</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1908">Honestete so &yogh;wene,</L>
<L>Ne wette</L>
<L>Schrewede tonge for te speke,</L>
<L N="1911">For sclaunder me schal lette.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="274" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1912">&para; &THORN;e sibbe mowe to-gadere nau&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;e foer&thorn;e grees wy&thorn;-inne;</L>
<L>Ne me ne scholde telle &thorn;e stok,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>scholde</I>, MS. <I>scholle</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1915">Ac after hym by-ginne<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;at.&mdash;by-ginne</I>, MS. <I>bygenne;</I> see note.</NOTE></L>
<L>To telle;
<PB REF="00000086.tif" N="68"></L>
<L>And &yogh;ef o&thorn;er &thorn;e fifte of-take&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fifte</I>, MS. <I>fixte</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1918">To-gare mo&yogh;e hy dwelle.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>To-gare = to-gadere.&mdash;mo&yogh;e</I>, MS. <I>more:</I></NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="275" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1919">&para; &YOGH;ef &thorn;ou myd word of &thorn;et hys nov&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I>, MS. <I>if.&mdash;v&thorn;e</I> in <I>nov&thorn;e</I> in a later hand.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="70"></L>
<L>Ary&yogh;t bi-treu&thorn;est one&mdash;</L>
<L>O&thorn;er &thorn;a&yogh; &thorn;et [&thorn;ou] bi-treu&thorn;y hy nau&yogh;t&mdash;</L>
<L N="1922">And hast flesches mone,</L>
<L>By lawe</L>
<L>Alle here sybbe affinite<MILESTONE N="177b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1925">To &thorn;e for &thorn;an schel drawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="276" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1926">&para; And &thorn;et ine &thorn;e selue degre</L>
<L>&THORN;at hy be&thorn; here by-sybbe;</L>
<L>And &yogh;ef &thorn;ou weddest eny of ham.</L>
<L N="1929">In inceste scholle &yogh;e lybbe<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota bene [<I>later</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>An er&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef hy ysibbe ine degres</L>
<L N="1932">Ry&yogh;t wy&thorn;-inne &thorn;e fer&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="277" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1933">&para; And so drawy&thorn; hy affinite</L>
<L>Wy&thorn; alle &thorn;yne sibbe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Wy&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>Wyl</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ase &thorn;ou of hire sibben dra&yogh;st</L>
<L N="1936">For &thorn;an, &thorn;a&yogh; hy ne libbe;</L>
<L>Wat de&thorn; hy&yogh;t?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>de&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>do&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hyt de&thorn; &thorn;e Inonynge ine flesch,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Inonynge</I>, probably altered from <I>no&thorn;ynge;</I> but see note.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1939">&THORN;e&yogh; non ne wyte ne se hy&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="278" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1940">&para; And holy cherche y-hote he&thorn;,</L>
<L>Me schal maky &thorn;e cryes</L>
<L>At cherche oppe holy day&yogh;es &thorn;re</L>
<L N="1943">By-fore &thorn;e poeple &thorn;ryes,</L>
<L>To assaye,</L>
<L>To sech contrait &yogh;ef me mey</L>
<L N="1946">Of destorber a-uaye.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Of</I>, MS. <I>Ef</I>.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000087.tif" N="69"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="279" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1947">&para; For, er&thorn;e &thorn;e banes [be] y-gred,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>er&thorn;e</I> = O.E. <I>&aelig;&macr;r &thorn;an</I>.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="71"></L>
<L>He &thorn;at &thorn;e treu&thorn;e make&thorn;</L>
<L>Far&thorn; ase he &thorn;at great work by-gun&thorn;,</L>
<L N="1950">And &thorn;anne conseil take&thorn;,</L>
<L>And teyle&thorn;;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>y</I> in <I>teyle&thorn;</I> hardly distinguishable from &thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac mani man &thorn;at so by-gun&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1953">Wy&thorn; grete harme fayle&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="280" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1954">&para; And &thorn;a&yogh; &thorn;e weddyng were maked</L>
<L>Ase hyt mytte by lawe,</L>
<L>&YOGH;et hyt my&yogh;te eft be ondo,</L>
<L N="1957">And eft al-so to-drawe.</L>
<L>Wet wyse?</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef &thorn;er ne mey no&thorn;ere kendelyche<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;er ne</I> over the line in a later hand; <I>no&thorn;ere</I> altered from <I>neuere</I>. The original reading was probably&mdash;<I>&yogh;ef me mey neuere kendelyche</I>, etc.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="178a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1960">Do &thorn;e flesches seruyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="281" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1961">&para; &THORN;et hys, &yogh;ef &thorn;at ere &thorn;e weddynge</L>
<L>Folle &thorn;at ylke lette,</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er were so ilet,</L>
<L N="1964">To do &thorn;e flesches dette<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L>By kende;</L>
<L>For &yogh;ef &thorn;at lettyng velle se&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="1967">Ne scholde hy nou&yogh;t to-wende.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="282" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1968">&para; And &thorn;a&yogh; &thorn;et on bi-wichched be</L>
<L>&THORN;anne hy to-gadere come,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hy ne my&yogh;te don ry&yogh;t nau&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1971">Ne a-sayde [hy] nase lome,<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wolde:</L>
<L>&YOGH;et &thorn;re &yogh;ier hy abyde scholde,</L>
<L N="1974">To-do ere hi be scholde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="283" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1975">&para; And &thorn;a&yogh; &thorn;at seruyse be foul,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="72"></L>
<L>&YOGH;et hyt hys tokne of gode;
<PB REF="00000088.tif" N="70"></L>
<L>For hy&yogh;t by-tokne&thorn; &thorn;e takyng</L>
<L N="1978">Of oure flesch and blode<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota [<I>later</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>Ine cryst[e]:</L>
<L>No stren may non encressy<NOTE PLACE="foot">Read <I>No stren ne may encressy nou?</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="1981">Wy&thorn;-oute flesches loste.<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="284" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1982">&para; And dette hy&yogh;t hys in spousod,</L>
<L>Wanne &thorn;e o&thorn;er hy&yogh;t wolde;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wolde</I>, MS. <I>welde</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &yogh;yf hyt &thorn;o&thorn;er nolde do,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hyt &thorn;o&thorn;er</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;yt o&thorn;er</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1985">Destrayned be he scholde<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L>By rytte</L>
<L>To do hyt, &yogh;yf &thorn;at he may:</L>
<L N="1988">&THORN;e lawe he&thorn; seche my&yogh;te.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>seche</I> (such), MS. <I>&thorn;ehe</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="285" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1989">&para; And &thorn;a&yogh; man habbe bysemer</L>
<L>Of seche manere destresse,</L>
<L>Be hem wel syker, hyt hys ydo</L>
<L N="1992">For wel grete godnesse</L>
<L>Of lyue;</L>
<L>For elles nolde &thorn;e la&yogh;e nau&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I> added over the line by a later hand.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="178b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1995">Of suche &thorn;ynge schryue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="286" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1996">&para; In spoushod be&thorn; godnesse &thorn;re,</L>
<L>Treu&thorn;e, streny[n]g, and signe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">A dot before <I>strenyg</I> and after it in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Treu&thorn;e hys, &thorn;at &thorn;er no gile be</L>
<L N="1999">&THORN;ourwe spousebreche maligne;</L>
<L>Ac, bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L>&THORN;at on may spousbreche by-come<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2002">For de-faute of &thorn;et o&thorn;er.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="287" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2003">&para; &THORN;at o&thorn;er godnesse hys strenyng,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="73"></L>
<L>&THORN;er me may children wene;</L>
<L>Ac &yogh;yf &thorn;at on &thorn;o&thorn;ren warne&thorn; hys flesch,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dot before and after <I>flesch</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2006">Ne my&yogh;t[e] hy naut strene:<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L>On-nette
<PB REF="00000089.tif" N="71"></L>
<L>&THORN;o scholde &thorn;at godnesse be<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;o</I>, MS. <I>s&thorn;o</I> (evidently meant for <I>so</I>), the <I>s</I> added by a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2009">By-twene ham in lette.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in lette</I>, MS. <I>inlette</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="288" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2010">&para; &THORN;e &thorn;rydde godnesse hys sacrament,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hijs &thorn;e holy signe</L>
<L>Of the ioynyng of god self</L>
<L N="2013">And holye cherche digne,<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at avayle&thorn;;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>avayle&thorn;:</I> the original reading seems to have been <I>fayle&thorn;</I>, which was corrected by a later hand to <I>abayle&thorn;</I>, or, as I should read it, <I>avayle&thorn;</I>. The metre requires <I>vayle&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;yf [&thorn;on] &thorn;o&thorn;ren warn&thorn; hys flesch,</L>
<L N="2016">&THORN;at sacrement hem fayle&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="289" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2017">&para; By &thorn;yse &thorn;re hy mo&yogh;e ise</L>
<L>Wanne hy ine flesche sene&yogh;e&thorn;,</L>
<L>Wanne hy wy&thorn;-oute &thorn;yse &thorn;re</L>
<L N="2020">Wy&thorn; fleschlich mone me[n]ge&thorn;:<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L>hare o&thorn;er,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>hare o&thorn;er o&thorn;er</I>, the first <I>o&thorn;er</I> above the line in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e more hy hyt do&thorn;, &thorn;e wors hi be&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hy hyt</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;yt;</I> cf. 2024.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2023">And god al-so &thorn;e lo&thorn;er.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="290" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2024">&para; Ase &yogh;ef hy hy&yogh;t my&yogh;te wel a-come</L>
<L>To letten o&thorn;er wyle,</L>
<L>And lesse do hyt &thorn;ane hy do&thorn;,</L>
<L N="2027">Wy&thorn;-oute o&thorn;eres peryl[e],<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac blonde&thorn;,</L>
<L>And&mdash;nys n&omacr; ned&mdash;wy&thorn; foule handlyng<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>n&omacr;</I> above the line.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="179a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2030">O&thorn;er o&thorn;er afonde&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="291" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2031">&para; Ne hy ne wonde&thorn; messeday,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="74"></L>
<L>Ne none holy tyde,</L>
<L>Ne holy stede, wy&thorn;-oute peryl</L>
<L N="2034">&THORN;a&yogh; hy my&yogh;te abyde;<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L>Spy, fel&thorn;e!</L>
<L>&THORN;er hy my&yogh;te hyt do kendelyche,</L>
<L N="2037">On-kende hys hare onselthe.
<PB REF="00000090.tif" N="72"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="292" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2038">&para; Hyt nys nau&yogh;t a&yogh;ens sacrement</L>
<L>Of god and holy cherche,</L>
<L>&THORN;ay hy nolde by goud purpos<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ay = &thorn;a&yogh;.&mdash;d</I> in <I>goud</I> and <I>r</I> (above the line) in <I>purpos</I> in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2041">Ine hare flesche werche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>werche</I>, MS. <I>worche</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>By-feld;</L>
<L>So ferde marye and ioseph,<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2044">By assent &thorn;at clene hem held.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="293" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2045">&para; For &thorn;ey hye wolde [by assent]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ey = &thorn;a&yogh;</I>. The line is too short. I have added <I>by assent</I> (cp. ll. 2044, 2053), which yields the two wanting stress syllables.</NOTE></L>
<L>In flesch by-leue clene,</L>
<L>&YOGH;et a&yogh;eyns treu&thorn;e nere hyt nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="2048">Ne for&thorn;e a&yogh;eyns strene.</L>
<L>Hou scholde hy&yogh;t</L>
<L>A&yogh;e gode purpos of strene [be],<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2051">Bote o&thorn;er of ham wolde hy&yogh;t?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="294" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2052">&para; Ne hy&yogh;t nys a&yogh;eyns sacrement</L>
<L>By assent &thorn;a&yogh; hy be clene</L>
<L>In spousho&thorn;, &yogh;ef hy louie&thorn; hem,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>louie&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>leuies</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2055">And wel libbe&thorn; imene;<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wytnesse</L>
<L>Cryst and &thorn;ys holy saulen eke,</L>
<L N="2058">Al louie&thorn; hem ine clannesse.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>louie&thorn;</I>, the <I>u</I> altered to <I>w</I> by a later hand.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="295" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2059">&para; And &yogh;yf bo&thorn;e be&thorn; of god wylle,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="75"></L>
<L>And of assent at emne,</L>
<L>To take to religion<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2062">And makye a vou solempne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I> between <I>makye</I> and <I>vou</I> inserted by a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hy mytte</L>
<L>In chastyte for euere mo<MILESTONE N="179b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2065">Seruy oure drytte.
<PB REF="00000091.tif" N="73"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="296" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2066">&para; And &yogh;ef &thorn;at ey&thorn;er o&thorn;er may</L>
<L>Kendelyche serue,</L>
<L>Ne mo&yogh;en hy a&yogh;eins wyl to-go,</L>
<L N="2069">Er &thorn;ane o&thorn;er schal sterue;<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L>No sauue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>No sauue</I>, read <I>To saue?</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Bote &yogh;ef &thorn;at on for-houred be,</L>
<L N="2072">He may de-partyng haue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="297" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2073">&para; And &yogh;ef hy so departed be,</L>
<L>Chastite he mote take,</L>
<L>So longe ase &thorn;o&thorn;res lyf ylest</L>
<L N="2076">&THORN;at whas hys ry&yogh;t[e] make;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>whas = was</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nyst gabbe,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef he o&thorn;er &thorn;ane hy for-ly&thorn;,</L>
<L N="2079">A&yogh;en a schel hys habbe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="298" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2080">&para; &THORN;a&yogh; hy mysdede, &yogh;et, and he wyle,</L>
<L>Eft a&yogh;eyn he may craue,</L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; &thorn;er such a departyng be,</L>
<L N="2083">And hijs wyf a&yogh;eyn haue,</L>
<L>And scholde;</L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; hy wy&thorn;-seyde hyt openlyche,<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2086">And a&yogh;eyn come nolde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="299" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2087">&para; Ac vnder-stond for &thorn;et hordom<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="76"></L>
<L>&THORN;at make&thorn; &thorn;es to stryue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at eche hordom ne parte&thorn; nau&yogh;t</L>
<L N="2090">&THORN;e man al fram hys wyf[e].<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>man</I>, MS. <I>mani</I> or <I>mam</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nou lestne :</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef &thorn;e o&thorn;er o&thorn;ren so by-swyke&thorn;,</L>
<L N="2093">No mo&yogh;e hy nou&yogh;t onuestne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="300" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2094">&para; Ne &thorn;a&yogh; a wyf by-gyled be</L>
<L>Of an o&thorn;er by wrake,</L>
<L>And wene&thorn; wel to for-leye be<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2097">Of hyre ry&yogh;tte make;</L>
<L>&YOGH;et more,
<PB REF="00000092.tif" N="74"></L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; hy be streng&thorn;e be for-leye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>be</I>, MS. <I>ben</I>.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="180a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2100">Tak&thorn; he nau&yogh;t houre lore.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he = hy</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="301" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2101">&para; Ne &yogh;ef &thorn;on &thorn;o&thorn;er profre&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>profre&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>proofre&thorn;</I>? for <I>profere&thorn;</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L>Wy&thorn; any o&thorn;er to beddy;</L>
<L>Ne &yogh;ef &thorn;on wen&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;res de&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ne</I> crossed out; the abbreviation for <I>and</I> written in the margin; <I>e</I> written over the <I>o</I> in <I>&thorn;on; wen&thorn;</I> altered to <I>welni&thorn;</I> (the <I>l</I> inserted, the <I>i</I> written over the line): all by a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2104">And he ano&thorn;er weddy:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>weddy</I> (subj.), MS. <I>wedde&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; come</L>
<L>&THORN;e make a&yogh;en, ne schelde hy be<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2107">To-do for hordome.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="302" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2108">&para; Ac &yogh;et, nou ounderstand for ham<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;et</I>, MS. <I>het</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at goo&thorn; a pylgrymage:</L>
<L>On w&emacr;dde&thorn;, &thorn;o&thorn;er abyde schel<NOTE PLACE="foot">After <I>On</I> a letter erased; <I>e</I> over the <I>o</I> in <I>&thorn;o&thorn;er, &thorn;er</I> (<I>er</I> abbreviated) on erasure in a later hand. See note.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2111">Wet o&thorn;er passe&thorn; age<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L>By kende,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er wat &thorn;at &thorn;er be of hys dea&thorn;</L>
<L N="2114">Ry&yogh;t god and certayn mende.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="303" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2115">&para; And &yogh;yf [&thorn;e] man halt ase hys wyf<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="77"></L>
<L>After &thorn;e gelt hys spouse,</L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; he by hyre ne ligge nou&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="marg">notabile [<I>later</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L N="2118">O&thorn;er halt hys ine hys house,</L>
<L>In tome,</L>
<L>Ne schal hy nau&yogh;t de-parted be</L>
<L N="2121">Fram hym for hordome.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="304" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2122">&para; &THORN;e signe hys of &thorn;e sacrement</L>
<L>&THORN;e treu&thorn;ynge wel cou&thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wel</I> on erasure.</NOTE></L>
<L>O&thorn;er cou&thorn;e signe of &thorn;et asent,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cou&thorn;e</I>, MS. <I>c&omacr;&thorn;ey</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2125">Wy&thorn; worde [of] &thorn;at hijs nou&thorn;e;<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L>And dygne
<PB REF="00000093.tif" N="75"></L>
<L>&THORN;ynges &thorn;er be&thorn; her mo &thorn;an on,</L>
<L N="2128">Onder &thorn;ys ylke signe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="305" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2129">&para; &THORN;et o &thorn;yng hys &thorn;et hol assent</L>
<L>By-tuixte man an wyf[e],</L>
<L>Wat byndi[n]g hys of &thorn;e spouseho&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>byndig</I> for the most part on erasure, in a different hand.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2132">To helde to ende of lyf[e];</L>
<L>And, bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L>&THORN;ys ilke &thorn;yng a signe hys eke<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dot after <I>&thorn;yng</I>.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="180b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2135">Of &thorn;yng to-forin an-o&thorn;er.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to fo</I> in a later hand on erasure, only <I>rin</I> original, but the last stroke of the <I>n</I> half erased, and after it an erasure of one or two letters. Was the original reading perhaps <I>&thorn;er-inne</I>?</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="306" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2136">&para; And &thorn;at &thorn;yng hys, as ich seyde her,</L>
<L>&THORN;o ich her-an gan werche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>werche</I>, MS. <I>worche</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e holy ioynyng of godself<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2139">And of al holy cherche;</L>
<L>In tome</L>
<L>Of spou[s]ho&thorn; &thorn;ys aueyement<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>aueye</I> . ., second <I>e</I> over line.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2142">Louke&thorn; &yogh;ou for hordome.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;ou</I> written in the margin.&mdash;<I>for</I>, read <I>fram</I>?</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="part">
<LG N="307" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2143">&THORN;O seynt Iohan in &thorn;e apokalips<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="78"></L>
<L>Se&yogh; priuetes of heuene,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>priuetes</I>, MS. <I>pruietes</I>, the <I>i</I>-stroke put in the wrong place.</NOTE></L>
<L>He se&yogh; a bok was fast ischet</L>
<L N="2146">Wy&thorn; strong[e] lokes seuene;</L>
<L>A wonder!</L>
<L>Ne my&yogh;te hy no man ondo<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>my&yogh;te</I>, MS. <I>my&yogh;ty</I> (i. e. <I>my&yogh;te hy</I>), <I>hy</I> written in the margin, in another hand.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2149">Aboue in heuene and onder.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="308" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2150">&para; And &thorn;o &thorn;at seint iohan y-se&yogh; &thorn;at,</L>
<L>Wel sore he gan to wepe;</L>
<L>&THORN;o seyde an angel:&mdash;"wep &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="2153">Ac take wel gode kepe:<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ys sygne
<PB REF="00000094.tif" N="76"></L>
<L>&THORN;at holy lambe &thorn;at sla&yogh;en hys</L>
<L N="2156">To ondo hyt hys wel dygne."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="309" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2157">&para; &THORN;ys ylke bok &thorn;e mistyk ys</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ese sacrementis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at were ischet fram alle men,</L>
<L N="2160">Wat god hymself out sent hys</L>
<L>To tounne;</L>
<L>For, be &thorn;ou syker, hy were in god,<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2163">Er &thorn;an &thorn;e wordle by-gounne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="310" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2164">&para; For ase he wyste wel [yno&yogh;]<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wel</I> [<I>yno&yogh;</I>], cf. p. 150, l. 586.</NOTE></L>
<L>We scholde be by-gyled,</L>
<L>So euer wyste he &thorn;at &thorn;e feend</L>
<L N="2167">Scholde a&yogh;en be by-wyled</L>
<L>&THORN;or&yogh; cryste;</L>
<L>Ac he hyt hadde wel priue<MILESTONE N="181a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2170">For saternases lyste;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="311" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2171">&para; Al what os com &thorn;et ilke lambe,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="79"></L>
<L>Ihesus, &thorn;at was y-slawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at onne-schette &thorn;e queynte loken</L>
<L N="2174">&THORN;at spek of &thorn;e alde lawe,<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seuene</L>
<L>So kedde out &thorn;yse sacremens,</L>
<L N="2177">By-ne&thorn;e and boue in heuene.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="312" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2178">&para; &THORN;e ferste loke onleke ihesus,</L>
<L>Ase he wel coude and my&yogh;te,</L>
<L>&THORN;o nychodemus to hym come<NOTE PLACE="marg">notabile [<I>later</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L N="2181">At one tyme by ny&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L>To lerny,</L>
<L>And he ondede hym cristendom:</L>
<L N="2184">No leng he nolde hyt derny.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="313" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2185">&para; &THORN;at lok [he] on-leak of confermyng</L>
<L>&THORN;er hijs apostles leye
<PB REF="00000095.tif" N="77"></L>
<L>Slepynde, &thorn;o &thorn;at he ham bed<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he</I> above the line in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2188">Aryse for to preye</L>
<L>Amonge,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hy ne uolle into fondyng,<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2191">Ac &thorn;at hye weren stronge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="314" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2192">&para; &THORN;e &thorn;rydde loke on-leke ihesus</L>
<L>&THORN;er he set atte sopere,</L>
<L>&THORN;o he sacrede hys flesch and blod,</L>
<L N="2195">Ase ich &yogh;ou seyde hyt here,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>here</I> = <I>ere</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>So holde,</L>
<L>In fourme of bred and eke of wyn,<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2198">&THORN;at we hyt notye scholde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="315" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2199">&para; And &thorn;o peter in ore ny&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ore</I>, O.E. <I>&amacr;(n)re</I>, MS. <I>o&yogh;e</I>.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="80"></L>
<L>&THORN;ryes hedde hyne for-sake,</L>
<L>And he by-held hyne &thorn;er a set,</L>
<L N="2202">Ry&yogh;t atte hys pynyng stake,</L>
<L>Nem kepe,</L>
<L>&THORN;er he on-leke penaunce loke,<MILESTONE N="181b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2205">&THORN;o peter gan to wepe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>vor to, vor</I> over the line in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="316" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2206">&para; &THORN;e fyfte, &thorn;at hys Elyynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fyfte</I>, MS. <I>fy&yogh;te</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Cryst on-leke to oure wayne,</L>
<L>&THORN;o hand and fet and al hys lymes<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fet</I> or <I>fot</I> in MS.?</NOTE></L>
<L N="2209">I-persed were ine payne<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L>One-helede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>One-helede</I>, unhealed; the <I>O</I> looks almost like <I>E</I> in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>For al &thorn;e sennes of oure lemes :</L>
<L N="2212">Anon so be we anelede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="317" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2213">&para; &THORN;e syxte on-leke swete ihesus,</L>
<L>Of ordre no&thorn;yng orne,</L>
<L>&THORN;o he a-ueng for oure loue</L>
<L N="2216">&THORN;e croune of scharpe &thorn;ornes;<NOTE PLACE="marg">notabile [<I>later</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel wyde
<PB REF="00000096.tif" N="78"></L>
<L>Ondede &thorn;e lok of ry&yogh;t spousyng</L>
<L N="2219">&THORN;e wounde onder hys syde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="318" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2220">&para; For ase wymman com of &thorn;e ryb</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e mannes ry&yogh;t syde,</L>
<L>So holyche[rche], spouse of god,</L>
<L N="2223">Sprang of &thorn;ane wonden wyde;<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota [<I>later</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>Nou leste</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;at was hed conseyl ine god</L>
<L N="2226">Sprounge hijs out at hys brest[e].</L>
</LG>
<LG N="319" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2227">&para; Nou, lord, &thorn;at coudest maky open<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="81"></L>
<L>&THORN;et no man coude ounschette,</L>
<L>And canste wel schetten &thorn;et hy[s] open,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;et hy be open, be</I> over the line in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2230">&THORN;at none o&thorn;er can dette,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>can dette</I>, MS. <I>man derte</I>.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L>To hopye</L>
<L>So graunte ous &thorn;yne sacremens,</L>
<L N="2233">&THORN;at non errour ne (ous) a-scapye;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>ous</I> above the line in a later hand. See note.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="320" TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2234">&para; And &thorn;at we hys mote aredy haue,</L>
<L>Lord, her at oure nede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no deue&yogh;l ne a-combry ous,</L>
<L N="2237">Lord, &thorn;ou hy&yogh;t ham for-bede<NOTE PLACE="marg">.n.</NOTE></L>
<L>Amonge;</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e tokene &thorn;at we neme,<MILESTONE N="182a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2240">Lat ouse &thorn;y dole fonge. AMEN.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>holy</I> written in the margin by a later hand, and marked for inser|tion before <I>dole</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<TRAILER>Oretis pro anima domini Willelmi de Schor|ham, quondam vicarii de chart, iuxta Ledes. Qui composuit istam compila|tionem de septem sacramentis.</TRAILER>


</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="2" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000097.tif" N="79">
<HEAD>II. Pater noster. Domine labia mea aperies, Etc'.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>on leaf</I> 182]</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="82"></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Ou opene myne lyppen, Lord,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. l. 17.</NOTE></L>
<L>Let fel&thorn;e of senne out-wende,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>out-wende</I> in a later hand on erasure.</NOTE></L>
<L>And my mou&thorn;e, wy&thorn; wel god accord<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>g</I> in <I>god</I> half erased.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4">Schel &thorn;yne worschypyng sende.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>yng sende</I> in a later hand on erasure.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<P>&para; Deus, in adiutorium meum intende!</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>[G]ode atende to my socour,<MILESTONE N="182b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ps. lxix. 2.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lord, hy&yogh;e, and help me fy&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Glorye to &thorn;e fader and sone,</L>
<L N="8">And to &thorn;e gost of my&yogh;tte;</L>
<L>Ase hyt was ferst, and hijs, and schal<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and schal</I> in MS. at the beginning of the next line.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10">Euere more be wy&thorn; ry&yogh;tte.<NOTE PLACE="foot">5-10. In the MS., as well as in Wright's edition, these lines are inserted in the wrong place, between ll. 26 and 27.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza"><HEAD>[Hora matutina].</HEAD>
<L>UAderis wyt of heue[ne] an he&yogh;,<MILESTONE N="182a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So&thorn;nesse of oure dry&yogh;te,</L>
<L>God and man y-take was<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>y-take, y</I> above the line.</NOTE></L>
<L N="14">At matyn-tyde by ny&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&THORN;e disciples &thorn;at were his,</L>
<L>Anone hy hyne for-soke;</L>
<L>I-seld to gywes, and by-traid,</L>
<L N="18">To pyne hyne toke.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Read <I>hy hyne</I>?</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<P>ADoramus te, christe, et benediscimus tibi, &amp;c'.</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; We &thorn;e honre&thorn;, ihesu cryst,</L>
<L>And blesse&thorn;, ase &thorn;ou os tou&yogh;test;</L>
<L>For &thorn;our&yogh; &thorn;y crouche and passion</L>
<L N="22">&THORN;ys wordle &thorn;ou for-bou&yogh;test.
<PB REF="00000098.tif" N="80"></L>
</LG>
<P>Oremus, Domine ihesu <I>christe</I>.<MILESTONE N="182b" UNIT="folio"></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>We &thorn;e bydde&thorn;, ihesu cryst,</L>
<L>Godes sone alyue,</L>
<L>Sete crouche, pyne and passyoun,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Sete on</I> (<I>on</I> over the line in a later hand) <I>crouche;</I> but cp. the Latin text.</NOTE></L>
<L N="26">And &thorn;y de&thorn;e &thorn;at hys ryue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Between this and the following line the verses 5-10 above are inserted in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>By-tuext ous and iugement,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="83"></L>
<L>&THORN;at no fend ous ne schende,</L>
<L>Nou, ne wanne &thorn;e tyme com&thorn;e</L>
<L N="30">&THORN;et we scholle hennes wende;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf &thorn;e lyues mylse and grace,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mylse</I>, MS. <I>mysse</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e dede red and reste,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>red and and</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Holy cherche acord and pays,</L>
<L N="34">Ous glorye and lyf &thorn;at beste;</L>
<L>&THORN;at leuest and regnest wy&thorn; &thorn;e fader</L>
<L>&THORN;er neuer nys no pyne,</L>
<L>And also wy&thorn; &thorn;e holy gost,</L>
<L N="38">Euere wy&thorn;-oute fyne. AmeN.</L>
</LG>
<P>Ave maria gracia plena. dominus tecum.</P>
<P>Benedicta tu, &amp;c'.</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>OSwete leuedy, wat &thorn;ey was wo,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ey</I> = <I>&thorn;e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;o ihesus by-come morne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>morne</I>, MS. <I>inorne</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For drede &thorn;o &thorn;e blodes dropen</L>
<L N="42">Of swote of hym doun orne!</L>
<L>And, leuedy, &thorn;e was wel wors,</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at &thorn;ou se&yogh;e in dede</L>
<L>&THORN;y leue childe reulyche y-nome,<MILESTONE N="183a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="46">And ase a &thorn;ef for&thorn;e lede.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>y</I> erased before <I>lede</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ase he &thorn;olede &thorn;et for ous,</L>
<L>Leuedy, wy&thorn;-oute sake,</L>
<L>Defende ous, wanne we dede be&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="50">&THORN;at noe fende ous ne take.
<PB REF="00000099.tif" N="81"></L>
</LG>
<P>&para; Pater noster. God, atente to my socour! Lord, hy&yogh;e, etc. [D]Eus in adiutorium meum. [p. 79] Domine ad. &para; Hora prima.<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="84"></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT prime, ihesus was iled</L>
<L>To-fore syre pylate,</L>
<L>&THORN;ar wytnesses false and fele</L>
<L N="54">By-lowen hyne for hate.</L>
<L>&para; In &thorn;ane nekke hy hene smyte,</L>
<L>Bonden hys honden of my&yogh;tte,</L>
<L>By-spet hym &thorn;at swe[t]e semblant<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;at &thorn;at swe&mdash;e semblant</I>. The wanting <I>t</I> in <I>swete</I> is owing to a hole in the parchment used by the scribe.</NOTE></L>
<L N="58">&THORN;at heuene and er&thorn;e a-ly&yogh;tte.</L>
</LG>
<P>&para; ADoramus te <I>christe</I>. We &thorn;e honoure&thorn;, &amp;c'. domine ihesu <I>christe</I>. We &thorn;e bidde&thorn;, ihesu cryst. Aue maria, &amp;c'.</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>OSwete leuedy, wat &thorn;e was wo<NOTE PLACE="foot">Versicle. <I>honoure&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>hounure&thorn;</I>.&mdash;<I>domine</I>, MS. <I><ABBR>d ne</ABBR></I>, the small <I>d</I> being intended for the rubricator.</NOTE></L>
<L>A gode fry-dayes morwe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>morwe</I>, MS. <I>mor&thorn;e</I> (or <I>in or&thorn;e</I>, as Wright).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;o al &thorn;e ny&yogh;t y-spende[d] was</L>
<L N="62">In swete ihesues sorwe!</L>
<L>&THORN;ou se&yogh;e hyne hyder and &thorn;yder ycached,</L>
<L>Fram pylate to herode;</L>
<L>So me bete hys bare flesch,</L>
<L N="66">&THORN;at hy&yogh;t arne alle a blode.</L>
<L>And ase he &thorn;olede &thorn;at for ous,</L>
<L>Leuedy, wi&thorn;-oute crye,</L>
<L>Scheld ous, wanne we deade be&thorn;,</L>
<L N="70">Fram alle feenden mestrye.</L>
</LG>
<P>&para; PAter noster. DEus in adiutorium. God, atende to<MILESTONE N="183b" UNIT="folio"> my socour! [p. 79] Crucifige, &amp;c'. [Hora tertia.]</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Crucyfige! crucifige!</L>
<L>Gredden hy at ondre;</L>
<L>A pourpre clo&thorn; hi dede hym on,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="85"></L>
<L N="74">A scorne an hym to wondre;</L>
<L>Hy to-stek hys swete hefed</L>
<L>Wy&thorn; one &thorn;ornene coroune;
<PB REF="00000100.tif" N="82"></L>
<L>Toe caluarye his crouche ha beer</L>
<L N="78">Wel reuliche ou&yogh;t of &thorn;e toune.</L>
</LG>
<P>&para; V<SUB>7</SUB>. Adoramus te. Ue &thorn;e honoure&thorn;, ihesu cryst, ut <I>supra</I> [p. 79]. Domine ihesu <I>christe</I>. We &thorn;e bydde&thorn;, ihesu cryst [p. 80]. [A]ue maria, &amp;c'.</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Oswete leuedy, wat &thorn;e was wo,</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at me ihesus demde,</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at me oppone hys swete body<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hys&mdash;swete</I> separated in MS. by the hole in the parchment. So also <I>se&mdash;mde</I>, l. 82, which proves that the hole must have existed before the scribe wrote these lines.</NOTE></L>
<L N="82">&THORN;e heuye crouche semde!</L>
<L>To bere hyt to caluary,</L>
<L>I-wys, hyt was wel wery;</L>
<L>For so to-bete and so to-boned,</L>
<L N="86">Hy&yogh;t was reweleche and drery.</L>
<L>And alse he &thorn;olede &thorn;at for ous,</L>
<L>Leuedy, a &thorn;ysse wyse,</L>
<L>I-scheld ous, wanne we dede be&thorn;,</L>
<L N="90">From alle fendene Iewyse.</L>
</LG>
<P>&para; DEus in adiutorium. Gode, atende to my socour. [p. 79] Pater noster. Hora sexta.</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>On crouche y-nayled was ihesus</L>
<L>Atte six&yogh;te tyde;</L>
<L>Stronge &thorn;eues hengen hy</L>
<L N="94">On ey&thorn;er half hys syde;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>On</I> in MS. at the end of the preceding line.&mdash;<I>syde</I>, MS. <I>sede</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ine hys pyne hys stronge &thorn;erst</L>
<L>Stanchede hy wy&thorn; &yogh;alle,<MILESTONE N="184a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So &thorn;at godes holy lombe<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="86"></L>
<L N="98">Of senne wesch ous alle.</L>
</LG>
<P>&para; ADoramus te <I>christe</I>. We &thorn;e honoure&thorn;, ihesu cryst [p. 79]. Oremus. Domine ihesu <I>christe</I>. We &thorn;e bidde&thorn; ihesu cryst [p. 80]. Aue maria gratia plena.</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Oswete leuedy, wat &thorn;e was wo,</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;y chyld was an-honge,</L>
<L>Itached to &thorn;e harde tre</L>
<L N="102">Wy&thorn; nayles gret and longe!
<PB REF="00000101.tif" N="83"></L>
<L>&THORN;e gywes gradden : "com a-doun!"</L>
<L>Hy neste wat y mende,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>y</I> = <I>hy</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;ran ha &thorn;ole[de] to be do</L>
<L N="106">To de&thorn; for man-kende.</L>
<L>And ase he henge, leuedy, four ous</L>
<L>A heye oppon &thorn;e helle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>helle</I>, MS. <I>hulle</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ischeld ous, wane we deade ben,</L>
<L N="110">&THORN;at we ne hongy in helle. Amen.</L>
</LG>
<P>&para; Pater noster. Deus in adiutorium. God, atende to my socour [p. 79]. Lord, hy&yogh;e, &amp;c'. Hora nona.</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Atte none ihesu cryst</L>
<L>&THORN;ane harde dea&thorn; felde;</L>
<L>Ha grade "hely" to hys fader,</L>
<L N="114">&THORN;e soule he gan op-&yogh;elde.</L>
<L>A kni&yogh;t wy&thorn; one scharpe spere</L>
<L>Stang hyne i&thorn;e ry&yogh;t syde;</L>
<L>&THORN;er&thorn;e schok, &thorn;e sonne dym</L>
<L N="118">By-come in &thorn;are tyde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>by-come</I> in MS. at the end of the preceding line.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<P>&para; Adoramus te. We &thorn;e honoure&thorn;, ihesu cryst [p. 79]. Domine ihesu christe. We &thorn;e bydde&thorn;, ihesu cryst [p. 80]. Aue maria gracia plena, &amp;c'.<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="87"></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Oswete leuedy, wat &thorn;e was wo,</L>
<L>&THORN;o ihesus deyde on rode!</L>
<L>&THORN;e crouche, and &thorn;e ground onder hym,<MILESTONE N="184b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="122">By-bled was myd his blode.</L>
<L>&THORN;at swerde persed &thorn;yne saule &thorn;o,</L>
<L>And so hyt dede wel ofter;</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;y sorwe for &thorn;y child :</L>
<L N="126">De&thorn;e adde be wel softer.</L>
<L>And ase he &thorn;oled &thorn;ane de&thorn;,</L>
<L>Leuedy, for oure mende,</L>
<L>Schulde ous, wanne we dede be&thorn;,</L>
<L N="130">Fram de&thorn; wy&thorn;-outen ende. Amen.
<PB REF="00000102.tif" N="84"></L>
</LG>
<P>&para; Pater noster. Deus in adiutorium. God, attende to my socour. Lorde hi&yogh;e, &amp;c'. [p. 79] De cruce deponitur. hora, etc. [Hora vespertina.]</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;e crouche he was do</L>
<L>At auesanges oure;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>auesanges</I>, read <I>euesanges</I>? = 'hora vespertina.'</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e streng&thorn;e lotede ine god<NOTE PLACE="foot">Between <I>streng&thorn;e</I> and <I>lotede</I> there is in the MS. a mark of insertion, and in the right margin, after <I>god, lefte</I> is written by a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L N="134">Of oure sauueoure.</L>
<L>Suche a dea&thorn; a vnder-&yogh;ede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>dea&thorn;</I>, <I>a</I> written over <I>e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of lyf &thorn;e medicine;</L>
<L>Alas, hi was y-leyd adoun,</L>
<L N="138">&THORN;e croune of blisse, in pyne.</L>
</LG>
<P>&para; Adoramus te. We &thorn;e honoure&thorn;, ihesu crist [p. 79 domine ihesu <I>christe</I>. We &thorn;e bidde&thorn;, ihesu cry [p. 80]. Aue maria gratia plena.<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="88"></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Oswete leuedy, wat &thorn;e was wo,</L>
<L>&THORN;o cryst was do of rode!</L>
<L>For as a mesel &thorn;er he lay,</L>
<L N="142">A-stouned, in spote and blode.</L>
<L>For-bere wepyng ne my&yogh;t hy</L>
<L>&THORN;at se&yogh;e al hou &thorn;ou weptyst;</L>
<L>Al hy &thorn;e se&yogh;e of hym blody,</L>
<L N="146">So ofte &thorn;ou hine by-cleptyst.</L>
<L>And ase he &thorn;olede &thorn;e fyl&thorn;e<MILESTONE N="185a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For fel&thorn;e of oure sennes,</L>
<L>Helpe ous, leuedy, we clene be,</L>
<L>Wanne we scholle wende hennes. AmeN</L>
</LG>
<P>&para; Pater noster, &amp;c'. Deus [in] adiutorium. God, attende to my socour, &amp;c'. Lord hi&yogh;e, &amp;c'. [p. 79] Hora complettorij.</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At complyn hyt was y-bore</L>
<L>To &thorn;e beryynge,</L>
<L>&THORN;at noble corps of ihesu cryst,</L>
<L N="154">Hope of liues comynge.
<PB REF="00000103.tif" N="85"></L>
<L>Wel richeleche hit was anoynt,</L>
<L>Folfeld hys holy boke;</L>
<L>Ich bydde, lord, &thorn;y passioun</L>
<L N="158">In myne mende loke.</L>
</LG>
<P>&para; Adoramus te. We &thorn;e honoure&thorn;, ihesu crist [p. 79]. Domine ihesu <I>christe</I>. We bydde&thorn;, ihesu cryst [p. 80]. Aue maria, gracia plena, &amp;c'.</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Oswete leuedy, wat &thorn;e was wo,</L>
<L>And drery was &thorn;y mone,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="89"></L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;ou sei&yogh;e &thorn;y lefe sone</L>
<L N="162">Ibered vnder &thorn;e stone!</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou wystest &thorn;our&yogh; &thorn;y fey<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I>, read <I>&thorn;a&yogh;</I>?&mdash;<I>fey</I>, MS. <I>fey&thorn;</I>, &thorn; added by a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L>Aryse &thorn;at he scholde,</L>
<L>A drery fay hyt was to &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fay</I>, MS. <I>fay&thorn;</I>, &thorn; in a later hand on erasure.</NOTE></L>
<L N="166">&THORN;at he lay vnder molde.</L>
<L>And ase he was four ous y-bered,</L>
<L>And aros &thorn;ourwe hys my&yogh;tte,</L>
<L>Help ous, leuedy, a domes day,</L>
<L N="170">&THORN;at we aryse mytte brytte. Amen.<NOTE PLACE="foot">In the right margin a later hand has added <I>&thorn;e leuedy</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;yse oures of &thorn;e canoune,</L>
<L>Lord, mene&yogh;e ich &thorn;e wel fayre,</L>
<L>Wy&thorn; wel gre&yogh;t deuocioun,<MILESTONE N="185b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="174">A reyson de-bonayre.</L>
<L>And ase &thorn;ou &thorn;oledest, lor[d], for me</L>
<L>Ope caluaryes doune,</L>
<L>So, acordaunt to &thorn;y trauayl,</L>
<L>Lord, graunte me &thorn;y coroune. AmeN.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="3" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000104.tif" N="86">
<HEAD>(III.) De decem preceptis.<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="90"></HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;E man &thorn;at godes hestes halt,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at myd gode wylle,</L>
<L>And nau&yogh;t one by-fore men,</L>
<L N="4">Ac bo&thorn;e loud and stylle,</L>
<L>Meche hys &thorn;e mede &thorn;at hym wor&thorn;e,</L>
<L>By so &thorn;at he na-drylle;</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef he hys breke&thorn;, and so by-leef&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>by-leef&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>by loef&thorn;?</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="8">Hys sauyle schal he spylle.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sauyle</I>, MS. <I>sauylle</I>, first <I>l</I> underdotted.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &YOGH;ef &thorn;ou hys halst, man, god &thorn;e sei&thorn;e</L>
<L>Ha wole be &thorn;e so kende,</L>
<L>He wole be fo to &thorn;yne fon,</L>
<L N="12">And frend to &thorn;yne frende;</L>
<L>Hye &thorn;e mysdo&thorn;, ham wyle mysdo,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Hye</I>, read <I>Hwo?</I></NOTE></L>
<L>And haue &thorn;ys in &thorn;yne mende :</L>
<L>Hys angel schal to-for &thorn;e go</L>
<L N="16">To wyte &thorn;e fram &thorn;e fende.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;yne sustenaunce &thorn;ou schel[t] haue,</L>
<L>&THORN;y&yogh; nau&yogh;t a lyue delyce,</L>
<L>Ac mete and clo&thorn;es renableliche,</L>
<L N="20">And lyf ine herte blysce.</L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; folk &thorn;e heelde a nice man,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>anice</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore nert &thorn;ou nau&yogh;t nyce;</L>
<L>I-likned wor&thorn; &thorn;y gode loos<MILESTONE N="186a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="24">So swete so &thorn;e spyce.
<PB REF="00000105.tif" N="87"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &YOGH;ef &thorn;e &thorn;at art a crystene man</L>
<L>Wel hy healde by-falle&thorn;,</L>
<L>Syker &thorn;ou my&yogh;t be of &thorn;at lond</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;ar melke and hony walle&thorn;;</L>
<L>&THORN;at hys &thorn;e blysse of heuene a-boue,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="91"></L>
<L>&THORN;ar holy soulen stalle&thorn;</L>
<L>Ine glorye &thorn;er none ende nys,</L>
<L N="32">Ne none swetnesse a-ppalle&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; To wyte &thorn;anne wat god ha&yogh;t</L>
<L>Is eche man wel y-halde;</L>
<L>&THORN;rof ich may telle ase ich wot,</L>
<L N="36">Ase o&thorn;er men me tealde,</L>
<L>And ase hyt hys in holye boke</L>
<L>I-wryten ine many a felde :</L>
<L>Lestne&thorn; to mey, par charyte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mey = me</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="40">Bo&thorn;e &yogh;onge and ealde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ealde</I>, the <I>a</I> altered by a later hand from <I>o</I>, which was written on erasure; an <I>e</I> before it is still clearly distinguishable.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O &thorn;yng hyt hys, al &thorn;at god hat,</L>
<L>Bote a two he hy&yogh;t dy&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at hys loue, man, syker &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L N="44">To louye wy&thorn; &thorn;y my&yogh;te.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>my&yogh;te</I>, MS. <I>my&yogh;t</I>, with a flourish to the <I>t</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou ert y-helde, man, &thorn;er-to</L>
<L>By skele and eke by ry&yogh;tte;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou &thorn;enke her-on, par charyte,</L>
<L N="48">By dayes and eke by ny&yogh;tte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;ys loue god he&thorn; y-di&yogh;t a tuo</L>
<L>Amang hijs hestes alle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ferste hys, for to louye god,</L>
<L N="52">By-falle what so falle;</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e to louye alle men,<MILESTONE N="186b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So bro&thorn;ren scholde ine halle,</L>
<L>Wy&thorn;-outen byternesse of mode,</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;at hijs &thorn;are saule galle.
<PB REF="00000106.tif" N="88"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e man &thorn;at healde&thorn; &thorn;ys[e] two,</L>
<L>Of charyte &thorn;e heastes,</L>
<L>Al he folue[l]&thorn; &thorn;e lawe of gode,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="92"></L>
<L N="60">And prophetene gestes.</L>
<L>Ac lasse loue &thorn;er hys wy&thorn; men</L>
<L>&THORN;ane be wy&thorn; wylde bestes :</L>
<L>&THORN;at do&thorn; &thorn;at manye y-schodred ben<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>y-schodred, r</I> written over <I>e</I>; see note.</NOTE></L>
<L N="64">Fram heuene-ryche festes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ten hestes haue&thorn; y-hote god,</L>
<L>Ase holy wryt ous tealde;</L>
<L>Ope two tablettes of ston</L>
<L N="68">Wy&thorn; hys finger bealde</L>
<L>He hys wrot, Moyses by-tok,<NOTE PLACE="foot">K&ouml;lbing supplies <I>and</I> before <I>Moyses</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wylom by da&yogh;es ealde,</L>
<L>To wyse man hou [he] schal wel<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>he</I>] supplied by K&ouml;lbing.</NOTE></L>
<L N="72">&THORN;ese ten hestes healde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In ston ich wot &thorn;at he hys wrot,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wot</I>, small <I>r</I> written over <I>o</I> in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>In tokne of sykernesse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wo &thorn;at wole ysaued be,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wo = who</I>, MS. <I>we</I>, originally <I>wey</I>, the <I>y</I> afterwards erased.</NOTE></L>
<L N="76">&THORN;e more and eke &thorn;e lesse,</L>
<L>By-houe&thorn; &thorn;at he healde hy</L>
<L>Wy&thorn; al hys bysynysse.</L>
<L>Allas! feawe &thorn;enche&thorn; &thorn;er-on</L>
<L N="80">I[n hare] wykkednesse.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>I[n hare</I>], MS. <I>I a</I>; between them there is a blank covering some five or six letters.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;et o table hedde &thorn;ry</L>
<L>Of &thorn;yse hestes tene;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ri longe&thorn; to loue of gode,<MILESTONE N="187a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="84">Ase hy&yogh;t schel wel be sene.</L>
<L>&THORN;e seuen longet to loue of man,</L>
<L>&THORN;at none scholde wene<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>none</I>, read <I>non ne?</I></NOTE>
<PB REF="00000107.tif" N="89"></L>
<L>Ine &thorn;o&thorn;er table sete &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="88">To-gadere and al y-mene.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Honury &thorn;ou schelt enne god,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="93"></L>
<L>Hym one to by-knowe;</L>
<L>Take nau&yogh;t hys name in ydelschepe,</L>
<L N="92">Wy&thorn; ydel wynde to blowe;</L>
<L>Hal&yogh;e &thorn;ou &thorn;e masseday,</L>
<L>Ase he com&thorn;e in &thorn;e rewe:</L>
<L>In &thorn;ese &thorn;re schewy&thorn; &thorn;e loue of god,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>schewy&thorn; . . god:</I> MS. <I>&thorn;e loue of god schewy hit: hit</I>, as well as <I>to</I> in l. 96, above the line in a later hand. But see note.</NOTE></L>
<L N="96">Were hyt hys to sewe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Worschipe &thorn;y fader and moder eke;</L>
<L>Ne bryng no man of lyue;</L>
<L>Do &thorn;e to none lecherye,</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;a&yogh; &thorn;e fondyngge dryue;</L>
<L>Wytnesse uals ne bere &thorn;ou non;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ef&thorn;e &thorn;ou ne schryue;</L>
<L>Coueyte none mannes wyf,</L>
<L N="104">Ne nau&yogh;t of hys forstryue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;ys be&thorn;e &thorn;e seuene &thorn;at loue of man</L>
<L>Schewe[&thorn;] what hy&yogh;t be scholde;</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef eny man fayle&thorn; eny of &thorn;ys,</L>
<L N="108">Nys hy&yogh;t bote an on-holde.</L>
<L>Ac al to fewe louye&thorn; ham,</L>
<L>And wylle&thorn; &thorn;at o&thorn;er wolde;</L>
<L>Alas! wat schal be hare red</L>
<L N="112">Wanne hy be&thorn; vnder molde?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ac many man desceyued hys,<MILESTONE N="187b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And wene&thorn; &thorn;at he hys helde;</L>
<L>And weyne&thorn; &thorn;at he be out of peryl,</L>
<L N="116">O&thorn;er ine senne so schealde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hym ne doute&thorn; of no breche</L>
<L>Of godes hestes healde;
<PB REF="00000108.tif" N="90"></L>
<L>Ac he not nefer wat hy bee&thorn;,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="94"></L>
<L N="120">Ne neuer hy ne tealde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; I-wryte hyt hys, ich telle hy&yogh;t &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Ine &thorn;e boke of wysdome,</L>
<L>&THORN;at eche man scholde conne hy,</L>
<L N="124">And rekeny wel y-lome;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at hy nere nau&yogh;t for-&yogh;ete,</L>
<L>Wane o&thorn;ere &thorn;ou&yogh;tes come,</L>
<L>Tys fyngres scolde man bynde hy<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Tys = to [te] hys;</I> cp. p. 33, l. 915; also <I>&thorn;yt</I>, l. 132 = <I>&thorn;ou [&thorn;e] hyt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="128">For doute of harde dome.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; For mannes honden and hys fet</L>
<L>Beret tokene wel gode</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e tenne comaundemens:</L>
<L N="132">&THORN;at, man, &thorn;yt onder-stoude!<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>onder-stoude, ou</I> written for <I>&omacr;</I>; so also in <I>for-broude</I>, l. 136.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ten fyngres and ten &thorn;ine tone,</L>
<L>Of flesche and bon and blode,</L>
<L>Tokne&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;yne workes ne be,</L>
<L N="136">A&yogh;eyns &thorn;e hestes, for-broude.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &YOGH;et somman hijs &thorn;at passioun-lyche<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>passioun-lyche</I>, read <I>passing-lyche</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L>Can telle hy myd &thorn;e beste,</L>
<L>Ac ine hys dedes uares he</L>
<L N="140">Ase he nau&yogh;t of hem neste;</L>
<L>And &yogh;et hym &thorn;ing&thorn; &thorn;at he de&thorn; wel,</L>
<L>And for to come to reste;</L>
<L>Ac al desceyued schel he be,<MILESTONE N="188a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="144">Wanne come&thorn; &thorn;e grete enqueste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Here-fore nys hy&yogh;t nau&yogh;t y-nou&yogh;</L>
<L>To telle hy uor to conne:<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>ne</I> (over the line in a later hand) <I>uor to conne</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And telle and werche wel &thorn;er-by,</L>
<L N="148">&THORN;anne hys hy&yogh;t alle y-wonne.
<PB REF="00000109.tif" N="91"></L>
<L>For wel to conne, and nau&yogh;[t] to don,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to don</I>, MS. <I>no don</I>.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="95"></L>
<L>Nys na&thorn;er rawe ne y-sponne;</L>
<L>Lytel hijs wor&thorn;, bote hyt endy wel,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>dy</I> in <I>endy</I> on erasure; <I>wel</I> in MS. at the beginning of the next line, with a dot after it.</NOTE></L>
<L N="152">&THORN;yng &thorn;at hijs wel by-gonne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;ey hyt be wel lyttelyche ysed,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lyttelyche</I> for <I>ly&yogh;telyche</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e ferste heste a rowe,</L>
<L>For to honoury anne god,</L>
<L N="156">Hym one to by-knowe,</L>
<L>&THORN;enche &thorn;ou most wel bysyly,</L>
<L>And &thorn;y wy&yogh;t &thorn;ran by-stowe,</L>
<L>And bydde hym, &thorn;at &thorn;ou hyt mote do,</L>
<L N="160">Wel myldeleche a knowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; For &thorn;ou ne my&yogh;t hytte nefere do,</L>
<L>Man, wel wy&thorn;-oute grace:</L>
<L>So he&thorn; &thorn;ys wordle bounde &thorn;e</L>
<L N="164">Wy&thorn; here lykynges lace.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lace</I>, MS. <I>lause, u</I> and <I>s</I> on erasure in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore &thorn;e by-houe&thorn; godes helpe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hyt wolde arace,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne teldest no wor&thorn;</L>
<L N="168">Of [here] blandynge face.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; For &yogh;yf &thorn;y wyl reio[ye]&thorn; more<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>reioye&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>re i o&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>In enyes kennes &thorn;ynges,</L>
<L>Be hy&yogh;t &thorn;y childe, o&thorn;er &thorn;y best,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;y</I> (K&ouml;lbing), MS. <I>&thorn;e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="172">Land, brouches, o&thorn;er rynges,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>rynges</I>, MS. <I>rynge&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>O&thorn;er a&yogh;t elles, wat so hyt be,<MILESTONE N="188b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bote god &thorn;at hys kynge of kynges,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Bote yne god, yne</I> added by a later hand above the line.&mdash;<I>heuene</I> (underdotted) after <I>of</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou ne a-nourest god ary&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">In the margin, above <I>ary&yogh;t</I>, a later hand has written <I>na&yogh;t</I>, to be inserted after <I>anourest</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="176">Ac dest is onderlynges.
<PB REF="00000110.tif" N="92"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; By-lef &thorn;ou in no wychecraft,</L>
<L>Ne ine none teliinge,</L>
<L>Ne for&thorn;e inne none ymage self,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="96"></L>
<L N="180">&THORN;a&yogh; &thorn;at be great botninge;</L>
<L>Bote as al holy cherche &thorn;e tek[&thorn;]</L>
<L>&THORN;ou make &thorn;yne wor&thorn;ynge,</L>
<L>For gode nele nau&yogh;t &thorn;at &thorn;ou hyt do,</L>
<L N="184">Bote by &thorn;ere wyssynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;anne asay &thorn;yn o&yogh;e &thorn;o&yogh;t</L>
<L>By &thorn;ysser ylke speche,</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf &thorn;ou annourest god ary&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="188">&THORN;yne inwit wyle &thorn;e teche;</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf &thorn;ou fynst &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne dest,</L>
<L>Amende, ich &thorn;e by-seche:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou ert a sot, and my&yogh;t do bet,</L>
<L N="192">And so si&yogh;st yn &thorn;e smeche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;at o&thorn;er heste apertelyche</L>
<L>Schewed mannes de-faute,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>schewed = schewe&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wanne he alday swere&thorn; ydelleche</L>
<L N="196">In kebbyng and in caute.</L>
<L>Mechel hys &thorn;at he make&thorn; hym</L>
<L>Her-efterward to touty,</L>
<L>Wenne he schal hys a-countes &yogh;yue</L>
<L N="200">Of ech idel sente.<NOTE PLACE="foot">196-200. See note.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;enne ne cou&thorn;e ich nanne red</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ylke a-countes oure,</L>
<L>Nere &thorn;e milse of god self,<NOTE PLACE="foot">After <I>milse</I>, a later hand has added above the line <I>&amp; merci</I>.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="189a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="204">Oure alder auditour[e],</L>
<L>&THORN;at wolle &thorn;e arerages for-&yogh;eue,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef hyt hys to hys honoure;</L>
<L>Ac cesse, man, of &thorn;y ydelschep,</L>
<L N="208">O&thorn;er ich wole out wel soure.
<PB REF="00000111.tif" N="93"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;rydde heste apertelyche<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="97"></L>
<L>Schewe&thorn; &thorn;y wykked rote,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;y</I>, MS. <I>wy&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wanne &thorn;ou [ne] halst &thorn;y masseday,</L>
<L N="212">As god hyt ha&thorn; y-hote,</L>
<L>Ac werkest, o&thorn;er werky dest,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>werky, y</I> altered from <I>e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Werkes &thorn;at be&thorn; to note:</L>
<L>&THORN;e wykkede ensaumple &thorn;at &thorn;ou &yogh;efst</L>
<L N="216">&THORN;ou a-beyst, ich &thorn;e by-hote.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And &thorn;a&yogh; &thorn;ou ne werche nau&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;a&yogh;</I> (K&ouml;lbing), MS. <I>&thorn;at</I>; we may as well read [<I>&thorn;a&yogh;] &thorn;at</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac gest to &thorn;yne gloutynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;yne</I> (suggested by K&ouml;lbing), MS. <I>&thorn;yne</I>; but see note.</NOTE></L>
<L>O&thorn;er in eny o&thorn;er folke<NOTE PLACE="foot">See note.</NOTE></L>
<L N="220">In pleye of &thorn;retynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">See note.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou halst wel wors &thorn;ane masseday</L>
<L>&THORN;ane man myd hys workynge;</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore do &thorn;e al y-holliche<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>do</I> (K&ouml;lbing), MS. <I>to</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="224">&THORN;at day to holy &thorn;ynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e fer&thorn;e heste schewe&thorn; &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fer&thorn;e</I>, MS. <I>feste</I> or <I>fefte</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ye senne schal sle &thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sle &thorn;e</I>, MS. <I>sle&thorn;e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou rewardest &thorn;yne eldrynges nau&yogh;t</L>
<L N="228">A lyue and eke a de&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at were wel besy to brynge &thorn;e for&thorn;e,</L>
<L>As hy my&yogh;ten onne&thorn;e;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>onne&thorn;e</I>, MS. <I>onny&thorn;e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou hy gna&yogh;st and flag&yogh;st ek,</L>
<L N="232">Ry&yogh;t hys &thorn;at fendes flea &thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>flca &thorn;e</I>, MS. <I>flea&thorn;e</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Nau&yogh;t nys &thorn;ys heste y-hote of god<MILESTONE N="189b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For suche eldren al-lone,</L>
<L>Ac hys of mannes eldren eke</L>
<L N="236">As he te&yogh;t atte font-stone,
<PB REF="00000112.tif" N="94"></L>
<L>&THORN;er holy cherche &thorn;y moder hys</L>
<L>In fader cristes mone;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>And fader in cristes mone;</I> see note.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;ef &thorn;ou ert on-boxom to hyre,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="98"></L>
<L N="240">Grace of God ne wor&thorn;e &thorn;e none.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e fyfte heste schewe&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou ne schalt nau&yogh;t smyte,</L>
<L>Ne nau&yogh;t ne mys-segge ne mys-do,</L>
<L N="244">Ne nau&yogh;t foulleche at-wyte.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>foulleche</I>, MS. <I>foules he</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For ofte &thorn;e mannes sle&yogh;te aryst,</L>
<L>Were man hy&yogh;t wene&thorn; wel lyte;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lyte</I>, MS. <I>lytel</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And he &thorn;at spille&thorn; mannes lyf,</L>
<L N="248">Veniounse hyt schel a[c]wyte.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>a</I>[<I>c</I>]<I>wyte</I> (K&ouml;lbing).</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And &yogh;ef &thorn;er hys mansle&yogh;&thorn;e pur,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;ef</I>, read <I>&yogh;et?&mdash;mansle&yogh;&thorn;e</I>, MS. <I>sle&yogh; &thorn;e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>As ous telle&thorn; holy boke,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf eny man for de-faute dey&thorn;,</L>
<L N="252">And eny hym for-soke</L>
<L>To helpe hym of &thorn;at he may,</L>
<L>Hys lyf to saue and loke:</L>
<L>Her dere &yogh;er acuse&thorn; fele</L>
<L N="256">&THORN;at god and or&thorn;e touke.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And &yogh;et seint iohan &thorn;e-wangelyst</L>
<L>Al into mende dra&yogh;e&thorn;,</L>
<L>He &thorn;at hatye&thorn; eny man,</L>
<L N="260">He seche &thorn;at he hym sla&yogh;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot">See note.</NOTE></L>
<L>Manye suche mansle&yogh;&thorn;en be&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mansle&yogh;&thorn;en:</I> MS. -<I>sle&yogh; &thorn;en</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at al day men for-gna&yogh;e&thorn;,</L>
<L>&amp; Sweche be&thorn; in helle depe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>w</I> in <I>Sweche</I> over the line, in the original hand-writing, it seems.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="190a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="264">&THORN;at deuelen al to-drawe&thorn;.
<PB REF="00000113.tif" N="95"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e sixte heste schewe&thorn; wel</L>
<L>&THORN;e so&thorn;e to al mankenne,</L>
<L>&THORN;e dede ydo in lechery</L>
<L N="268">Hys ry&yogh;t a dedleche senne;</L>
<L>And elles nere hy&yogh;t nau&yogh;t for-bode<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for-bode</I> begins next line in MS.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="99"></L>
<L>amange &thorn;e hestes tenne :</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;at segge&thorn; hyt nys nau&yogh;t so,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>so</I> in MS. transposed to the following line.</NOTE></L>
<L N="272">hare wy&yogh;t hys al to &thorn;enne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Her hys for-bode glotenye,</L>
<L>So ich &thorn;e by-hote;</L>
<L>For hyt norysse&thorn; lecherye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hyt</I>, MS. <I>ich</I>. After <I>lecherye</I> an underdotted <I>a</I> is written in MS</NOTE></L>
<L N="276">Ase fer, &thorn;e brondes hote.</L>
<L>And &thorn;a&yogh; &thorn;er be alone lomprynge</L>
<L>In lecheryes rote,</L>
<L>Al hyt destrue&thorn; charyte,</L>
<L N="280">Wy&thorn; wrake and wy&thorn; &thorn;rete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e seuende heste schewed wel</L>
<L>Man schal be true in dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no man abbe of &thorn;e o&thorn;eres naut<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;rete</I>? distinctly so in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="284">&THORN;or&yogh; &thorn;efte wycke rede;</L>
<L>For al hys &thorn;efte &thorn;at man te&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>abbe</I>, read <I>nabbe</I>? (K&ouml;lbing).</NOTE></L>
<L>Myd wyl of wynnynghede<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wynnynghede</I>? MS. <I>wymynghede</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>A&yogh;ens &thorn;e ry&yogh;t o&yogh;eres wyl,</L>
<L N="288">So lawe y-wryte hyt sede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;anne hys hyt a &thorn;ef, wo-so hyt be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at manne god so take&thorn;,</L>
<L>Be hy&yogh;t by gyle o&thorn;er mestry,</L>
<L N="292">O&thorn;er wordes &thorn;at he crake&thorn;.</L>
<L>In londe suche his many a &thorn;ef<MILESTONE N="190b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at y-now hym make&thorn;;
<PB REF="00000114.tif" N="96"></L>
<L>He wen&thorn; by chere of iugement,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>chere</I>, read <I>schere</I> (<I>skere</I>)? See p. 105, l. 183.</NOTE></L>
<L N="296">Ac helle after hym wake&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e e&yogh;tende heste &thorn;e for-bed</L>
<L>&THORN;e false wytnessynge;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at hys, man, syker &thorn;ou be,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="100"></L>
<L N="300">Alle manere lesynge</L>
<L>To hermy in [hys] body man,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er in hys o&thorn;er &thorn;ynge,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er in hys saule, and &thorn;at hys worst,<NOTE PLACE="foot">K&ouml;lbing suggests leaving out <I>in</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="304">In peryl for to brynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Al hyt hys senne &thorn;at me le&yogh;&thorn;,</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;at men le&yogh;&thorn; for gode</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t deadlyche senne nys &thorn;at nau&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="308">For myldenesse of mode.</L>
<L>Ac elles, man, al &thorn;at &thorn;ou legst</L>
<L>Is dea&thorn;lich and for-brode;</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;et hy&yogh;t use&thorn;, ich wot hy be&thorn;</L>
<L N="312">Vn-wyser &thorn;ane &thorn;e wode.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Alas! onne&thorn;e eny man</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;yse heste(s) healde;</L>
<L>Alle hy be&thorn; y-torned to lesynge,</L>
<L N="316">&THORN;es &yogh;onge and eke &thorn;es ealde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ealde</I>, MS. <I>olde</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er-to hys mentenaunce great,</L>
<L>&THORN;at make&thorn; hy wel bealde :</L>
<L>Do &yogh;e nau&yogh;t so, par charyte,</L>
<L N="320">Ac &yogh;oure tongen &yogh;e wealde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="41" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e ne&yogh;ende heste &thorn;e for-bed</L>
<L>&THORN;at wyl to lecherye,</L>
<L>And to spousbreche nameleche,<MILESTONE N="191a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="324">&THORN;at so meche hys to glye.</L>
<L>&THORN;anne nys hyt nau&yogh;t one dea[d]lyche</L>
<L>Swych dede to complye,
<PB REF="00000115.tif" N="97"></L>
<L>Ac ys &thorn;at uoule wyl al so</L>
<L N="328">To swyche fylenye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="42" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e te&thorn;e heste &thorn;e fo[r]-bet<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="101"></L>
<L>Wyl tou o&thorn;er manne &thorn;ynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>tou = to</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;at desturbet charyte,</L>
<L N="332">In onde man to brynge.</L>
<L>Defende&thorn; &yogh;ou for godes loue</L>
<L>Fram alle wykked wyllynge;</L>
<L>For suche wyl hys for dede iset</L>
<L N="336">In godes knelechynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="43" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Nou ich &yogh;ou bydde for &thorn;e blode</L>
<L>&THORN;at ihesus blede on &thorn;e rode,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in te herte take&thorn; &thorn;ys two<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omit <I>two</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L N="340">To &yogh;oure soule fode;</L>
<L>And fo[l]&yogh;e&thorn; nau&yogh;t in &thorn;ys wordle</L>
<L>&THORN;e uyle commune floude</L>
<L>&THORN;at fleu&thorn; in-to &thorn;e fendes mou&thorn;e;</L>
<L N="344">And so sei&thorn;e iop &thorn;e gode AmeN.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="4" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000116.tif" N="98">
<HEAD>IV. [De septem mortalibus peccatis.]<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="102"></HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEnne make&thorn; many &thorn;ral,</L>
<L>&THORN;at scholde be wel fry;</L>
<L>And senne make&thorn; many fal,</L>
<L N="4">&YOGH;at he ne mote i&thorn;y.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Senne brynge&thorn; man a-doun,</L>
<L>&THORN;at scholde sitte a deys;</L>
<L>Senne make&thorn; storbylo[u]n,</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;ar scholde be godes peys.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>peys</I>, MS. <I>peays</I>, the <I>a</I> inserted (and the <I>s</I> added) by a later hand.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="191b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Senne make&thorn; by-wepe</L>
<L>&THORN;at somman er by-lo&yogh;;</L>
<L>Senne brynge&thorn; wel depe</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;at hym wel hy&yogh;e dro&yogh;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Senne hys swete and lyke&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Between <I>hys</I> and <I>swete</I> some letters erased.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wanne a man hi de&thorn;;</L>
<L>And al so soure hy bryke&thorn;,</L>
<L N="16">Wanne he ueniaunce y-se&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Senne make&thorn; nywe schame,</L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; hy for-&yogh;ete be;</L>
<L>And senne brynge&thorn; men in grame,</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;ar er was game and gle.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and gle</I> later hand.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And senne make&thorn; al &thorn;e who<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>who</I> = <I>wo;</I> same spelling, 11. 29, 46, etc.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at man an er&thorn;e he&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>ha&thorn;</I>.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000117.tif" N="99"></L>
<L>And brynge&thorn; mannes saule also</L>
<L N="24">In helles uoule bre&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;ey man be fram helle y-wared<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>y-wared</I>, MS. <I>y-wered</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;our&yogh; repentaunce here,</L>
<L>&YOGH;et ne may nau&yogh;t some man be spared</L>
<L N="28">Fram purgatories fere,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at he ne schel soffry &thorn;er hys who,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="103"></L>
<L>Ase he hijs here ateynt;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ateynt</I>, MS. <I>atenkt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And her nys fer namore &thorn;er-to</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;anne hys fer dereynt.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>dereynt</I>. In the MS. the second <I>e</I> is written close to the long-tailed <I>r</I>, and a stroke drawn through the tail of the <I>r</I>, such as generally occurs in the letter <I>p;</I> so that the word intended by the scribe may really have been <I>depeynt</I>. See note.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac purgatorie and helle,</L>
<L>Hy be&thorn; so lyte by-leued,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Hy be&thorn;</I> in MS. at the end of the preceding line.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at, what so meuere telle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>what so me&umacr;e men telle&thorn;</I>, <I>men</I> (above the line), and the &thorn; in <I>telle&thorn;</I> in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L N="36">[Men] be&thorn; &thorn;rof al adeued.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hem wolde douty more</L>
<L>A lytel pyne her,<MILESTONE N="192a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ane ham wolde al &thorn;at sore</L>
<L N="40">And on-ysely fer.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac hwo se&yogh; euer eny<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>eny</I> later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at hedde of senne glye,</L>
<L>For pond o&thorn;er for peny<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>peny</I>, MS. <I>peyne</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="44">&THORN;at he ne changede hys blye,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wy&thorn; schame and eke wy&thorn; schounde,</L>
<L>Wy&thorn; sor&yogh;e and eke wy&thorn; who?
<PB REF="00000118.tif" N="100"></L>
<L>And &thorn;at was ked in londe</L>
<L N="48">By some nau&yogh;t fern ago.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;anne ich may wyssy ase ich can,</L>
<L>Mi self &thorn;a&yogh; ich be spre&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Mi self</I>, MS. <I>I Mi self, Mi</I> (in a different hand) inserted between <I>I</I> and <I>self</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at, bote &thorn;ou wylle wondy, man,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wondy</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="52">&THORN;y pyne after &thorn;y de&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;y pyne</I>, read <I>&thorn;e pyne</I>?</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wonde &thorn;e sor&yogh;e &thorn;at hys her<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Wonde</I>, read <I>uondy, Uonde</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L>Fol&yogh;ende after &thorn;y queed;</L>
<L>And &yogh;et &thorn;e tyt &thorn;e lasse fer,</L>
<L N="56">Whanne &thorn;e fal&thorn; to be dead.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whanne &thorn;ou scholdest sene&yogh;y,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ene&yogh;y</I> in lighter ink.</NOTE></L>
<L>By-&thorn;enche, leue frend,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>By</I>-<I>&thorn;enche</I>, read <I>By</I>-<I>&thorn;ench &thorn;e</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;a&yogh; &thorn;y flesch &thorn;e mene&yogh;y,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="104"></L>
<L N="60">&THORN;e wordle o&thorn;er &thorn;e fend,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<L>By-&thorn;enche hou schort hys &thorn;e lykynge,</L>
<L>And hou &thorn;e schame hys stronge,</L>
<L>And hou &thorn;ou wre&thorn;est &thorn;ane kyng<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wre&thorn;est</I>, the <I>r</I> written over the <I>e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="64">Of heuene wy&thorn; &thorn;y wrong.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wh</I> (underdotted) after <I>heuene</I> in MS.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;i&yogh; man mo&yogh;e &thorn;or&yogh; hys resoun<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mo&yogh;e</I>, MS. <I>mo&yogh;o</I>. After <I>&thorn;or&yogh;</I>, <I>resoun</I> is written, but has been crossed out and underdotted.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ywyte wanne he mys-de&thorn;,</L>
<L>&YOGH;et &thorn;er by-houe&thorn; gre&yogh;t sarmoun</L>
<L N="68">To hame &thorn;at lewed be&thorn;e.<MILESTONE N="192b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<L>For feawe of ham conne &thorn;e skele</L>
<L>Hou senne a-boute come&thorn;;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at a-combre&thorn; swy&thorn;e fele</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;at none kepe nome&thorn;.
<PB REF="00000119.tif" N="101"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er-fore &thorn;ys tale ryme&thorn;</L>
<L>Hou men in senne be&thorn;,</L>
<L>And hou senne by-lyme&thorn;</L>
<L N="76">Man &thorn;at to senne hym de&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er-fore neme &yogh;e kepe<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;er fore fore</I> (struck out).</NOTE></L>
<L>Al hou &thorn;e senne syt,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e ne falle to depe</L>
<L N="80">For wane of &yogh;oure wyt.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou lyst hou man hys bounde</L>
<L>Wy&thorn; senne swy&thorn;e stronge,</L>
<L>And hou he bere&thorn; dea&thorn;-wounde,</L>
<L N="84">And fenym &thorn;are a-monge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e wonde swel&thorn; an ake&thorn;,</L>
<L>So do&thorn; &thorn;e naddre steng,</L>
<L>And gret and gretter make&thorn;,</L>
<L N="88">And fel&thorn;e make &thorn;reng.<NOTE PLACE="foot">85-88. See note.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Iwounded was mankende<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="105"></L>
<L>After &thorn;at hy was wro&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;or&yogh; &thorn;e neddre, &thorn;e feend[e],</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;at hy he&thorn; al &thorn;or&yogh;-sou&yogh;t</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;orwe &thorn;e fenym of senne</L>
<L>&THORN;at al mankende slak&thorn; :</L>
<L>Nys nou non [of] &thorn;at kenne<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nys</I>, MS. <I>Nes</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="96">&THORN;at &thorn;at fenym ne take&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;at fenym was ferst y-kest<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>y-kest</I>, MS. <I>y-kast</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>On eue and on adam,<MILESTONE N="193a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And so for&thorn;e &thorn;enne hyt her ylest,</L>
<L N="100">Ase kenne of-&yogh;erne&thorn; yne man.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;erne&thorn; yne</I> on erasure in a later hand.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000120.tif" N="102"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<L>So hy&yogh;t nys nau&yogh;t senne-lyas,</L>
<L>&THORN;at child &thorn;at haue&thorn; lyf,</L>
<L>Ybore o&thorn;er on-bore was,</L>
<L>bote Crystnynge breke&thorn; &thorn;at stryf.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bote</I>, in the handwriting of a later revisor of the text. It had been erroneously written at the end of line 103, where it has been erased.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Oryginale &thorn;ys senne hys cleped,</L>
<L>For man of kende hyt take&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">After <I>take&thorn;</I>, a later hand has added <I>syn</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="108">. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">Here two lines are wanting.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ry&yogh;t so hys al mankende a-merred</L>
<L>&THORN;or&yogh; &thorn;e route of fenym,</L>
<L>&THORN;at do&thorn; &thorn;at mannes body ybered</L>
<L N="112">Nys bote a lyte slym.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Her-vppe y&thorn;o&yogh;t ha&thorn; meny a man,</L>
<L>And ised many a foul</L>
<L>&THORN;at on-wyslyche god ous by-gan,</L>
<L N="116">And hys red was to coul,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at let man to suich meschyef,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>let</I>, read <I>ledde?&mdash;meschyef</I>, the second <I>e</I> written over the <I>y;</I> so also in the corresponding ryme-word <I>lief</I> the <I>i</I> is written over the <I>e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at my&yogh;te hyt habbe vndo;</L>
<L>Ac &yogh;ef &thorn;ou wolt by gode lief,</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;enche &thorn;ou namore so.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ne vel&thorn;e hyt nau&yogh;t to clypye a&yogh;en,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="106"></L>
<L>We soe&thorn; wel hyt hys &thorn;ous,</L>
<L>God te atwyte oure won<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>won</I>, read <I>wen</I>? but see note.</NOTE></L>
<L N="124">No longe&thorn; no&thorn;yng to ous.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<L>For wo dyspute&thorn; a-&yogh;eyn hym,</L>
<L>Concluded schel he be;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wo</I> ( = <I>who</I>), MS. <I>we</I>.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000121.tif" N="103"></L>
<L>Dispute nau&yogh;t, ac kepe nym,</L>
<L N="128">Wo &thorn;art, and who hys he.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wat help&thorn; hyt &thorn;e crokke<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Wat</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;at</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at hys to fel&thorn;e ydo<MILESTONE N="193b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A&yogh;e &thorn;e crokkere to brokke :&mdash;</L>
<L N="132">"Wy madest &thorn;ou me so?"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e crokkere my&yogh;te segge :</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou proud er&thorn;e of lompet,</L>
<L>Ine fel&thorn;e &thorn;ou schelt lygge,</L>
<L N="136">&THORN;ou ert nau&yogh;t elles ne&yogh;t."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ry&yogh;t so may god an-swerye &thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>an-swerye</I>, originally <I>and swerye</I>, the <I>d</I> afterwards erased.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wanne &thorn;ou hym at-wyst;</L>
<L>Wat help&thorn;e hyt so wrau to be,</L>
<L N="140">Wanne &thorn;ou wy&thorn; gode chyst?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Do nau&yogh;t so, ac mercy crye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e [ne] tyde wors;</L>
<L>For suiche al day, me may ysy,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ysy</I>, MS. <I>yse</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="144">Encresse&thorn; here cors.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac be &thorn;ou wel, man, be &thorn;e wo,</L>
<L>Of gode ne tel &thorn;ou nau&yogh;t ly&yogh;te;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ly&yogh;te</I>, MS. <I>lytel</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For syker be, &thorn;at he let do,</L>
<L N="148">He let hyt do wy&thorn; ry&yogh;te.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swech ry&yogh;t scheawe&thorn; wy&thorn; God aboue,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>God aboue</I> in MS. at the beginning of the next line.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e[&yogh;] hy&yogh;t be hyd fram &thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;enche namore, for godes loue,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="107"></L>
<L N="152">So he&yogh;e pryuete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac &thorn;ench &thorn;ou nart bote esche,</L>
<L>And so &thorn;ou lo&yogh;e &thorn;e,
<PB REF="00000122.tif" N="104"></L>
<L>And byde god &thorn;at he wesche</L>
<L N="156">&THORN;e fel&thorn;e &thorn;at hys in &thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I> in MS. at the end of the preceding line.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;y&yogh; &thorn;ou lange abyde,</L>
<L>Ne at-wyt hym nau&yogh;t &thorn;y who,</L>
<L>Ac tyde &thorn;e what by-tyde,</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;ou &thorn;onke hym euere mo.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;onke</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;enke</I>.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="194a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="41" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And so soum grace &thorn;e by-tyt,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>by-tyt</I>, MS. <I>by tyde</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac elles &thorn;e hy for-gest;</L>
<L>For god wy&thorn;-stonde&thorn; hym &thorn;at chyt</L>
<L N="164">And a&yogh;e god wrest,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="42" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ase he wy&thorn;-stent &thorn;e prouden,</L>
<L>And myld[en] grace sent</L>
<L>To libbe a-mang &thorn;e louden,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Read <I>amang &thorn;e alouden</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L N="168">Wenne o&thorn;ere be&thorn; ischent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="43" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou we see&thorn; wel hou hyt hys</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ane oryginal;</L>
<L>Nou lest ou man [may] do amys</L>
<L N="172">&THORN;or&yogh; hys o&yogh;ene gale.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="44" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys senne come&thorn; nau&yogh;t of &thorn;y ken,</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;y self ech del;</L>
<L>&THORN;o segge&thorn; &thorn;ys lerede men,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;o</I>, read <I>so</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L N="176">And clypye&thorn; hyt 'actuel.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="45" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys manere senne nys nau&yogh;t ones,</L>
<L>Ac hys ischyt in &thorn;ry,</L>
<L>In &thorn;ou&yogh;t, in speche, in dede amys,</L>
<L N="180">&THORN;ys may ech man ysy.
<PB REF="00000123.tif" N="105"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="46" TYPE="stanza">
<L>He &thorn;at ne &thorn;ynke&thorn; nau&yogh;t bote wel,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ne</I> over the line in MS.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="108"></L>
<L>And speke&thorn; and do&thorn; al ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;e man hys sckere of actuel,</L>
<L N="184">Ac ho hys here so bry&yogh;t?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ho</I> = <I>who</I>, as in l. 185; MS. <I>he</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="47" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ho hys he &thorn;at al be&thorn; wel</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;o&yogh;tes &thorn;at he kak&thorn;e?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>kak&thorn;e</I>, read <I>kek&thorn;</I>, from <I>kec</I>[<I>c</I>]<I>he</I>, to catch?</NOTE></L>
<L>And who hys &thorn;at speke scheal</L>
<L N="188">Ary&yogh;t al &thorn;at he speke&thorn;?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="48" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And wo hys he &thorn;at alnewe[y]</L>
<L>de&thorn; wel al &thorn;at he de&thorn;?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>de&thorn;</I> in MS. at the end of the preceding line.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="194b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>No man, no man, ac ny&yogh;t and day</L>
<L N="192">&THORN;ys men by-soyled be&thorn;,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="49" TYPE="stanza">
<L>So as hy be&thorn; men, ase we see&thorn;,</L>
<L>Wy&thorn; sennes al &thorn;or&yogh;-&thorn;erled :<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;or&yogh;</I>-<I>&thorn;erled</I>, read <I>&thorn;or&yogh;</I>-<I>&thorn;erle</I> (O.E. <I>&thorn;urh</I>-<I>&thorn;&ymacr;rel</I>, adj.), and the corre|sponding ryme-word <I>werdle</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L>Many hys &thorn;e senne &thorn;at me de&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>de&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>do&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="196">In tal &thorn;e wyde wordle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="50" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of senne ich wot by &thorn;yse sckele<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sckele</I>, MS. <I>sckyle</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;er hijs wel great host;</L>
<L>And, for &thorn;e fend iuint so fele,</L>
<L N="200">&THORN;er-of hys alle hys host.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="51" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And he araye&thorn; hare trome</L>
<L>As me a-reyt men in fy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For he syk&thorn; gode &thorn;eawes some<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>some</I> in MS. at the beginning of the following line.</NOTE></L>
<L N="204">A-&yogh;enes ham ydy&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000124.tif" N="106"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="52" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And ase god dy&yogh;t &thorn;eawes<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>dy&yogh;t</I>, MS. <I>dyst</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>In alle gode men,</L>
<L>&THORN;e feend a-raye&thorn; &thorn;e schreawes</L>
<L N="208">In wykken &thorn;er a-&yogh;en.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="53" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys hys &thorn;at fy&yogh;t an er&thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at al wyn&thorn; o&thorn;er lest,</L>
<L>And ase &thorn;e fy&yogh;ttere hys werthe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>werthe</I>, MS. <I>worthe</I>, written at the beginning of the following line.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="109"></L>
<L N="212">&THORN;e cheueteyn hym chest.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="54" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac cheueteyn of senne</L>
<L>Ich wot &thorn;at &thorn;e fend hys,</L>
<L>For wyse, and alle kenne</L>
<L N="216">Araye&thorn; hys amys.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Araye&thorn;</I> MS.; Wr. <I>Arayes</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="55" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And ase &thorn;ere in bataylle</L>
<L>O kyng bere&thorn; &thorn;e bee&yogh;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bee&yogh;</I>, MS. <I>bee&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Soe hyt were a gret faylle</L>
<L N="220">&YOGH;ef &thorn;e host were em-he&yogh;.<MILESTONE N="195a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="56" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er-fore me make&thorn; prynses</L>
<L>&THORN;e host to gouerni,</L>
<L>And ase whe-welen &thorn;e linses</L>
<L N="224">To-gadere helde&thorn; hy.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="57" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And ase al &thorn;at hys here</L>
<L>By soueda&yogh;es ge&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>soueda&yogh;es</I> = <I>seue da&yogh;es</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of senne alle manere</L>
<L N="228">Seue deuelen prynces be&thorn; :</L>
</LG>
<LG N="58" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at seuene certeygne<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>seuene</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;ene</I>. Read <I>&thorn;e seuene</I>? or <I>&thorn;at be&thorn; &thorn;e seuene</I>? (cp. p. 89, l. 105)&mdash;or omit <I>&thorn;at</I> before <I>Cryst</I> in the following line?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at Cryst kest out, hyt sey&thorn;
<PB REF="00000125.tif" N="107"></L>
<L>Of marie maudaleyne</L>
<L N="232">&THORN;at goospel &thorn;at ne wey&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wey&thorn;</I>. K&ouml;lbing writes <I>le&yogh;&thorn;</I>, and l. 230 <I>se&yogh;&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="59" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e ferste pryns hys prede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lede&thorn; &thorn;ane flok,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of alle o&thorn;ere onlede</L>
<L N="236">Hys rote and eke stok.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="60" TYPE="stanza">
<L>For nys non of &thorn;e syxe</L>
<L>&THORN;at hy ne come&thorn; of &thorn;ane,</L>
<L>For myx of alle myxe</L>
<L N="240">In heuene hy by-gan.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="61" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Prede suwe&thorn; in floures<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="110"></L>
<L>Of wysdom and of wyt,</L>
<L>Amang leuedys in boures</L>
<L N="244">&THORN;e foule prude sy&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="62" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vnder couele and cope</L>
<L>&THORN;e foule prede ly&thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;e&yogh; man go gert wy&thorn; rope,</L>
<L N="248">&yogh;et prede to hym swy&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="63" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Prede sy&yogh;t vnder ragge</L>
<L>Wel cobel and wel balg&thorn;;<MILESTONE N="195b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at ke&thorn;e&thorn; wordes bragge</L>
<L N="252">And countenaunces &yogh;alde&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="foot">249-252. See note.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="64" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nys non, &thorn;a&yogh; som myt wene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at some prede ne take&thorn;,</L>
<L>Ne none so proud, ich wene,</L>
<L N="256">As he &thorn;at al for-sake&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="65" TYPE="stanza">
<L>For who hys &thorn;at neuere set hys &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And er&thorn;e to be he&yogh;?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he&yogh;</I>, MS. <I>hy&yogh;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Who hys hit &thorn;at neuer y&thorn;ou&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">Read <I>&thorn;at neuer</I> [<I>he&thorn;</I>] <I>y&thorn;o&yogh;t</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L N="260">Of pompe &thorn;at he se&yogh;?
<PB REF="00000126.tif" N="108"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="66" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Who yst &thorn;at neuer nas rebel</L>
<L>A&yogh;eins hys souerayn?</L>
<L>Wo ist &thorn;at be nome schel,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ist</I>, MS. <I>hist</I>, the <I>h</I> underdotted. For the sense of ll. 263-4 see note.</NOTE></L>
<L N="264">And nabbe non agayn?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="67" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Who yst &thorn;at neuere gollich nas,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>yst</I>, MS. <I>hyst, h</I> underdotted.&mdash;<I>gollich</I>, MS. <I>godlich</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wanne chaunce at wylle come?</L>
<L>Who yst &thorn;at, wanne he preysed was,</L>
<L N="268">Neuer at he&yogh; hyt nome?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="68" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Who hyst &thorn;at neuer &thorn;o&yogh;te</L>
<L>He scholde honoured be</L>
<L>For dedes &thorn;at he wroute,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="111"></L>
<L N="272">Wanne men (ne) hy&yogh;t mytte se?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="69" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Who hys &thorn;at neuer he&yogh;&thorn;e dro&yogh;</L>
<L>Toward hys &thorn;at wes?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wes</I>, MS. <I>was</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ho hys [&thorn;at] neuer ne kedde wo&yogh;</L>
<L N="276">In boste to hys sugges?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="70" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ho ne&thorn; wy&thorn; pompe y-schewed hym</L>
<L>&YOGH;et o&thorn;er &thorn;ane he was?</L>
<L>Nou ypocresy, kepe nym,</L>
<L N="280">Regne&thorn;, hyt nys no leas.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="71" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ho yst &thorn;at neuer nas yblent<MILESTONE N="196a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wy&thorn; non surquydery?</L>
<L>&THORN;at hys, wanne a proud man he&thorn; y-ment<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he&thorn; y-ment</I> in MS. at the beginning of the following line, with a dot after it.</NOTE></L>
<L N="284">O&thorn;er &thorn;ane hyt schel by.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="72" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wo &thorn;at neuer ne dede &thorn;ous</L>
<L>He wole prede by-fle&yogh;;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wole</I>, see note.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;ef &thorn;at kebbede eny of ous,</L>
<L N="288">Ich wo&yogh;t wel &thorn;at he le&yogh;.
<PB REF="00000127.tif" N="109"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="73" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e man &thorn;e hym wole a-fayty</L>
<L>Of prede &thorn;at hys so he&yogh;,</L>
<L>Fol wel he mo&yogh;t hys weyti</L>
<L N="292">Bo&thorn;e fer and ne&yogh;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="74" TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &yogh;ef he let to no&thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne awayte&thorn; hy,</L>
<L>Ich segge hym wel to so&thorn;e</L>
<L N="296">&THORN;at ry&yogh;t proud schel he by.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>by</I>, MS. <I>be</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="75" TYPE="stanza">
<L>For prede hys a senne of herte,</L>
<L>And bouute schewe&thorn; hy</L>
<L>Wy&thorn; kebbynges aperte</L>
<L N="300">And weddyng many a bly:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>weddyng</I> for <I>wedyng</I>, clothing, O.E. <I>&yogh;ew&aelig;&macr;dian?&mdash;many a bly</I> (O.E. <I>bl&iacute;o</I>), MS. <I>manyable</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="76" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;or&yogh; dedes of bostynge,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="112"></L>
<L>And atyr stent and say,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>stent</I> for <I>stend</I>, pa. pple., O.E. <I>st&aelig;&macr;nan</I>, to adorn with precious stones?&mdash;<I>say</I>, read <I>gay</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L>And o&thorn;er suche &thorn;ynge(s)</L>
<L N="304">&THORN;at men vsye&thorn; al day.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="77" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er feend of onde</L>
<L>Hys pryns and cheuetayn;</L>
<L>&THORN;at senne hys ryf in londe,</L>
<L N="308">And nau&yogh;t hys hyre wayn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="78" TYPE="stanza">
<L>For sorwe he he&thorn; of gode,</L>
<L>And harm hys hyre blysse;<MILESTONE N="196b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In hyre pryncy mode<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pryncy</I>, read <I>pryncely</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L N="312">&THORN;e hert[e] walt al &thorn;ys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="79" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys senne hys ouer-nyce,</L>
<L>Ac holde schal hy be</L>
<L>&THORN;e senne of meste malice</L>
<L N="316">A&yogh;eyns charyte;
<PB REF="00000128.tif" N="110"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="80" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wanne loue hys here preye,</L>
<L>Al for to confundy,</L>
<L>And wyl het to by-traye<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>het</I> for <I>he&thorn;</I>, as l. 339.</NOTE></L>
<L N="320">&THORN;at wolde gode by.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="81" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Onde hys a senne of herte,</L>
<L>And bouute schewe&thorn; hy,<NOTE PLACE="foot">After <I>schewe&thorn;</I> an underdotted <I>w</I> is written in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>To harmy and to herte,</L>
<L N="324">Wanne hy de&thorn; bacbyty;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="82" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wanne hy holde&thorn; hy wreches<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wreches</I>, MS. <I>werches</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at god and hende be&thorn;,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ere souche plecches<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>plecches</I>, MS. <I>plocches?</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="328">Schewe&thorn; wat onde de&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="83" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;rydde senne hys wrethe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at so meche hys itelde;</L>
<L>Hyt make&thorn; blod and brethe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>brethe</I>, MS. <I>breche</I> (or <I>broche</I>).</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="113"></L>
<L N="332">Aboute &thorn;e herte aneld.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="84" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wanne manne ne&thorn; nau&yogh;t hys chaunce<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>chaunce</I>, MS. <I>thonse</I>, for <I>chonse</I>, a possible form; if we retain it, we have to alter the corresponding ryme-word <I>veniaunce</I> to <I>venionse</I> (cp. p. 94, l. 248).</NOTE></L>
<L>to wylle, and alse &thorn;enk&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to wylle</I> in MS. at the end of the preceding line.&mdash;<I>alse</I> = <I>alse he</I>.&mdash; <I>&thorn;enk&thorn;</I> [: <I>clenke&thorn;</I>], MS. <I>&thorn;ynthe</I>. We may as well write <I>&thorn;eng&thorn;</I> [: <I>cleng&thorn;</I>].</NOTE></L>
<L>He compasy&thorn; veniaunce</L>
<L N="336">To hym &thorn;at a-&yogh;en clenke&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="85" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And so hyt fret and hys y-frete</L>
<L>Euere in egrete,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in egrete</I>, MS. <I>megrete, i</I>-stroke wanting.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wanne hy het to meche hete,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hy</I>, read <I>hyt?&mdash;het</I> = <I>he&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="340">Hyt lette&thorn; charite.<MILESTONE N="197a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000129.tif" N="111"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="86" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Inne herte hys &thorn;ys senne&yogh;ing,</L>
<L>And bouute schewe&thorn; mod</L>
<L>&THORN;or&yogh; cheste and mysdoynge</L>
<L N="344">And wy&thorn;-drawynge of god.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="87" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Coueytyse hys &thorn;e fer&thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fer&thorn;e</I>, MS. <I>furte</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ilych dropesy,</L>
<L>Wanne al &thorn;at hys an er&thorn;e</L>
<L N="348">To hyre hys al besy.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="88" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And hou hy habbe&thorn; hy uerk&thorn;,</L>
<L>And mannes herte byset,</L>
<L>Fram gode and so &thorn;anne name y-ke&yogh;t</L>
<L N="352">Seruise of mamenet.<NOTE PLACE="foot">349-352. See note.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="89" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; hy by herte senne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;a&yogh;</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;at</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;et boute schewe&thorn; hy<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>schewe&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>scheut&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>To mochel amang mankenne</L>
<L N="356">&THORN;or&yogh; wrang an trychery;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="90" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;or&yogh; &yogh;eskynge efter gode,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&yogh;eskynge fram</I> (expuncted) <I>efter</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;or&yogh; bor&yogh; and &yogh;emer &yogh;elde,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw wrechydnesse of mode,</L>
<L N="360">And neuer more ful-felde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="91" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e fyfte senne hys sleu&thorn;e<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="114"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;at man scholde do,</L>
<L>Hye breke&thorn; god[e] treu&thorn;e</L>
<L N="364">Wy&thorn; god and man also,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="92" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wanne man lete&thorn; adrylle</L>
<L>&THORN;at he god &yogh;elde schel,</L>
<L>And for-sluggy&thorn; by wylle<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for-sluggy&thorn;</I>, MS. -<I>slaggy&thorn;</I> (corrected N.E.D.).</NOTE></L>
<L N="368">&THORN;at scholde men to stel.
<PB REF="00000130.tif" N="112"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="93" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of herte come&thorn; &thorn;es senne,</L>
<L>And schewe[&thorn;] boute al-so<MILESTONE N="197b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Hou hy lette&thorn; mankenne</L>
<L N="372">Of &thorn;at scholde by do.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="94" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hyt hys &thorn;orwe besynesse</L>
<L>&THORN;at men for-slewy&thorn; hyt,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er wyle &thorn;or&yogh; &yogh;delnesse</L>
<L N="376">God dede onido for-slyt.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>onido</I>, MS. <I>enido</I> (the <I>i</I>'s have no stroke).</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="95" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Glotonye hys &thorn;e syxte,</L>
<L>And hys mo ine fleasch y-do;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mo</I>, MS. <I>me</I> or <I>ine</I>, of which the following <I>ine</I> may be only a dittograph.</NOTE></L>
<L>And lecherye, &thorn;e nyxte,</L>
<L N="380">In flesche hys senne al-so.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>in flesche</I> in MS. at the end of the preceding line.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="96" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac glotonye entycy&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>entycy&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>enty&thorn;y&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>To lecherye her,</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;at hy norysse&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">After <I>norysse&thorn;, hote</I> (expuncted). ll. 383-4 probably ought to run thus :&mdash;
<Q><L><I>&THORN;at hy</I> [<I>also</I>] <I>norysse&thorn;</I></L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L><I>Ase hote brondes &thorn;et fer</I>.</L>
<L N="384">Hote brondes &thorn;et fere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="97" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of glotonyes foure<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>glotonyes foure</I>, K&ouml;lbing's emendation; MS. <I>glotonye hys four</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e boke speke&thorn; openlyche:</L>
<L>To meche fode deuoury,</L>
<L N="388">And to lykerouslyche,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="98" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And to freche to fretene<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>, MS. <I>Ando</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wanne man hijs tyme he&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>man</I>, MS. <I>men</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And out of tyme to hetene<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="115"></L>
<L N="392">&THORN;at none siknesse ne&thorn;.
<PB REF="00000131.tif" N="113"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="99" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of lecherye come&thorn; wreche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wreche</I> in MS. at the beginning of the following line.</NOTE></L>
<L>Foul speche, and foul delyt,</L>
<L>Commune hordom, spousbreche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>spousbreche</I> in MS. at the beginning of next line.</NOTE></L>
<L N="396">Incest, and sodomyt.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sodomyt, t</I> altered from <I>e</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="100" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And hys incest wy&thorn; kenne</L>
<L>&THORN;e lecherye so;</L>
<L>And sodomyt hys senne</L>
<L N="400">A&yogh;ens kende y-do.<MILESTONE N="198a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="101" TYPE="stanza">
<L>By-feld be&thorn; men in slepe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>slepe</I>, MS. <I>sleau&thorn;e;</I> see note.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ase glotonye hyt brynge&thorn;;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>brynge&thorn;</I>: <I>&thorn;encke&thorn;</I>, read <I>breng&thorn;</I> : <I>&thorn;eng&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ofte hyt do&thorn; moni kepe</L>
<L N="404">&THORN;at man wakynge &thorn;encke&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>brynge&thorn;</I> : <I>&thorn;encke&thorn;</I>, read <I>breng&thorn;</I> : <I>&thorn;eng&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="102" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac &yogh;ef euyl hyt come nau&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Dea[d]lyche senne next.</L>
<L>Ac hou hyt falle&thorn; y-lome ne&yogh;.</L>
<L N="408">Ech man nau&yogh;t y-wyst.<NOTE PLACE="foot">405-408. I have transcribed these lines as they are written in the MS.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="103" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;yse manere sennes seuene,</L>
<L>Ase &yogh;e hys here ise&yogh;e&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;e</I>, MS. <I>he</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>I-lette&thorn; men fram heuene,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>I-lette&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>Me lette&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="412">And al dedlyche hy be&thorn;,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="104" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wanne hy y-&thorn;ou&yogh;t be&thorn; o&thorn;er y-speke,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er y-don in stat</L>
<L>A&yogh;e &thorn;e lawe of god, to breke</L>
<L N="416">&THORN;e hestes &thorn;at he hat.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="105" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of alle &thorn;e sennes &thorn;a[t] &thorn;er be&thorn;</L>
<L>&THORN;os bere&thorn; &thorn;at los;
<PB REF="00000132.tif" N="114"></L>
<L>For euerech senne &thorn;at me de&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>de&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>do&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="420">Longe&thorn; to some of &thorn;os.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;os</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;es</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="106" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And her-by &thorn;ou my&yogh;t, man, y-seo<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I> in MS. at the beginning of the following line.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="116"></L>
<L>hou here ende hys sour;</L>
<L>Nou loke her-in, pur charite,</L>
<L N="424">And make hyt &thorn;y myrour.</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Oretis pro anima domini Willelmi de Schorham, quondam vicarii de chart iuxta ledes, qui composuit istam compilacionem de septem mortalibus peccatis. Et omni|bus dicentibus oracionem<MILESTONE N="198b" UNIT="folio">dominicam cum salutacione angelica, &chi;l<SUP>a</SUP> dies uenie, a domino Symone, Archiepiscopo cantuarie, conceduntur.</TRAILER>


</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="5" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000133.tif" N="115">
<HEAD>V. [The Five Joys of the Virgin Mary.]</HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<L>MEche hys &thorn;at me synge&thorn; and rede&thorn;,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="117"></L>
<L>Of hyre &thorn;at al mankende glede&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>glede&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>glade&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3">Ibore was here on erthe;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ey alle speke, &thorn;at speke&thorn; wyd tonge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ey</I> = <I>&thorn;e&yogh;.&mdash;alle speke</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;ey I alle speke</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of hyre worschype, and murye sounge,</L>
<L N="6">&YOGH;et more he were werthe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he</I> = <I>hy;</I> so, too, ll. 8, 12, 16.&mdash;<I>werthe</I>, MS. <I>worthe</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;yse aungeles herye&thorn; here wy&thorn; steuene,</L>
<L>Ase he hys hare quene of heue[ne],</L>
<L N="9">And eke hare blysse;</L>
<L>Ouer al er&thorn;e leuedy hys here,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hys</I> = <I>hy ys;</I> so, too, l. 17.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;or&yogh;-out helle ge&thorn; here power,</L>
<L N="12">Ase he hys emperysse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Cause of alle &thorn;yse dignyte,</L>
<L>&THORN;or&yogh; clennesse and humylyte,</L>
<L N="15">Was godes owene grace;</L>
<L>Wer-&thorn;or&yogh; he ber &thorn;an heuene kyng :</L>
<L>Worschype hys wor&thorn;y ine alle &thorn;yng,</L>
<L N="18">In euereche place.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Al &thorn;at hys boue and vnder molde,</L>
<L>Hou my&yogh;t hyt bote hyt bowe scholde</L>
<L N="21">To hyre owene mede?</L>
<L>Wanne he &thorn;at al &thorn;ys wordle schel welde</L>
<L>To hyre worschipe hys yhelde</L>
<L N="24">For here moder-hede.
<PB REF="00000134.tif" N="116"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Al &thorn;yse maydenes, wy&thorn;-out bost,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="118"></L>
<L>Hy bere&thorn; god in here goste,</L>
<L N="27">In hare holy &thorn;ou&yogh;t[e];<MILESTONE N="199a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ac hy wy&thorn;-oute mannes ymone</L>
<L>In body, and nau&yogh;t in gost a-lone,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>alone</I>, MS. <I>aboue</I> (Wr. corr.).</NOTE></L>
<L N="30">To manne hyne broute.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of hyre &thorn;at hys &thorn;os dygne of take,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of take</I>, read <I>op-take</I>, assumpta? M&auml;tzner writes <I>of lake</I> (O.E. <I>l&amacr;c</I>, gift, offering).</NOTE></L>
<L>Hou my&yogh;te ich of hyre songes make,</L>
<L N="33">&THORN;at am so foul of lyue?</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou me bede, soster, synge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>, read <I>Ac</I>? (K&ouml;lbing's conjecture).</NOTE></L>
<L>And alle in-to one songe brynge</L>
<L N="36">Here swete ioyen fyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<L>To segge &thorn;at ich hyt maky can,</L>
<L>&THORN;at am so one-connende a man,</L>
<L N="39">Dar ich me nau&yogh;t auanty;</L>
<L>Ac tryste ich wolle to oure leuedy,</L>
<L>And maky hyt ase hyt wyle by,</L>
<L N="42">And ase hy hy[t] wole me granty.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hy hy</I>[<I>t</I>], MS. <I>hy hy;</I> M&auml;tzner omits one <I>hy.&mdash;wole</I>, distinctly so in MS.; Wr. <I>wolde</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<L>As man ine hys by-leaue yse&thorn;,</L>
<L>Ioyen of hyre so fele &thorn;er be&thorn;,</L>
<L N="45">Ne may hys no man telle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hys</I> (not <I>hyt</I>) in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ase hy ha&thorn; of hyre leue sone:</L>
<L>Hyt passe&thorn; al mankendes wone,</L>
<L N="48">And out of mannes spelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Four manere ioyen hy hedde here</L>
<L>Of hyre sone so lef an dere,</L>
<L N="51">Wytnes opan &thorn;e godspelle;
<PB REF="00000135.tif" N="117"></L>
<L>And al[le] come&thorn; of &thorn;e blysse<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of &thorn;e</I>, MS. <I>ofte &thorn;e</I> (M&auml;tzner corr.).</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="119"></L>
<L>&THORN;at hye he&thorn; nou, wy&thorn;-oute mysse,</L>
<L N="54">So stremes of &thorn;e welle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e wylle &thorn;at hys in paradys</L>
<L>Fol wel by-tokne&thorn; &thorn;ys auys,</L>
<L N="57">Wy&thorn; here stremes foure,<MILESTONE N="199b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;et orne&thorn; out ouer al &thorn;at londe,</L>
<L>Nys neuer er&thorn;lyche man &thorn;at fond<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nys</I>, read <I>Nes</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">Hou fele come of &thorn;e stoure.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys wulle hys god self man by-come,</L>
<L>Of hym &thorn;ys ioyen be&thorn; alle y-nome,</L>
<L N="63">And alle ine uour manere:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>uour</I>, MS. <I>nout</I>, M&auml;tzner <I>noue</I> = new; but cp. l. 49.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e furste was wy&thorn; concepcioun,</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e angel gabryel come a-doun</L>
<L N="66">Ine stede of messager[e],</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<L>To brynge &thorn;e ty&thorn;ynge by-fore</L>
<L>&THORN;at cryst of hyre wolde by bore,</L>
<L N="69">Mannes trespas to &yogh;elde,</L>
<L>For to brynge ous out of helle:</L>
<L>Wo mytte &thorn;enche o&thorn;er telle<NOTE PLACE="foot">An <I>o</I> has been cancelled after <I>mytte</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="72">Wat ioye &thorn;er y uelde!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<L>In na&yogh;areth, &thorn;e ryche toun,</L>
<L><I>Aue maria</I> was &thorn;at soun</L>
<L N="75">Of gabrieles steuene;</L>
<L>&THORN;o was &thorn;at mayde wel ygret,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wel</I> is the reading of the MS.; Wr. <I>was</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wy&thorn; a present wel ageet<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wel ageet</I>, M&auml;tzner <I>weleget</I> (for <I>weleged</I>), enriched; see note.</NOTE></L>
<L N="78">Fram vader oure of heuene.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<L>So he was ine hyre ycome,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="120"></L>
<L>For fleasch and blod of hyre to nome,</L>
<L N="81">Ase &thorn;e angel hyre seyde;
<PB REF="00000136.tif" N="118"></L>
<L>Ne hy of mannes mone neste,</L>
<L>Ne hy ne brek nau&yogh;t hyre by-heste,</L>
<L N="84">Ac euere clene a mayde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>, read <I>As</I>?</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt johan &thorn;e baptyst on-bore,</L>
<L>&THORN;o hy spek hys moder by-fore,</L>
<L N="87">Ine ioye he gan to asprynge.<MILESTONE N="200a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ely&yogh;abet wel &thorn;at aspyde,</L>
<L>Hou a spylede onder hyre syde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hyre</I>, MS. <I>hys</I> (M&auml;tzner corr.).</NOTE></L>
<L N="90">And made hys reioyynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<L>More encheyson hadde oure leuedy</L>
<L>Ioyous and bly&thorn;e for to by,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>by</I>, MS. <I>be</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="93">Wy&thorn;-oute prede and boste;</L>
<L>For in hyre selue hy hyne fredde,</L>
<L>Fol wel hy wyste hou [hy] hyne hedde<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>hy</I>] inserted by M&auml;tzner.</NOTE></L>
<L N="96">&THORN;or&yogh; self &thorn;e holy goste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ioseph kedde &thorn;at he was mylde,</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at he wyste hy was wy&thorn; chylde,</L>
<L N="99">A-wey he wolde alone;</L>
<L>Ha nolde nau&yogh;t he were a-slawe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he</I> = <I>hy;</I> so, too, l. 111.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne for&thorn;e y-iuged by &thorn;e lawe</L>
<L N="102">To by stend wy&thorn; stone.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac ioseph was wel bly&thorn;e, aply&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;o to hym cam &thorn;e angel bry&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&THORN;o</I>, MS. <I>So</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="105">To segge hym wat he scholde;</L>
<L>Wel bly&thorn;&thorn;ere my&yogh;te be &thorn;at may,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="121"></L>
<L>&THORN;at was y-conforted al day</L>
<L N="108">Wy&thorn; aungeles wanne hy wolde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<L>In &thorn;yssere ioye we scholde by-louken</L>
<L>Al hyre ioyen of uourti woken</L>
<L N="111">&THORN;e wylest he &yogh;ede wy&thorn; chylde.
<PB REF="00000137.tif" N="119"></L>
<L>Of hyre [barme] hyt was god game,<NOTE PLACE="foot">See note.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er-inne &thorn;et vnicorn weks tame</L>
<L N="114">&THORN;at er &thorn;an was so wylde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;an</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;ang</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;et o&thorn;er ioye of hyre ycore</L>
<L>Was of ihesus, of hyre ybore</L>
<L N="117">A crystemasse ny&yogh;te,<MILESTONE N="200b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wy&thorn;-oute sor&yogh;e, wy&thorn;-oute sore;</L>
<L>And so ne schal &thorn;er neuer more</L>
<L N="120">Wymman wy&thorn; childe dy&yogh;te.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>dy&yogh;te</I>, M&auml;tzner proposes <I>be dy&yogh;te</I>. Perhaps we ought to read <I>hyt dy&yogh;te</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<L>For so hy hyne scholde ferst auonge,</L>
<L>&THORN;er nes no senne &thorn;er amonge,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nes</I> (M&auml;tzner <I>nas</I>), MS. <I>nys</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="123">Ne noe flesches lykynge;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore of hyre y-bore he was,</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;e sonne passe&yogh;t &thorn;or&yogh; &thorn;e glas</L>
<L N="126">Wy&thorn;-outen on openynge.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omission of <I>on</I> proposed by M&auml;tzner.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<L>In sua&thorn;ebendes hy hyne dy&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Ase hyt hys &thorn;e chyldes ry&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="129">And &yogh;ef hym melk to souke;</L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; hyt were &thorn;ustre of ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;er nas wane of no ly&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="132">&THORN;e heuene gan onlouke.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Out com an aungel wy&thorn; great leem<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>leem</I>, second <I>e</I>, being written close to the <I>m</I>, looks like <I>o</I> in MS.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="122"></L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e feld of bedleem,</L>
<L N="135">Amonges &thorn;e schepherden,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>schep-</I>, MS. <I>schop</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L>Te telle &thorn;at cryst was ybore;</L>
<L>&THORN;er come singinde &thorn;er-fore</L>
<L N="138">Of angeles manye verden.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;anne sede he swy&thorn;e wel</L>
<L><I>Gracia plena</I>, gabryel,</L>
<L N="141">And &thorn;at hys "fol of grace";
<PB REF="00000138.tif" N="120"></L>
<L>Wanne glorye of hyre hys fol a-boue,</L>
<L>And pays igrad for hyre loue</L>
<L N="144">Of angeles in place.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e oxe and asse in hare manyour,</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at hy se&yogh;en hare creatour<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>creatour</I>, MS. <I>creature</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="147">Lyggynde in hare forage,<MILESTONE N="201a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Al one-knowynge &thorn;a&yogh; hy were,</L>
<L>Hy makede ioye in hare manere,</L>
<L N="150">And eke in hare langage.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ope &thorn;e he&yogh;e e&yogh;tynde day</L>
<L>He onder-&yogh;ede &thorn;e gywen lay,</L>
<L N="153">And was ycircumcysed.</L>
<L>Iesus me clepede hyne &thorn;er-uore,</L>
<L>Ase aungeles, er he were ybore,</L>
<L N="156">Hys eldren hadde y-wysed.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mochele ioye hy aspyde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e kynges &thorn;re &thorn;at come ryde</L>
<L N="159">Fram be easte wel iverre;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Wr. <I>i-verre</I>, MS. <I>werre</I> (distinctly).</NOTE></L>
<L>Gold, myrre, stor, were here offrynges,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="123"></L>
<L>&THORN;at he was lord and kyng of kynges</L>
<L N="162">Wel by-toknede &thorn;e sterre.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at he scholde y-offred by<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>by</I>, MS. <I>be</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e <I>templo domini</I>,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>templo</I>, so MS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="165">Ase la&yogh;e &yogh;ef &thorn;e termes,</L>
<L>Symeon, &thorn;e olde man, gan crye,</L>
<L>And spek of hym fur prophecye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fur</I> = <I>for</I> (M&auml;tzner); or ought we to read <I>&thorn;or&yogh;</I> (also spelt <I>&thorn;our&yogh;</I>)?</NOTE></L>
<L N="168">And tok hym ine hys earmes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;o he was bote twelf wynter ald,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he</I>, MS. <I>&yogh;e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And he&yogh; ine &thorn;e temple he seat wel bald,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I> (= <I>An</I>) <I>he&yogh;</I>, MS. <I>he&yogh; he</I>, but the <I>he</I> has been cancelled.</NOTE></L>
<L N="171">And &thorn;a&yogh; he speke smale,
<PB REF="00000139.tif" N="121"></L>
<L>Many man wondrede on hym &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>For to alle clerkes &thorn;at &thorn;er were</L>
<L N="174">He &yogh;af answere and tale.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alyue uertu was hys childe-hode,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Alyue</I>, read <I>Al yne</I>? cp. p. 123, l. 253, <I>Al ine ioye was hyre mende.&mdash;chylde-hode</I>, MS. -<I>ho&thorn;e</I>, the &thorn; not quite distinct.</NOTE></L>
<L>And so he com to hys manhode;</L>
<L N="177">Ine flom iordanes syche<MILESTONE N="201b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He was ycrystned, &thorn;e heuene onleake,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fader of heuene doun to hym spake,</L>
<L N="180">&THORN;e gost com coluere ylyche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<L>To &thorn;yssere ioye longye scholle</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e ioyen &thorn;at hyre folle</L>
<L N="183">Of hyre chylde god,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Read <I>Of hyre chyld &thorn;e gode</I>? cp. p. 126, l. 348, <I>iesus &thorn;e gode</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fram &thorn;an tyme he was ybore</L>
<L>For al mankende &thorn;at was for-lore,</L>
<L N="186">For[t] he deyde one &thorn;e roude.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Fort</I>, until (M&auml;tzner), MS. <I>For</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E &thorn;rydde ioye &thorn;at com of cryste<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="124"></L>
<L>Hadde oure leuedy of hys opryste</L>
<L N="189">Fram dea&thorn;es harde bende,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e sepulcre &thorn;er he laye,</L>
<L>Ase hyt fel &thorn;ane &thorn;rydde daye</L>
<L N="192">After hys lyues ende.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wet ioye of hym my&yogh;te be more</L>
<L>After suiche sor&yogh;ynge and swyche sore,</L>
<L N="195">Ase hye yseye hine feye,</L>
<L>&THORN;anne isi&yogh;e hyne come to lyue a&yogh;en,</L>
<L>And euereft more alyue to ben,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omit <I>And</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L N="198">And neuere eft to dey&yogh;e?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at he was lyf and streng&thorn;e and my&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he kedde on Estre ny&yogh;tte,</L>
<L N="201">Al ine &thorn;e dawyynge :
<PB REF="00000140.tif" N="122"></L>
<L>Al &thorn;a[t] was an erthe schok,</L>
<L>And heuene aboue vnder-toke</L>
<L N="204">Hys holy vppe-rysynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ar doun come aungeles whyte ine wede,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he was aryse hy sede,</L>
<L N="207">And hare sawe was trewe;<MILESTONE N="202a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne laye nau&yogh;t vnder molde</L>
<L>For to a-saye, ho so wolde,</L>
<L N="210">&THORN;ane stone hye ouer-&thorn;rewe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; &thorn;at he ine hys manho&thorn; deyde,</L>
<L><I>Dominus</I> tecum &thorn;at a seyde,</L>
<L N="213">&THORN;o &thorn;e aungel here by-redde,</L>
<L>(&THORN;at hys to seggene "god es my&yogh;tte"),<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>godes my&yogh;tte; my&yogh;tte</I> = <I>mytte, myd &thorn;e</I>.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="125"></L>
<L>Ine ry&yogh;te so&thorn;e hyt moste sitte<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sitte;</I> M&auml;tzner <I>fitte</I>, i. e. <I>fi&yogh;te</I>, fight.</NOTE></L>
<L N="216">&THORN;et god-ho&thorn; wel hyt kedde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nedde oure leuedy &thorn;yse blysse a-lone,</L>
<L>Ac al hyre frendes in hyre mone,</L>
<L N="219">So meche was here &thorn;e more;</L>
<L>For more hijs blysse god and clene</L>
<L>Among frendes to habbe ymene,</L>
<L N="222">After sor&yogh;ynge and sore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<L>O &thorn;at hy were bly&thorn;e, &thorn;o hye (here) se&yogh;en<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>here</I> MS.; Wr. <I>were</I> (omitted by M&auml;tzner).&mdash;<I>se&yogh;en</I>, MS. <I>si&yogh;en</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>So glorious alyue, wy&thorn; here e&yogh;en,</L>
<L N="225">&THORN;et hy yseye er ine paygne!</L>
<L>Furste a schewed hym wy&thorn; a fayre chaunce</L>
<L>To here &thorn;et hys ensample of repentaunce,</L>
<L N="228">Marye magdaleyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And so hyseye hyne peter, and se&thorn;enes hy alle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hyseye</I> = <I>yseye</I> = <I>yse&yogh;</I>, saw; MS. <I>hygeye</I>, M&auml;tzner <I>hygede</I>, hied.&mdash;<I>se&thorn;enes</I>, first <I>e</I> resembling <I>o;</I> Wr. <I>sothenes</I>, M&auml;tzner <I>sothes</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;er thomas of ynde, a k[n]owes yfalle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>k</I>[<I>n</I>]<I>owes</I>, corrected by M&auml;tzner.</NOTE></L>
<L N="231">Groped hys holy wounde;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Groped</I>, MS. <I>Croped;</I> cp. l. 240.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000141.tif" N="123"></L>
<L>&THORN;are he fond flesch and blod myd &thorn;e bones,</L>
<L>An nou he gan to crye loude for &thorn;e nones:</L>
<L N="234">"My lord ich abbe y-founde."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Houre lord hym answerde in &thorn;et cas:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou leuedest, for &thorn;ou se&yogh;e me, thomas,</L>
<L N="237">&THORN;at &thorn;ou me haddest y-founde;<MILESTONE N="202b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ac, thomas, ich &thorn;e telle, yblessed hy be&thorn;,</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at on me by-leue&thorn; and nau&yogh;t me se&thorn;,</L>
<L N="240">Ne gropye&thorn; none wounde."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="41" TYPE="stanza">
<L>To &thorn;yssere ioyen scholle by yleyd<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="126"></L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e ioyen &thorn;at mo&yogh;e be yseyd,</L>
<L N="243">Ine wyttes o&thorn;er in mende,</L>
<L>Fram crystes resurreccioun,</L>
<L>Wat come&thorn; hys ascensioun</L>
<L N="246">At fourty da&yogh;en ende.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>da&yogh;en</I>, MS. <I>sa&yogh;en</I> (Wr. corr.).</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="42" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E fer&thorn;e ioye telle ich may,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&THORN;e fer&thorn;e</I> in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at fel opon &thorn;e holy &thorn;oresday,</L>
<L N="249">Opone a mounteyne he&yogh;e;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mounteyne</I>, MS. <I>mounte yne</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hi se&yogh; ihesus, and o&thorn;re some,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Hi</I> (not <I>he</I>) in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of flesch and blod of hyre ynome,</L>
<L N="252">Op in-to heuene ste&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="43" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Al ine ioye was hyre mende,</L>
<L>&THORN;o hy se&yogh;e here and oure kende,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&THORN;o</I>, MS. <I>So</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="255">Ihesus, hyre leue sone,</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e blysse of heuene sty,</L>
<L>To agredy wor&thorn;y scholde hy be<NOTE PLACE="foot">See note.</NOTE></L>
<L N="258">At hyre assumpcioun[e].</L>
</LG>
<LG N="44" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &yogh;et ne were hyt no&yogh;t y-no&yogh;</L>
<L>One to agredy hyre loo&yogh;</L>
<L N="261">And he&yogh; ine heuene blysse,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I> (= <I>an</I>) <I>he&yogh;</I>.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000142.tif" N="124"></L>
<L>Ac oure also, hyt nis non o&thorn;er,</L>
<L>For he hys oure kende bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="264">&THORN;at leue we to wysse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="45" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ine hym ne schal hyt nau&yogh;t lang be<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>schal</I>, MS. <I>schalt</I> (M&auml;tzner corr.).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at we to hym ne scholle te,</L>
<L N="267">Wanne we scholle wende hennes;<MILESTONE N="203a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ac schel on ous, &thorn;at be&thorn; onkende,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="127"></L>
<L>Ne dra&yogh;e&thorn; nau&yogh;t hys loue to mende,</L>
<L N="270">And wre&thorn;e&thorn; hyne wy&thorn; sennes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="46" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &yogh;et he hys milde and sparye&thorn; some,</L>
<L>And ase he wente op, he wole come</L>
<L N="273">A domesday wel bry&yogh;te,</L>
<L>For te trye manne dede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>trye</I>, MS. <I>crye</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And after dede &yogh;iue mede</L>
<L N="276">And iugement to ry&yogh;tte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="47" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Betere red nys &thorn;er non here</L>
<L>For to be crystes yuere,</L>
<L N="279">And hy&yogh; ine heuene blysse,</L>
<L>Bote fel&thorn;e of senne to by-vly,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fel&thorn;e</I> (not <I>fol&thorn;e</I>) in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bydde god and oure leuedy</L>
<L N="282">&THORN;at hy ous helpe and wysse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="48" TYPE="stanza">
<L>For hyre poer nys nou&yogh;t y-lessed,</L>
<L>Ac toup alle o&thorn;ren hys y-blessed,</L>
<L N="285">So&thorn;e wyf and mayde;</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;at godspel telle&thorn; ous,</L>
<L><I>Benedicta tu in mulieribus</I>,</L>
<L N="288">Eli&yogh;abeth hyt sayde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="49" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Al here ioyen a lok-sounday,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e &thorn;&auml;t me aspye may,</L>
<L N="291">&THORN;at hyre and er&thorn;e felle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I> = <I>an</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al fram crystes ascencioun,</L>
<L>Al wat com&thorn;e hyre assumpcioun,</L>
<L N="294">To &thorn;yssere loungy schelle.
<PB REF="00000143.tif" N="125"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="50" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E fyfte ioye of oure leuedy<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="128"></L>
<L>Not er[&thorn;]lych man hou hyt may by,</L>
<L N="297">Ne &thorn;er-of [may] more aspye,<MILESTONE N="203b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bote &thorn;at &thorn;e gloriouse beerde</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;yse world (&thorn;e) gloriouse ferde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">(<I>&thorn;e</I>) omitted by M&auml;tzner.</NOTE></L>
<L N="300">Wy&thorn; greate melodye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="51" TYPE="stanza">
<L>One-cou&thorn; to &thorn;e, man, hys &thorn;es figure,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e offyce of hyre sepulture</L>
<L N="303">Was al an heuene gyse;</L>
<L>And toller hys man to heuene speche</L>
<L>&THORN;anne be a best, &thorn;a&yogh; man hym teche</L>
<L N="306">Reyson and mannes wyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="52" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er-fore nys &thorn;er-of naut y-wryte,</L>
<L>For man ne mot nou&yogh;t her y-wyte</L>
<L N="309">Wat hys so he&yogh; a steuene;</L>
<L>Ac holy cherche der wel by-knowe</L>
<L>&THORN;at hy ne &thorn;olede none dea&thorn;es &thorn;rowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;rowe</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;ro&yogh;e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="312">&THORN;at lowe&thorn; &thorn;at lyf of heuene.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lowe&thorn; = lo&yogh;e&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>lower</I>, M&auml;tzner <I>lowerth</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="53" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hyt hys y-wryte &thorn;at angeles brytte</L>
<L>To holy manne dea&thorn;e aly&yogh;te</L>
<L N="315">[&THORN;et] her an er&thorn;e leye;</L>
<L>In holy bok hys hyt inome</L>
<L>&THORN;at god hym self a wolde come,</L>
<L N="318">Wanne hy scholde deye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="54" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er-bye we mowe wel y-wyte,</L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; &thorn;er be nau&yogh;t of y-wryte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>be</I> MS. (Wr. <I>he</I>, M&auml;tzner corr.).</NOTE></L>
<L N="321">&THORN;at cryst hym self was &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>Myd hym of heuene &thorn;e ferede,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="129"></L>
<L>&THORN;e eadi leuedy for to lede,</L>
<L N="324">Most here no fend offere.
<PB REF="00000144.tif" N="126"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="55" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hy wente vppe, my leue bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L>In body and soule, hyt nys non o&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="327">For cryst hys god and kende:<MILESTONE N="204a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at body &thorn;at he tok of hys o&yogh;en,</L>
<L>Hou mytte hyt ligge a-mang &thorn;e lo&yogh;en,</L>
<L N="330">Wy&thorn;-oute honour and mende?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="56" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;anne ich dar segge mid gode ry&yogh;te</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;e court of heuene aly&yogh;tte</L>
<L N="333">Attare departynge;</L>
<L>And cryst hym self a&yogh;eins hyre com,</L>
<L>And body and saule op wy&thorn; hym nom</L>
<L N="336">In-to hys wonyynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="57" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at hy hys quen, ase ich er mende,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I>, read <I>&thorn;ar;</I> cp. p. 113, l. 417.</NOTE></L>
<L>Here grace hy may doun to ous sende,</L>
<L N="339">Hire ioye to fol-uelle.</L>
<L>Ich hopye hy nele nau&yogh;t let ous spylle,</L>
<L>For he hys al to hyre wylle</L>
<L N="342">Of ioye &thorn;at hijs &thorn;e welle.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at hijs</I> repeated in MS.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="58" TYPE="stanza">
<L>For of hyre wombe he hys &thorn;at frut,</L>
<L>Were-of &thorn;es angeles habbe&thorn; hare dut,</L>
<L N="345">And men hare holy fode;</L>
<L>Eli&yogh;abeth, hy sede &thorn;ys:</L>
<L>"<I>Et</I> benedictus <I>fructus ventris</I></L>
<L N="348"><I>Tui, iesus</I> &thorn;e gode."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="59" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of songe hys to &thorn;en ende y-brout,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Of</I>, M&auml;tzner <I>O</I> (<I>a</I>, indefinite article).</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="130"></L>
<L>Ase &thorn;ou hest, soster, me by-so&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="351">Ase ich hene my&yogh;tte frede.</L>
<L>Nou syng and byde &thorn;e heuene quene</L>
<L>&THORN;et hy ous brynge al out of tene</L>
<L N="354">At oure mest[e] nede. AmeN.</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Oretis pro anima Willelmi de Schorham, quondam vicarii de chart iuxta Ledes.</TRAILER>


</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="6" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000145.tif" N="127">
<HEAD>VI. [On the Virgin Mary.]</HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<L>MArye, mayde mylde and fre,<MILESTONE N="204b" UNIT="folio"><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="131"></L>
<L>Chambre of &thorn;e trynyte,</L>
<L N="3">One wyle lest to me,</L>
<L>Ase ich &thorn;e grete wy&thorn; songe;</L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; my fet on-clene be,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>fet vn on clene, vn</I> underdotted.</NOTE></L>
<L N="6">My mes &thorn;ou onder-fonge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou art quene of paradys,</L>
<L>Of heuene, of erthe, of al &thorn;at hys;</L>
<L N="9">&THORN;ou bere &thorn;ane kyng of blys,</L>
<L>Wy&thorn;-oute senne and sore;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast y-ry&yogh;t &thorn;at was amys,</L>
<L N="12">Ywonne &thorn;at was y-lore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou ert &thorn;e coluere of noe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at broute &thorn;e braunche of olyue tre,</L>
<L N="15">In tokne &thorn;at pays scholde be</L>
<L>By-tuexte god and manne;</L>
<L>Suete leuedy, help &thorn;ou me,</L>
<L N="18">Wanne ich schal wende hanne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou art &thorn;e bosche of synay,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art &thorn;e rytte sarray,</L>
<L N="21">&THORN;ou hast ybrou&yogh;t ous out of cry</L>
<L>Of caleng of &thorn;e fende;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art crystes o&yogh;ene drury,</L>
<L N="24">And of dauyes kende.
<PB REF="00000146.tif" N="128"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou ert &thorn;e slinge, &thorn;y sone &thorn;e ston<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="132"></L>
<L>&THORN;at dauy slange golye op-on;</L>
<L N="27">&THORN;ou ert &thorn;e &yogh;erd al of aaron</L>
<L>Me dreye ise&yogh; spryngynde :</L>
<L>Wytnesse at ham euerechon</L>
<L N="30">&THORN;at wyste of &thorn;yne chyldynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou ert &thorn;e temple salomon,<MILESTONE N="205a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In &thorn;e wondrede gedeon,</L>
<L N="33">&THORN;ou hest ygladed symeon</L>
<L>Wy&thorn; &thorn;yne swete offrynge</L>
<L>In &thorn;e temple atte auter ston,</L>
<L N="36">Wy&thorn; ihesus, heuene kynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou ert judith, &thorn;at fayre wyf,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast abated al &thorn;at stryf,</L>
<L N="39">Olofernes wy&thorn; hys knyf</L>
<L>Hys heuede &thorn;ou hym by-nome;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hest ysaued here lyf<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lyf</I>, MS. <I>lef</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="42">&THORN;at to &thorn;e wylle come.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou ert hester, &thorn;at swete &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>And asseuer, &thorn;e ryche kyng,</L>
<L N="45">&THORN;ey he&thorn; ychose to hys weddyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ey</I> = <I>&thorn;e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And quene he he&thorn; a-uonge;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he</I>, read <I>&thorn;e</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L>For mardocheus, &thorn;y derlyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For</I>, not <I>In</I> (Wr.), is the reading of the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="48">Syre aman was y-honge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e prophete ezechyel</L>
<L>In hys boke hyt wytnesse&thorn; wel,</L>
<L N="51">&THORN;ou ert &thorn;e gate so stronge so stel,</L>
<L>Ac euere y-schet fram manne;<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="133"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou erte &thorn;e ry&yogh;te uayre rachel,</L>
<L N="54">Fayrest of alle wymman[ne].
<PB REF="00000147.tif" N="129"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<L>By ry&yogh;te toknynge &thorn;ou ert &thorn;e hel</L>
<L>Of wan spellede danyel;</L>
<L N="57">&THORN;ou ert emaus, &thorn;e ryche castel,</L>
<L>&THORN;ar reste&thorn; alle werye :</L>
<L>Ine &thorn;e restede emanuel,</L>
<L N="60">Of wan y-speke&thorn; ysaye.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wan y-speke&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>wany speke&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ine &thorn;e hys god by-come a chyld;<MILESTONE N="205b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ine &thorn;e hys wreche by-come myld,</L>
<L N="63">&THORN;at vnicorn &thorn;at was so wyld</L>
<L>Aleyd hys of a cheaste :</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast y-tamed [hyt], and i-styld,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>y-tamed</I>, MS. <I>y tamend, n</I> underdotted.</NOTE></L>
<L N="66">Wy&thorn; melke of &thorn;y breste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ine &thorn;e apocalyps sent Iohn</L>
<L>Ise&yogh; ane wymman, wy&thorn; sonne by-gon,</L>
<L N="69">&THORN;ane mow[<I>n</I>]e al onder hyre ton,</L>
<L>I-crouned wy&thorn; tuel sterre;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>tuel</I>, twelve; same form p. 61, l. 1726.</NOTE></L>
<L>Swych a leuedy nas neuere non,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Swych</I>, MS. <I>swyl</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="72">Wy&thorn; &thorn;ane fend to werre.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ase &thorn;e sonne take&thorn; hyre pas</L>
<L>Wy&thorn;-oute breche &thorn;or&yogh;-out &thorn;at glas,</L>
<L N="75">&THORN;y maydenhod, on-wemmed hyt was</L>
<L>For bere of &thorn;yne chylde;</L>
<L>Nou, swete leuedy of solas,</L>
<L N="78">To ous senfolle be &thorn;ou mylde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Haue, leuedy, &thorn;ys lytel songe,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="134"></L>
<L>&THORN;at out of senfol herte sprong;</L>
<L N="81">A&yogh;ens &thorn;e feend &thorn;ou make me strong,</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf me &thorn;y wyssynge;</L>
<L>And &thorn;a&yogh; ich habbe y-do &thorn;e wrang,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wrang</I> [:<I>strong</I>:<I>sprong</I>:<I>songe</I>]. The true Mid.-Kent forms are : <I>wrang</I> [:<I>strang</I>:<I>sprang</I>:<I>sang</I>].</NOTE></L>
<L N="84">&THORN;ou graunte me amendynge.</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Oretis pro anima domini Roberti Grosseteyte, quondam Episcopi Lincolniae.</TRAILER>


</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="7" TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000148.tif" N="130">
<HEAD>VII. On the Trinity, Creation, the Existence of Evil, Devils, Adam and Eve, &amp;c.</HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN holy sauter me may rede<MILESTONE N="206a" UNIT="folio"><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="135"></L>
<L>Hou god &thorn;ourwe &thorn;e prophete sede,</L>
<L N="3">Dauyd, y-wysse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fol in hys herte sede :<NOTE PLACE="foot">Read <I>&thorn;at</I> [<I>&thorn;e</I>] <I>fole</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L>'&THORN;er nys no gode,' dar man nau&yogh;t drede</L>
<L N="6">To don amys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e hyt hys so, hyt hys grete doute<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Se&thorn;&thorn;e</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;esse</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;are be woxe of &thorn;are route</L>
<L N="9">Mani a fol,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Mani and fole</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at wene&thorn; ryt, wy&thorn;-oute mysse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;er nys god ine heuene blysse,</L>
<L N="12">Ne helle pool.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>helle</I>, MS. <I>lelle</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at eny soche be crystene man,</L>
<L>God for-bede! and nau&yogh;t for &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="15">We y-soe&thorn; al day<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>wey soe&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at menye y-crystnedde were,<NOTE PLACE="foot">K&ouml;lbing proposes to put a colon after <I>day</I> in l. 15, and to write <I>menye &thorn;at</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fare&thorn; ryt ase hy nere</L>
<L N="18">Nau&yogh;t of &thorn;e fay.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And manye of ham &thorn;at be&thorn; so fel[l]e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;a&yogh; me godne sckele hem telle,</L>
<L N="21">Nau&yogh;t hy&yogh;t ne gan&thorn; :<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>gan&thorn;</I>, read <I>gen&thorn;</I> (for <I>gein&thorn;</I>)? See note.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000149.tif" N="131"></L>
<L>A&yogh;en hy clappe&thorn; &thorn;ys and &thorn;at,</L>
<L>And manye of ham not neuere wat,</L>
<L N="24">Ne wat he men&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<L>To sechen hyt hys wel lytel prys<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sechen</I> (dat. plur.), K&ouml;lbing <I>sech</I>.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="136"></L>
<L>Reyson to telle, &thorn;et hys y-wys,</L>
<L N="27">Ac lete ham be;</L>
<L>For, bote hy take a betere fay,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>Ac</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Atte last hy go&thorn; to schame a-way,</L>
<L N="30">Me may hyt see.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac &yogh;ef &thorn;ou wenst, man, &thorn;at errour,<MILESTONE N="206b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;are ne be no sauueour</L>
<L N="33">Ne o&thorn;er lyf,</L>
<L>And hyt be for de-faute of lore,</L>
<L>Lest now wat ich segge more,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>h</I> (underdotted) after <I>wat</I> in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="36">Wy&thorn;-oute stryf.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &yogh;ef &thorn;ou [be] ylered man,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>be</I> supplied by Wright.&mdash;<I>onderstan</I>[<I>s</I>]<I>t</I>, in the following line, would rather suggest the ind. <I>art</I> (<I>ert</I>), but change of mood is found elsewhere.</NOTE></L>
<L>And onderstan[s]t &yogh;et al for &thorn;an</L>
<L N="39">No god ne be,</L>
<L>Ich acsy &thorn;e a questioun,</L>
<L>And, ase hyt longe&thorn; to reysoun,</L>
<L N="42">And-swere &thorn;ou me.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e erthe hys heuy, wy&thorn;-oute wylle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wey y-seo&thorn;, and by al stylle<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wey</I> = <I>we</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="45">To gonne &thorn;rop.</L>
<L>Wat, hou fare&thorn; hy &thorn;at hy nasynke&thorn;,</L>
<L>Ase here kende were, hyt &thorn;ynke&thorn;;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ynke&thorn;</I> in MS. (Wright <I>&thorn;enke&thorn;</I>).</NOTE></L>
<L N="48">Ho halt ys op?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ho</I> = <I>who</I>.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000150.tif" N="132"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Herto me sey&thorn;, and he&thorn; ysed,</L>
<L>To healde hy op hyt nys no ned,</L>
<L N="51">Ne neuere nes,</L>
<L>For chisel, grauel, stones harde,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="137"></L>
<L>Ande here depnysse ry&yogh;t dounwarde</L>
<L N="54">Hys endeles.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;at be fals me may aspye<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&THORN;at &thorn;at</I>, K&ouml;lbing; MS. <I>&THORN;a&yogh; &thorn;at</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>By wytnesse of philosophye</L>
<L N="57">And clerkes fele;</L>
<L>And fals ich may hit prouie wel,</L>
<L>&THORN;er hyt hys ned, and were ich schel,</L>
<L N="60">By &thorn;ysse skele.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>skele</I>, MS. <I>skyle</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e sonne and monne and many sterren<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>monne</I> or <I>moune</I>?</NOTE><MILESTONE N="207a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>By easte aryse&thorn; swy&thorn;e ferren,</L>
<L N="63">Ase ham y-wor&thorn;e;</L>
<L>By weste hy grende&thorn;, alle &thorn;yse,</L>
<L>And come&thorn; a&yogh;en &thorn;er hy aryse</L>
<L N="66">Al vnder for&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;os my&yogh;t wete wel, wo-so wolde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wolkne by-clep&thorn; al &thorn;e molde,</L>
<L N="69">And so hyt do&thorn;;</L>
<L>Ne may hy nau&yogh;t &thorn;anne be endeles</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;os be-go so hys and wes,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wes</I>, MS. <I>was</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="72">An &thorn;at hys sou&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac saye ry&yogh;t &thorn;os&mdash;and ich afowe</L>
<L>&THORN;at euerech man hyt mo&yogh;t alowe</L>
<L N="75">&THORN;at reson hent:&mdash;</L>
<L>Hy&yogh;t hys a my&yogh;t of alle my&yogh;tte</L>
<L>&THORN;at halt op &thorn;er&thorn;e and sterren bry&yogh;te</L>
<L N="78">Aboute itrent.
<PB REF="00000151.tif" N="133"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys ilke mytte, for hyt wel may,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="138"></L>
<L>Brynge&thorn; for&thorn;e a wyt of swete aray,</L>
<L N="81">&THORN;et no swech nys;</L>
<L>For al &thorn;at hys an he&yogh; and lo&yogh;e</L>
<L>Hit schift and ditte&thorn; ase hys o&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="84">And so hyt hys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wat make&thorn; sonne, mone, and sterren</L>
<L>To certeyn go, aboute and ferren,</L>
<L N="87">And faylle&thorn; na&yogh;t?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>na&yogh;t</I>, MS. <I>nou&yogh;t</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hyt mot wyt and wysdom, neade,</L>
<L>&THORN;et of &thorn;e mytte &thorn;et ich er sede</L>
<L N="90">Hys for&thorn;e ara&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou &thorn;ou sixte wel hou hyt syt,<MILESTONE N="207b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ys ylke my&yogh;te and eke &thorn;ys wyt,</L>
<L N="93">In oure boke:</L>
<L>&THORN;e mytte hys fader of oure crede,</L>
<L>Wysdom &thorn;e sone, for wytti-hede</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;at he for&thorn; toke.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Euer was &thorn;ys ylke my&yogh;tte,</L>
<L>And euer wor&thorn;, bye gode ryte,</L>
<L N="99">Ne say nau&yogh;t nay!</L>
<L>Hou mytte hyt [cesse], and eft by-gynne,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>cese</I> (or <I>deye</I>) supplied by K&ouml;lbing; <I>cesse</I>, p. 92, l. 207.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;et nede ne&thorn; of none gynne,</L>
<L N="102">Ac al do mey?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And ase hyt hys by-fore y-nome,</L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; &thorn;at wyt of &thorn;e mytte [come]</L>
<L N="105">By kende wey,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wyt was euere na&thorn;eles,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="139"></L>
<L>&THORN;e my&yogh;tte nys neuer wytles,</L>
<L N="108">Ne by ne may.
<PB REF="00000152.tif" N="134"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Her-to acorde&thorn; oure fay,</L>
<L>&THORN;at holy cherche ne&yogh; eche day</L>
<L N="111">Wel merye synge&thorn;,</L>
<L>Ine a song ofte by note</L>
<L>'Quicunque <I>uult</I>' &thorn;et hys y-hote,</L>
<L N="114">Ry&yogh;t ase me singe&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>singe&thorn;</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>&thorn;ing&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &thorn;er hyt of &thorn;e uader sey&thorn;,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e sone to-gadere ley&thorn;,</L>
<L N="117">In boke yset:</L>
<L>'&THORN;e sone hys of &thorn;e fader alone</L>
<L>Engendred, nau&yogh;t ymad of mone,</L>
<L N="120">Nef o&thorn;e[r] wet.'<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nef = ne of; wet</I>, MS. <I>wat</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Folye hyt hys to meche to &thorn;enche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;enche</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;ynche</I>.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="208a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e engendrure, and &thorn;ynne adrenche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ynne</I> = <I>&thorn;e ynne;</I> or shall we read <I>&thorn;rynne</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L N="123">Of fader and sone :</L>
<L>So ase hy be&thorn;e, [hy] euer were,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>hy</I>], so also K&ouml;lbing.</NOTE></L>
<L>And soche by-&yogh;ete neuere nere</L>
<L N="126">Elles ine wone.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac nau&yogh;t for&thorn; &thorn;an, &thorn;at hyt be so&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for&thorn; &thorn;an</I> = <I>for &thorn;an</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Holy cherche to wytene do&thorn;,</L>
<L N="129">We wyten hyt wel;</L>
<L>Ilef hyt, o&thorn;er &thorn;ou ert by-caut,</L>
<L>For ho &thorn;at nele by-leue hyt nau&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="132">To helle he schel.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;elke sone &yogh;et na&thorn;eles<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="140"></L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t ase &thorn;e fader hys endeles,</L>
<L N="135">Ase my&yogh;t and wyt:</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef euer was [fader], euer was sone,</L>
<L>For be&thorn;e reysoun and eke wone</L>
<L N="138">Alowe&thorn; hyt.
<PB REF="00000153.tif" N="135"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou we habbe&thorn; uader and sone,</L>
<L>Ase hye be&thorn; ry&yogh;t ine persone,</L>
<L N="141">And &thorn;an-cheysoun.</L>
<L>Wat may &thorn;e holy gost nou be?</L>
<L>Persone &thorn;rydde in trynyte,</L>
<L N="144">Nou herkne reysoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou sixt &thorn;et al &thorn;at far&thorn; ary&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Be hyt &thorn;yster, be hyt ly&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="147">To acord hys wyue;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wyue</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L>For &yogh;ef &thorn;er were werre a-boue<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>werre</I>, K&ouml;lbing; MS. <I>weyre</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Amang &thorn;e sterren, and no loue,</L>
<L N="150">Al hy to-dryue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And bote a truwe loue come<MILESTONE N="208b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;are my&yogh;tte and &thorn;a wysdome,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;a</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>thare</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="153">Ne my&yogh;t hyt by;</L>
<L>And ry&yogh;t of ham he moste come,</L>
<L>For werof elles te be y-nome</L>
<L N="156">Can non ysy.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Euer-to lef &thorn;at loue were,</L>
<L>For my&yogh;tte and wysdom neuer nere</L>
<L N="159">Wy&thorn;-oute acord;</L>
<L>For &yogh;ef acord hem hedde yfaylled,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="141"></L>
<L>Ar ayder o&thorn;er hedde a-saylled<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ar = hare</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="162">Wy&thorn; wykked word.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hou scholde my&yogh;tte maky wrake,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er eny descord onder-take</L>
<L N="165">Wy&thorn; o&yogh;e wyt?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>o&yogh;e</I>, MS. <I>e&yogh;e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>So nest, ac euer weren hy:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nest = nes it</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;anne moste loue euer by,</L>
<L N="168">Nou &thorn;ou sixt hyt.
<PB REF="00000154.tif" N="136"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys loue hys self &thorn;at holy spyryt;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-to acorde&thorn; holy wry&yogh;t</L>
<L N="171">Ine &thorn;ylke songe</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich was embe, [of] oure faye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at holy cherche singe&thorn; a daye</L>
<L N="174">At pryme longe:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<L>'&THORN;e holy [gost] of [&thorn;e] fader ryche</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e sone, of o&thorn;er ylyche,</L>
<L N="177">So he for[&thorn;] come&thorn;;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>come&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>com&thorn;e</I> [: <I>nome&thorn;</I>, 2 plur. imperat.].</NOTE></L>
<L>No&thorn;er by-&yogh;ete, ne for&thorn;e i-wro&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>by-&yogh;ete</I>, MS. <I>by-hete</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of a&yogh;t &thorn;at hys, ne for&thorn;e of no&yogh;t':<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for&thorn;e</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>formed.&mdash;no&yogh;t</I>, MS. <I>nau&yogh;t</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="180">By lawe hyt nome&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And euer was &thorn;at holy spyry&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="209a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at ylke songe wytnesse&thorn; hyt,</L>
<L N="183">And more &thorn;er-to:</L>
<L>&THORN;at he schal by, and hys, and was<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he</I> (or <I>hyt</I>?), MS. <I>hy</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ase fader of heuene ry&yogh;t endeleas;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ase</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;at</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="186">And sone al-so.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;et oure by-leaue wole onder-gon<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="142"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;yse &thorn;re be&thorn; ry&yogh;t al on,</L>
<L N="189">And nys no wrong;</L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; hy be ine reyson dyuers,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>reyson</I>, read <I>persone</I>? See note.</NOTE></L>
<L>O god hyt hys, and stent in uers<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>ase</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="192">Ine &thorn;ulke song.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; my&yogh;te, wysdom, and eke loue,</L>
<L>Hy &thorn;re by, ase ich sede a-boue,</L>
<L N="195">Diuers ine werk,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>werk</I>, MS. <I>work</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ine hem self o god hy be&thorn;;</L>
<L>Nys non &thorn;at a&yogh;t elles y-se&thorn;</L>
<L N="198">So god [a] clerke.
<PB REF="00000155.tif" N="137"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And na&thorn;eles ofte hy be&thorn; y-blent,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>y-blent</I>, MS. <I>y blendt, d</I> underdotted.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;yse clerkes, wy&thorn; here argument,</L>
<L N="201">Ande gynne&thorn; le&yogh;e;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>le&yogh;e</I>, MS. <I>lye</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hare o&yogh;e wyt, hyt hym by-keche&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>by-keche&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>by ch</I> (underdotted) <I>keche&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at god so sotylleche seche&thorn;,</L>
<L N="204">&THORN;at syt so he&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e fader hys god, for he may al;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>al</I>, MS. <I>alle, le</I> underdotted.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e sone hys god, for he wot al,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>god</I>, K&ouml;lbing; MS. <I>swete</I>, see note.&mdash;<I>al</I>, MS. <I>all</I> (second <I>l</I> underdotted).</NOTE></L>
<L N="207">Wy&thorn;-out[e] crye;</L>
<L>&THORN;e gost hys god, &thorn;at one&thorn; al,</L>
<L>&YOGH;et ne be&thorn; hy bote o god al,</L>
<L N="210">Nau&yogh;t godes &thorn;ry.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; my&yogh;tte be to &thorn;e fader yleyd,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;e</I> over the line.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="209b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And wysdome of &thorn;e sone yseyd,</L>
<L N="213">And loue &thorn;e gost,<NOTE PLACE="foot">K&ouml;lbing supplies <I>of</I> after <I>loue</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;et be&thorn; hy &thorn;re of one my&yogh;tte,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="143"></L>
<L>Of one wytte and loue ly&yogh;tte,</L>
<L>&THORN;or&yogh; fay &thorn;e hyt wost.<NOTE PLACE="foot">In MS. this line is written in the margin.&mdash;<I>&thorn;e</I>, weakened form of <I>&thorn;ou</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou &thorn;ou syxt wel &thorn;at encheysoun</L>
<L>Of oure by-leue, and eke reysoun,</L>
<L N="219">&THORN;et o god hys;</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef &thorn;ou &thorn;enkest for&thorn;er hou hyt may be,</L>
<L>Go nau&yogh;t to ni&yogh; hys maieste,</L>
<L N="222">To &thorn;enche amys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<L>[N]Ou hys al &thorn;ys by skele ondo,</L>
<L>And by-leaue alegged &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L N="225">&THORN;at god hys he.</L>
<L>Nou we moste y-wyte more,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;yse worldle some lore,</L>
<L N="228">Hou hy&yogh;t may be:
<PB REF="00000156.tif" N="138"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wader &thorn;y[s] worldle euer were,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Wader</I> = <I>whether</I>, MS. <I>Fader</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>O&thorn;er a some tyme nere,</L>
<L N="231">And &thorn;o by-gan?</L>
<L>Euerte mytte hy nau&yogh;t by,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Euerte</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>Eterne</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ich schal &thorn;e telle reyson wy,</L>
<L N="234">So&thorn;e ase ich can.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>So&thorn;e</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>Soche</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<L>For godes my&yogh;tte, ande eke hys wyt,</L>
<L>And eke hys wylle, to soffry hy&yogh;t</L>
<L N="237">So were wo&yogh;;</L>
<L>For he hys almytty, ase ich er sede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he</I>, MS. <I>&yogh;e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al-wys, and wyl ine god-hede,</L>
<L N="240">&THORN;et hys yno&yogh;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="41" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac &yogh;ef he nedde &thorn;ys world y-wrou&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="210a" UNIT="folio"><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="144"></L>
<L>And my&yogh;te and cou&thorn;e, and dede hy&yogh;t nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="243">Hyt were amys;</L>
<L>Ac hys al-my&yogh;tte hys of suche entaylle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>al-my&yogh;tte</I>, MS. <I>al my&yogh;tty</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hys al-wyt, hou mytte hyt faylle<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>al-wyt</I>, MS. <I>al mytty;</I> see note.</NOTE></L>
<L N="246">Of &thorn;et god hys?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="42" TYPE="stanza">
<L>He made hyt al, nys hyt non o&thorn;er,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>al hy</I> (underdotted).</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at of nau&yogh;te, my leue bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="249">He made hys werke;</L>
<L>For er he a-gounne hys work so merye,</L>
<L>Nas no&thorn;er fourme ne materye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fourme, u</I> over the line.</NOTE></L>
<L N="252">Ne ly&yogh;t ne derk.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="43" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ne acombre nau&yogh;t &thorn;y wyt any mo,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>any mo</I>, MS. <I>and mo</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>To meche to &thorn;enche hou hyt was &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="255">Hyt [nys] nau&yogh;t wor&thorn;;</L>
<L>Hou man hyt my&yogh;te wete ich not,</L>
<L>For so to wytene, ase god hyt wot,</L>
<L N="258">Comest &thorn;ou nau&yogh;t for&thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000157.tif" N="139"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="44" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac some mey acsy, war god was</L>
<L>&THORN;o no&thorn;yng of &thorn;e worlde nas,</L>
<L N="261">Ne great ne smal?</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;e worlde hys nou, was he,</L>
<L>And &yogh;et he hys, and euer schal be,</L>
<L N="264">Ihole ouer al.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="45" TYPE="stanza">
<L>He hedde nede of none gynne,</L>
<L>Ne &yogh;et now ne&thorn;, to wonye ynne,</L>
<L N="267">&THORN;ou kepe nym;</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef &thorn;e fal&thorn; &thorn;rof to be aposed,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>fal&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>faly</I>.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="145"></L>
<L>Sey, god nys nau&yogh;t in &thorn;er worldle aclosed,</L>
<L N="270">Ac hy hys ine hym.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="46" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; hy nabbe ende ne for&thorn;e gol,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hy</I>, read <I>he</I>?</NOTE><MILESTONE N="210b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;et ouer al he hys y-hol,</L>
<L N="273">Wy&thorn;-oute drede;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>drede</I>, K&ouml;lbing; MS. <I>crede</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nau&yogh;t o del here, ano&thorn;er &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>Ase great body, as hyt were,</L>
<L N="276">&THORN;at al by-&yogh;ede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="47" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou wost he may by y&thorn;o&yogh;t of me</L>
<L>Alle yhollyche, and eke of &thorn;e</L>
<L N="279">Wel betere, ich ply&yogh;te;</L>
<L>He may by wel ine dyuers lo&yogh;</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t al at ones, wel yno&yogh;:</L>
<L N="282">&THORN;at dei&thorn; hys my&yogh;tte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="48" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;yse wordle he made, as ich er sede,</L>
<L>Al ase hy hys ry&yogh;t nou ine dede,</L>
<L N="285">And lo&yogh; and he&yogh;;</L>
<L>Ine &thorn;e gynynge of holy wryt,</L>
<L>Hou he hyt made ry&yogh;t &thorn;er hyt sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="288">Ich hyt yse&yogh;e.
<PB REF="00000158.tif" N="140"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="49" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ine da&yogh;es sixe he made hyt Ry&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Heuene and erthe and wolkne bry&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="291">&THORN;et water te-dy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Tren and gras and er&thorn;e dre&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Sonne and mone and sterren grey&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="294">&THORN;at be&thorn; so bry&yogh;t;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="50" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fo&yogh;eles, fisches ine &thorn;e depe,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="146"></L>
<L>Bestes, wormes for to crepe,</L>
<L N="297">And a last, man;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at hyt was god and sad,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;ys world, &thorn;at was ymad</L>
<L N="300">Of hym &thorn;at can.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="51" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Al hyt was god, wy&thorn;-oute lak,<MILESTONE N="211a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Hard and nesche, wyte and blacke,</L>
<L N="303">And al &thorn;at wes:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wes</I>, MS. <I>was</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nedes godes creature</L>
<L>Moste be ry&yogh;t by nature,</L>
<L N="306">Al senneles.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>senneles</I>, MS. <I>sennes les</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="52" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;ef quead so were of gode y-nome,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>y-nome</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>y-come</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>By ry&yogh;tte he my&yogh;tte be wy&thorn;-nome</L>
<L N="309">Ry&yogh;t ase a qued;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore ne my&yogh;te he nau&yogh;t do wro&thorn;e:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>do</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>be</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac schrewadnesse be&thorn; hym lo&thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hym</I> altered from <I>hem</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="312">And hys for-beade.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="53" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;e god self hyt for-beade,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>Ac.&mdash;se&thorn;&thorn;e</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;esse</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wannes come&thorn; for&thorn;e al &thorn;at quead,</L>
<L N="315">So meche &thorn;er hys?
<PB REF="00000159.tif" N="141"></L>
<L>And wel to donne apayne&thorn; ueawe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>apayne&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>apanye&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac hym apayne&thorn; many a screwe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>many a screwe</I>, MS. <I>man&thorn; ascrewe</I> (Wright correx.).</NOTE></L>
<L N="318">To do amys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="54" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at god hyt soffre&thorn;, hou mey hyt be,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mey</I>, MS. <I>meny</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e of so great my&yogh;tte hys he</L>
<L N="321">&THORN;et, &yogh;ef ha wolde,</L>
<L>He my&yogh;tte uordo &thorn;at hys quead,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="147"></L>
<L>And lete ous libbe, and nau&yogh;t be dead?</L>
<L N="324">Hyt &thorn;ing&thorn; ha scholde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dot after <I>&thorn;ing&thorn;</I> in MS.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="55" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Leue bro&thorn;er, &yogh;ef he so scholde,</L>
<L>By &thorn;e syker &thorn;at he so wolde,</L>
<L N="327">Ac he hyt nele.</L>
<L>Ich kan &thorn;e telle reyson wy</L>
<L>He let y-wor&thorn;e quead to by;</L>
<L N="330">Nou harkne skele.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="56" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at al&thorn;er-ferste &thorn;at god schop,<MILESTONE N="211b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at was heuene, &thorn;er nys no wop,</L>
<L N="333">So&thorn; for to telle;</L>
<L>For he hyt made of swyche aray,</L>
<L>For alle manere blysse and play</L>
<L N="336">&THORN;er to folfelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="57" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac o blysse hys, nys nau&yogh;t folfeld,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hys</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>ther</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>War-fore &thorn;at heuene hys al ydueld,</L>
<L N="339">And &yogh;et nou wor&thorn;;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wor&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>wer&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac ich schel telle wat hys &thorn;at blysse,</L>
<L>And so we scholle wyte to wysse</L>
<L N="342">Hou quead come&thorn; for&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="58" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;ef &thorn;e by-fal&thorn; auancement<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>auance</I>-, MS. <I>auence</I>-</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &yogh;ef&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;e was yment,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;ef&thorn;e</I>, MS. <I>&yogh;ef &thorn;e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="345">Wel bly&thorn;e art &thorn;ou;
<PB REF="00000160.tif" N="142"></L>
<L>And &yogh;ef &thorn;e falle&thorn; to be eyr</L>
<L>Of a regne mechel and fayr,</L>
<L N="348">More hys &thorn;y prou.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="59" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac nys no blysse ne no feste<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="148"></L>
<L>A&yogh;eyns &thorn;e ioye of conqueste</L>
<L N="351">&THORN;et hys &thorn;or&yogh; god;</L>
<L>Ne mey me more ioye aspye,</L>
<L>&THORN;ane wanne a man &thorn;or&yogh; pur mestrye</L>
<L N="354">Ke&thorn; hys manhod.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="60" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And to great defaute hyt were,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef no ioye of conqueste nere,</L>
<L N="357">So merye hys hy:</L>
<L>Nou sixt &thorn;ou &thorn;anne mytte beste</L>
<L>Hou ioye &thorn;at come&thorn; of conqueste</L>
<L N="360">Mot neades by.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="61" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nys gryt stryf wy&thorn;-oute queade,<MILESTONE N="212b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;er conqueste hys, stryf hys neade,</L>
<L N="363">And som yschent:</L>
<L>&THORN;anne nys hyt to god no wrang</L>
<L>To soffre queade &thorn;e gode amang</L>
<L N="366">To auancement.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="62" TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &yogh;ef quead nere in none &thorn;ynge,</L>
<L>&THORN;er nere stryf ne contekynge,</L>
<L N="369">Ne no wy&thorn;-sey;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>no</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>nou&yogh;t</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;yf stryf nere, ne victorye,</L>
<L>So scholde ine heuene [faylly] (&thorn;at) glorye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;at</I> omitted by K&ouml;lbing. B&ouml;ddekker proposed to write&mdash;<I>Hou scholde me haue &thorn;at glorye</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="372">Ac hyt ne mey.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>t</I> in <I>hyt</I> indistinct in MS.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="63" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er-fore &thorn;er hys a maystre schreawe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>maystre</I>, MS. <I>mastrye</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wy&thorn; hym mo be&thorn;, and &thorn;et nau&yogh;t ueawe,</L>
<L N="375">And neades mote;
<PB REF="00000161.tif" N="143"></L>
<L>For he hys heaued of schrewednesse,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="149"></L>
<L>As god hys cheaf of alle godnesse</L>
<L N="378">And alle bote.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="64" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hou mytte schreaudnesse by,</L>
<L>Bote scherewen were hy<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hy</I>, MS. <I>by</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="381">&THORN;at hy ferst &thorn;ou&yogh;te?</L>
<L>For god ne dede no quead in dede,</L>
<L>For al was god, ase ich er sede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>But</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="384">Al &thorn;at he wroute.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="65" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;es ilke screawe so hys ly&yogh;t-barn,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ly&yogh;t-barn</I>, MS. <I>ly&yogh;t banr</I>. K&ouml;lbing reads the two lines:&mdash; <I>Thes ilke screawe so hy&yogh;t: ly&yogh;tbere, That god drove into helle fere;</I> but see note.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at in-to helle god at-arn</L>
<L N="387">Ferst for hys prede;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ferst</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>Than</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac god hyne makede fayr yno&yogh;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>For</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bry&yogh;t ande schene, and he&yogh;est in lo&yogh;,</L>
<L N="390">Ferst ine hys dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="66" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac are he were y-mad parfyt,<MILESTONE N="212b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ase gode soffrede hy&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="393">He waux wel proud:</L>
<L>He wolde sette hys sete ryche</L>
<L>Of north half, and be god ylyche,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>north</I>, MS. <I>norch</I> (Wright corr.).</NOTE></L>
<L N="396">To be a-lowed.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="67" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And so he werry ferst by-gan</L>
<L>Wy&thorn; gode ine heuene, and &yogh;et te &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>te &thorn;an</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>by than</I> (temporal).</NOTE></L>
<L N="399">O&thorn;er wel fele,</L>
<L>Wy&thorn; hym &thorn;at helde wy&thorn; alle my&yogh;tte,</L>
<L>Angeles &thorn;at god hedde ymad bry&yogh;tte</L>
<L N="402">In alle wele.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="68" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys by-ganne schrewednesse<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="150"></L>
<L>Op an he&yogh;, ine heuene blysse,</L>
<L N="405">&THORN;e ferste day;
<PB REF="00000162.tif" N="144"></L>
<L>Hy&yogh;t moste neades for &thorn;e glorye,</L>
<L>Elles hedde y-faylled fyctorye,</L>
<L N="408">Ac hyt ne may.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="69" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac alle hy weren ydryuen out,</L>
<L>Wy&thorn; lucyfer &thorn;at was so stout,</L>
<L N="411">&THORN;or&yogh; godes my&yogh;tte;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;or&yogh;</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;o&yogh;r</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hy &thorn;at ne hylde wy&thorn; &thorn;e left</L>
<L>Sta[b]le woxe, &thorn;at neuere eft<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sta[b]le</I>, so also K&ouml;lbing.</NOTE></L>
<L N="414">Sene&yogh;y ne my&yogh;tte.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sene&yogh;y</I>, MS. <I>Sene &yogh;y</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="70" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Tuo skeles be&thorn;, &thorn;at me may wyte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at none nere ymad parfyte</L>
<L N="417">Ine heuene ferst,</L>
<L>Er &thorn;e bataylle yended was</L>
<L>By-twexte god and sathanas</L>
<L N="420">&THORN;at now hys werst.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>werst</I>, MS. <I>worst</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="71" TYPE="stanza">
<L>O reyson was for angeles gode<MILESTONE N="213a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at chose ary&yogh;t, and faste stode</L>
<L N="423">At &thorn;ylke dede:</L>
<L>For &thorn;at hy scholde, &thorn;or&yogh; pur co[<I>n</I>]queste,</L>
<L>Habbe ioye euere to leste</L>
<L N="426">For hare mede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="72" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er reyson was for &thorn;e deuel,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he schal to mys wende hys cheuel<NOTE PLACE="foot">See note.</NOTE></L>
<L N="429">&THORN;or&yogh; hys malyce,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at folueld were &thorn;e glorye,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="151"></L>
<L>And hym seelf &thorn;or&yogh; noble uictorye</L>
<L N="432">Lys al hy[s] blysse.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Lys</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>les</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="73" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;ef hy hade be mad parfy&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hade</I>, MS. <I>heade</I>, first <I>e</I> underdotted.</NOTE></L>
<L>We nedde y-haued ry&yogh;t no profy&yogh;t</L>
<L N="435">Ine heuene a-boue;
<PB REF="00000163.tif" N="145"></L>
<L>Nou schal man be in hare lo&yogh;,</L>
<L>And habbe ioye and blysse yno&yogh;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>yno&yogh;</I> in a later hand.</NOTE></L>
<L N="438">And pes and loue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="74" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;e hyt moste nides by</L>
<L>&THORN;et soche schrewen were hy,</L>
<L N="441">Ase gode hyt mente,</L>
<L>Hou yst &thorn;et hy ine helle slabbe&thorn;,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are-tou none grace nabbe&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;are-tou = &thorn;er-to</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="444">To repente?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="75" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Suppose here hijs o iustyse,</L>
<L>God and truwe in alle wyse,</L>
<L N="447">And wys of rede;</L>
<L>And dampne&thorn; &thorn;eues for to ordeyne</L>
<L>Peys in londe, nau&yogh;t fo[r] weyne,</L>
<L N="450">Ne for queadhede.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>queadhede</I>, MS. <I>quead heuede</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="76" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Suppose he &thorn;at schel hem spylle,<MILESTONE N="213b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And honge&thorn; hy wy&thorn; grete wylle,</L>
<L N="453">And hys wel glad;</L>
<L>Ne he ne&thorn; reuthe of hys em-cryste,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>reuthe</I>, MS. <I>reuche.&mdash;em-cryste</I>, MS. <I>eny cryste</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; hy neuere of &thorn;ef&thorn;e neste:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ef&thorn;e</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;ef &thorn;e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="456">&THORN;es hys a quead,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="77" TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &thorn;at he hys mansle&yogh;&thorn;e pur,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>mansle&yogh; &thorn;e</I>.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="152"></L>
<L>Of wylle of mysauenture,</L>
<L N="459">To spylle blod;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at mente hyt, &thorn;at iustyse</L>
<L>Hys to preysy in &thorn;ysse wyse</L>
<L N="462">For hys wyl god.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="78" TYPE="stanza">
<L>So &thorn;ou sixte &thorn;at me may dy&yogh;te</L>
<L>Quead for gode, and &thorn;at wy&thorn; ry&yogh;tte,</L>
<L N="465">And so me de&thorn;;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>de&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>der</I> (Wright correx.).</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000164.tif" N="146"></L>
<L>And hy &thorn;at do&thorn; hyt ine deade,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ine deade</I>, read <I>in mysdede</I>? cp. l. 473.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wy&thorn; hare wyl of schrewed-hede,</L>
<L N="468">Dampnable be&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="79" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;os mo&yogh;e we wel by reysoun scheawe</L>
<L>&THORN;at, &thorn;a&yogh; god soffrede such a schreawe</L>
<L N="471">Al for to spylle,</L>
<L>Hyt was for gode, ase ich er sede,</L>
<L>And lucyfer in hys mysdede</L>
<L N="474">Was wykke of wylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="80" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;are-uore dampnable he hys,</L>
<L>For he was [glad] to don amys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">[<I>glad</I>], cp. l. 453; K&ouml;lbing <I>greedy</I>, or <I>glad</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="477">&THORN;o &thorn;at he my&yogh;tte;</L>
<L>And god soffred &thorn;at ylke dede,</L>
<L>For god come &thorn;rof, ase ich er sede,</L>
<L N="480">Ase god hy&yogh;t dy&yogh;tte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="81" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ne hyt nys of god no malyce<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>no</I>, MS. <I>ne</I>.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="214a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e&yogh; he hym soffrede lese hys blysse<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lese</I> K&ouml;lbing, MS. <I>lasse</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="483">And alle hys wele,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I> K&ouml;lbing, MS. <I>In</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al &thorn;a&yogh; he &thorn;or&yogh; hys grace my&yogh;tte<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;a&yogh;</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;at</I>.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="153"></L>
<L>Habbe y-don hym wilni &thorn;at ry&yogh;tte;</L>
<L N="486">Nou harkne skele.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="82" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hyt onbycome ine eche place</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef ech [&thorn;]yng hadde ylyche grace</L>
<L N="489">To ioye and blysse;</L>
<L>And ich mey &yogh;yuen, and eke wy&thorn;-dra&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at myn hys, by gode la&yogh;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>myn myn</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>myn o&yogh;e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="492">Wy&thorn;-oute malyce.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="83" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ne may nau&yogh;t &thorn;anne god al-so,</L>
<L>War he wyle, hys grace do,</L>
<L N="495">And eke wy&thorn;-dra&yogh;e,
<PB REF="00000165.tif" N="147"></L>
<L>&YOGH;ef he wole, wy&thorn;-out malyce,</L>
<L>And wy&thorn;e-oute alle manere uyce?</L>
<L N="498">Nys &thorn;ys god la&yogh;e?<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ys</I>, MS. <I>nys</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="84" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;es, y-wys, god la&yogh;e hys:</L>
<L>&THORN;et hyt be al ase hys wyl hys</L>
<L N="501">Hyt wyle wel by-come;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omit <I>Hyt</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L>Nys non &thorn;at conne dy&yogh;te hyt bet,</L>
<L>Al-&thorn;a&yogh; hyt &thorn;enche wel on-net,</L>
<L N="504">Hys wyl, to some.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="85" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;at god wyle grace &yogh;eue<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;eue</I>, MS. <I>&yogh;yue</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Euer to libbe, hyt mot leue</L>
<L N="507">Ine sauement;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar he wyle hys grace wy&thorn;-dra&yogh;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hys</I>, MS. <I>wy&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nys nau&yogh;t malyce, ac hyt hys la&yogh;e</L>
<L N="510">And iugement.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="86" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac wy he graunte&thorn; grace to one,<MILESTONE N="214b" UNIT="folio"><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="154"></L>
<L>And soche and o&thorn;eren grauntye&thorn; none,</L>
<L N="513">Segge ich ne kanne;</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;et hys hys priuete<NOTE PLACE="foot">See note.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of hys domes in equyte,</L>
<L N="516">Wy&thorn; wyl to &thorn;anne.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wyl</I>, MS. <I>wel</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="87" TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &thorn;er nys nou&yogh;t of &thorn;ysse wylle</L>
<L>Her to iugy, ac be we stylle,</L>
<L N="519">We be&thorn; y-let;</L>
<L>For dauyd ous to wyten de&thorn;,</L>
<L>In boke, &thorn;at godes domes be&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">(Ps. xxv. 7),</NOTE></L>
<L N="522">A groundlyas pet.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="88" TYPE="stanza">
<L>For hys ne may no wyt areche,</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;o &thorn;et hym self wyle teche</L>
<L N="525">He scheawy&thorn; hy,
<PB REF="00000166.tif" N="148"></L>
<L>And &thorn;e he nele, hy be&thorn; pryue:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he nele</I>, MS. <I>henele</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al &thorn;at y-ordeyned he&thorn; he<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>be&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="528">Mot neades by.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="89" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;e deuel ydampned hys,</L>
<L>And wy&thorn; hym al-so &thorn;at be&thorn; hys,</L>
<L N="531">Deuelen wel mo;</L>
<L>For &thorn;at &thorn;e grace of god him faylle&thorn;,</L>
<L>Moche hys &thorn;e pyne &thorn;at hem eyle&thorn;,</L>
<L N="534">And eke &thorn;e who.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>who</I> = <I>wo</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="90" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wy hy ne mo&yogh;e, ase ich er sede,</L>
<L>Wel repenty of hare mysdede</L>
<L N="537">Lest enne skele,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich schal segge, ase ich can;<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="155"></L>
<L>Mo be&thorn;, ac &thorn;et longy te man<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ac</I>, MS. <I>at.&mdash;longy</I>, read <I>longe&thorn;</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L N="540">Ne be&thorn; nau&yogh;t fele.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="91" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swy&thorn;e fayr &thorn;yng hys &thorn;at wyte,<MILESTONE N="215a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;er by-syde blak a lyte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>blak</I>, MS. <I>blok</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="543">Wel ydy&yogh;t;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ydy&yogh;t</I>, MS. <I>ydry&yogh;t</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e wyte hyt &thorn;e uayrer make&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>&thorn;e wyte &thorn;e uayrer hyt make&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>And [hym] selue more hyt blake&thorn;,</L>
<L N="546">And al hyt hy&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="92" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e wyse man &thorn;e wyser seme&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wyse</I>, MS. <I>wyser.&mdash;seme&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>sone&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;et menye foules dreme&thorn;,</L>
<L N="549">And no reysoun;</L>
<L>&THORN;e merrer hyt hys ine bataylle</L>
<L>&THORN;et me syk&thorn; al &thorn;e vomen faylle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>me syk&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>msyk&thorn;</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="552">And falle a-doun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="93" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys lykynge hys for heuene blysse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at leste schal wy&thorn;-oute mysse</L>
<L N="555">Ase euere mo;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ase</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>And</I>.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000167.tif" N="149"></L>
<L>&THORN;ar hys so meche &thorn;e more merye<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;ar</I>, read <I>&thorn;at</I>?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e deuel ys &thorn;at me[y] nau&yogh;t ne derye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>deuel ys</I>, MS. <I>deuelys</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="558">And helle also.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="94" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hy &thorn;et &thorn;er be&thorn; so mo&yogh;e ysy<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mo&yogh;e</I>. MS. <I>more</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wat peryl ascaped be&thorn; hy,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>be&thorn;</I>, MS. <I>bey</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="561">And be &thorn;e bly&thorn;ere;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at folueld &thorn;e ioye nere,</L>
<L>Bote euere helle pyne were,</L>
<L N="564">And &thorn;rynne wi&thorn;ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="95" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac wo be&thorn; wer&thorn;er for to by<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="156"></L>
<L>Euer ine helle &thorn;anne hy<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hy</I>, M&auml;tzner, Spp. II., s. v. <I>gult</I>, MS. <I>by</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="567">&THORN;er sech gelt hys?</L>
<L>&THORN;enne mey be wel &thorn;ys skele:</L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; grace faylly ham to wele<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wele</I>, MS. <I>wole</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="570">No wonder nys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="96" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And ase angeles &thorn;e faste stode<MILESTONE N="215b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For heuer eft by-come gode,</L>
<L N="573">And glad an bly&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t deuelen [so] for screawed-hede<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ry&yogh;t deuelen</I> [<I>so</I>], K&ouml;lbing <I>Ry&yogh;t</I> [<I>so</I>] <I>deuelen</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Euer mo forse scholle brede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>mo</I>, MS. <I>me</I> (or <I>ine</I>, i-stroke wanting?); see note.</NOTE></L>
<L N="576">And wre&thorn;e and ny&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="97" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac &thorn;o hy hedde ine heuene ytopped,</L>
<L>Wy nedde hy be ine helle y-stopped</L>
<L N="579">For euere mo,</L>
<L>Ac Nau&yogh;t her in &thorn;ys myddelnerde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>, MS. <I>At</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For to maky men offerde,</L>
<L N="582">And to mysdo?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="98" TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &thorn;o hye weren out ycached,</L>
<L>And ou&yogh;t of hare lo&yogh; arached</L>
<L N="585">For hare senne,
<PB REF="00000168.tif" N="150"></L>
<L>We mo&yogh;e weten hyt wel y-nou</L>
<L>&THORN;at al ydel was hare lo&yogh;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>al</I>, so also K&ouml;lbing; MS. <I>ase</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="588">&THORN;at hy weren ynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="99" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And one-by-comeleche &thorn;yng hyt were</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef eny lo&yogh; &thorn;er le&thorn;y were,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&YOGH;ef</I>, MS. <I>&yogh;e&yogh;. &mdash;le&thorn;y</I>, the <I>e</I> resembling <I>o</I> in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="591">Seruynde of nou&yogh;t[e];</L>
<L>&THORN;ar-fore god made mannes schefte,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="157"></L>
<L>&THORN;at ylke lo&yogh; al for to crefte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>crefte</I>, MS. <I>crafte</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="594">Ase god hy&yogh;t &thorn;oute.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="100" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac manne ne mytte nau&yogh;t &thorn;e glorye</L>
<L>Crefte, wy&thorn;-oute victorye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Read <I>Crefte</I> [<I>al</I>]?</NOTE></L>
<L N="597">My leue bro&thorn;er;</L>
<L>For &yogh;ef he nadde hy&yogh;t &thorn;or&yogh; conqueste,</L>
<L>Folueld ne mytte be hys feste</L>
<L N="600">Al ase ano&thorn;er.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="101" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;are-fore god made hym god and wys,<MILESTONE N="216a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And mayster ouer al paradys,</L>
<L N="603">Ac nau&yogh;t parfyt;</L>
<L>For o trou &thorn;[r]ynne god for-bead,</L>
<L>Ase he nolde nou&yogh;t be dead,</L>
<L N="606">Nau&yogh;t take hyt.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="102" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And god reyson was &thorn;at he nere<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>he nere</I>, MS. <I>henere</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nau&yogh;t parfyt, ase o&thorn;er were</L>
<L N="609">To-uore ysed;</L>
<L>Ac, ase he was y-mad of er&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t here an er&thorn;e hyt was wel wer&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wer&thorn;e</I>, MS. <I>wor&thorn;e</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="612">He were asayd.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="103" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er-fore nas helle nau&yogh;t y-schet,</L>
<L>Ne deuelyn &thorn;er-inne nau&yogh;t y-det<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>y-det</I>, MS. <I>y dut</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="615">Ine &thorn;are crybbe,
<PB REF="00000169.tif" N="151"></L>
<L>For &thorn;at hy scholde man asaye</L>
<L>Wa&thorn;er he was wor&thorn;e for to deye</L>
<L N="618">O&thorn;er to libbe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="104" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac &thorn;o &thorn;e deuel hyt aspyde<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="158"></L>
<L>&THORN;at man hym scholde &thorn;er abyde</L>
<L N="621">To be assayde,</L>
<L>He &thorn;ou&yogh;te gyle al onder-go,</L>
<L>For of &thorn;et he hadde her ydo<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>her</I> = <I>er</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="624">He was affrayde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="105" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nas wonder &thorn;a&yogh; he were affrayd,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>were</I>, MS. <I>wede</I> (corr. M&auml;tzner, Spp. II, s. v. <I>anayen</I>, erroneously for <I>auayen</I>).</NOTE></L>
<L>For swy&thorn;e wel he was auayd</L>
<L N="627">Of mannes stad;</L>
<L>For after god semblant he bere,</L>
<L>And he &thorn;ou&yogh;te a &thorn;et hym uel er,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>uel</I>, MS. <I>wel</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="630">&THORN;o he was ymad.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="106" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac hys enuie a&yogh;eins man<MILESTONE N="216b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So great by-come&thorn;, &thorn;et al for &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>by-come&thorn;</I>, read <I>by-com</I>, pret.?</NOTE></L>
<L N="633">He nolde lette</L>
<L>&THORN;at he nold[e] man afounde,</L>
<L>And an hym, bote he mytte stonde,</L>
<L N="636">Hys uenym sette.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sette</I>, MS. <I>sente</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="107" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And dede hym in an addre wede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at best was of mest schreuhede,</L>
<L N="639">Of alle beste;</L>
<L>Hyt moste neades screwed by-come,</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at hy[t] hedde ine hym y-nome</L>
<L N="642">Soch a tempest[e].</L>
</LG>
<LG N="108" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And he gan to &thorn;e trowe glyde</L>
<L>&THORN;at was for-boden, al forte abyde</L>
<L N="645">After hys praye;
<PB REF="00000170.tif" N="152"></L>
<L>Ac sore hym drade for to faylly,<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="159"></L>
<L>And dorste nau&yogh;t adam asaylly,</L>
<L N="648">Al for to waye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="109" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac wel hym &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at eue nas</L>
<L>Na&yogh;t so stedefast ase adam was,</L>
<L N="651">&THORN;at was hyre lorde;</L>
<L>And ase hy come, he gan here knowe,</L>
<L>And to hyre speke out of &thorn;e trowe</L>
<L N="654">&THORN;ys ylke word:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="110" TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Leue dame, say me now,</L>
<L>Wy he&thorn; god for-bode hyt &yogh;ow<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;ow</I> K&ouml;lbing, MS. <I>now</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="657">&THORN;et &yogh;e ne mote<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;e</I>, MS. <I>he</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Eten of al &thorn;at frut &thorn;at hys</L>
<L>Here growynde in paradys</L>
<L N="660">To &yogh;oure bote?"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="111" TYPE="stanza">
<L>"We ete&thorn; y-nou," qua&thorn; eue, "y-wys,<MILESTONE N="217a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e trowes of paradys,</L>
<L N="663">And be&thorn; wel gled;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>gled</I>, MS. <I>glad</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bote &thorn;ys trow mote we nau&yogh;t take,</L>
<L>For bo&thorn;e me and mynne make</L>
<L N="666">God hyt for-bede,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="112" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And seyde, &yogh;ef we &thorn;er-of ete,</L>
<L>We scholde deye, and lyf for-lete</L>
<L N="669">And alle blysse."</L>
<L>"Nay," qua&thorn; &thorn;e fend, "ac &yogh;e ne scholde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ac</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>&thorn;at</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac he wot fol wel wet he wolde,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wel</I>, MS. <I>wel wel</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="672">&THORN;at for-bead &thorn;ys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="113" TYPE="stanza">
<L>He wot wel, &yogh;ef &yogh;e &thorn;er-of toke,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>He</I>, MS. <I>&yogh;e</I>.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="160"></L>
<L>Wy&thorn; e&yogh;en scholde &yogh;e for&thorn; loke</L>
<L N="675">Ry&yogh;t ase godes,
<PB REF="00000171.tif" N="153"></L>
<L>And conne bo&thorn;e god and quead,</L>
<L>And neuer &thorn;e ra&thorn;er be dead</L>
<L N="678">For hys for-bodys."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="114" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;os he gan hyre herte ablowe,</L>
<L>And hy se&yogh; &thorn;at frut ine &thorn;e trowe</L>
<L N="681">Was fayr and god,</L>
<L>And et &thorn;rof, dame lykerouse,</L>
<L>And made ek eten hyt hyre spouse:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>made</I>, MS. <I>maden</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="684">Hy weren wode.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="115" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Anon opened &thorn;er bo&thorn;e hare e&yogh;en,</L>
<L>And naked &thorn;at hy weren y se&yogh;en,</L>
<L N="687">And woxe of-schamed;</L>
<L>Wy&thorn; leaues hy helede hem &thorn;er-fore;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>helede</I>, MS. <I>helete</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne mytte hy no leng be for-bore</L>
<L N="690">To be y-blamed.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="116" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac &thorn;o hy herde god speke,<MILESTONE N="217b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wel sone an hal by-gonne &thorn;reke,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>by gonne &thorn;reke;</I> K&ouml;lbing <I>by-gonne hy seke</I>. The two lines probably ought to run thus:&mdash;
<LIST>
<ITEM>Ac &thorn;o hy herde godes speche,</ITEM>
<ITEM><I>Wel sone an hal hy gonne seche</I>. See note.</ITEM>
</LIST></NOTE></L>
<L N="693">Wer &thorn;et hy mytte.</L>
<L>"Adam," qua&thorn; god, "wer my&yogh;tou be?"</L>
<L>Que&thorn; he: "lord, &thorn;o we herde &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="696">We were of fly&yogh;te;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="117" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And nedes moste, lord, to so&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Al for &thorn;at we be&thorn; naked bo&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="699">Ase uole &thorn;ynges."</L>
<L>Que&thorn; god: "ho ha&thorn; y-scheawed &yogh;ou<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="161"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e be&thorn; bo&thorn;e naked nou,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;e</I>, MS. <I>he</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="702">Bote &yogh;oure Etinges?"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Etinges</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>doinges. E</I> resembles <I>O</I> or <I>s</I> in MS.; but see note.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000172.tif" N="154"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="118" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sede adam wy&thorn;erlyche to gode:</L>
<L>"Nedde ich y-broke nau&yogh;t &thorn;y for-bode,</L>
<L N="705">Ne nau&yogh;t do so,</L>
<L>Nedde &thorn;e wymman, lord, y-be</L>
<L>&THORN;at to fela&yogh;e &thorn;ou madest me,</L>
<L N="708">Hy dede me hyt do."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Hy</I>, MS. <I>Hyt</I>, but <I>t</I> nearly rubbed out.&mdash;<I>dede</I>, MS. <I>dede hyt</I>.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="119" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;o seyde god almy&yogh;ty to eue:</L>
<L>"Wy madest &thorn;ou man mys-byleue,</L>
<L N="711">And &thorn;ous mys-went?"</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;o seyde eue: "so wey &thorn;at wyle!<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>Ac so</I> (underdotted) <I>&thorn;o.&mdash;so wey &thorn;at wyle</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>se wey &thorn;at wyle</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e eddre, lord, wy&thorn; hyre gyle</L>
<L N="714">He&thorn; ous y-schent."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="120" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;o by-gan god speke to &thorn;at worm:</L>
<L>"For &thorn;ou areredst &thorn;erne storm</L>
<L N="717">And alle &thorn;ys hete,</L>
<L>Acorsed be &thorn;ou bestes by-syde,</L>
<L>Opone &thorn;y wombe &thorn;ou schalt glyde,</L>
<L N="720">And er&thorn;e frete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="121" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And ich schal makye contekhede<MILESTONE N="218a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>By-tuyce &thorn;yne and wyues sede,</L>
<L N="723">And moche to pleity;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>pleity</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>playte</I>, MS. <I>pleny</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>So schal &thorn;y power be by-reued,<NOTE PLACE="foot">K&ouml;lbing inserts <I>&thorn;e</I> after <I>power</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;et schal wymman trede &thorn;ine heued,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&yogh;et</I>, so also K&ouml;lbing, with a query; MS. <I>&yogh;ef</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="726">And &thorn;ou hyre wayti."<NOTE PLACE="foot">K&ouml;lbing <I>hyre</I> [<I>heel</I>] <I>wayti</I>. See note.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="122" TYPE="stanza">
<L>So sede he wymman here lere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>So</I>, read <I>&thorn;o</I>?&mdash;<I>here lere</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>scholde lere</I> ('should learn').</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="162"></L>
<L>Hou hy scholde al hyre children bere</L>
<L N="729">Ine sor&yogh;e and stryf,
<PB REF="00000173.tif" N="155"></L>
<L>And &thorn;et hy scholde lybbe her</L>
<L>Euere ine mannes daunger</L>
<L N="732">Al hyre lyf.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="123" TYPE="stanza">
<L>To adam seyde god of heuene:</L>
<L>"For &thorn;ou dedest by &thorn;ine wyues steuene</L>
<L N="735">&THORN;et was for-hote,</L>
<L>&THORN;er[&thorn;e] hys acorsed ine &thorn;yne deade,</L>
<L>In swinched &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;y lyf leade,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>swinched</I> for <I>swinch-hed?</I> or simply an error for <I>swinche?</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="738">And ete ine swote,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="124" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Al wat &thorn;ou art a&yogh;en ycome</L>
<L>In-to er&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;art of ynome,</L>
<L N="741">&THORN;or&yogh; dea&thorn;es bende;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou nart bote of poudre y-welt,</L>
<L>And a&yogh;en into poudre schelt,</L>
<L N="744">Manne, at &thorn;yne ende."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="125" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;or&yogh; &thorn;e fend, &thorn;at hys oure uo,</L>
<L>&THORN;os by-ganne ferst al oure wo</L>
<L N="747">&THORN;et we be&thorn; inne;</L>
<L>An &thorn;os by-ganne ferst trecherye</L>
<L>&THORN;or&yogh; &thorn;e feend, and ek enuye,</L>
<L N="750">Manne for to wynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="126" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And wonderuol was &thorn;ys assay,<MILESTONE N="218b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And wonder-lyche &yogh;ede man a-way,</L>
<L N="753">Ly&yogh;tlyche y-lore;</L>
<L>Ac wonder-lyche &yogh;et for&thorn; myt &thorn;an<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="163"></L>
<L>Her ine &thorn;ys world hys euer man</L>
<L N="756">To sorwe y-bore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="127" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac, crystene man, for al &thorn;ys wounder,</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne go nau&yogh;t onder</L>
<L N="759">&THORN;or&yogh; wantrokynge;</L>
<L>For so&thorn;e apreued hys &thorn;ys sa&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e by &thorn;e elde and nywe la&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="762">Wy&thorn;-oute lesynge.
<PB REF="00000174.tif" N="156"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="128" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And ske[l]fol was &thorn;ys ordinaunce,</L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; man by-uolle so hard a chaunce<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>by-uolle</I> may also be read <I>by uelle</I> in MS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="765">&THORN;or&yogh; trycherye;</L>
<L>For &thorn;or&yogh; mestrye &thorn;at he uor&thorn; dro&yogh;</L>
<L>&THORN;e feend in heuene lias hys lo&yogh;,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>lias</I> seems to be the reading of the MS.; Wright <I>has</I>, which makes no sense.</NOTE></L>
<L N="768">&THORN;or&yogh; pur mastrye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="129" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ry&yogh;t al-so, &thorn;o he gyle &thorn;ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>For to brynge man to no&yogh;te</L>
<L N="771">Pryuelyche,</L>
<L>God almy&yogh;ty, &thorn;at hys wyl wyste,</L>
<L>A&yogh;eyns hym &thorn;o&yogh;te go by lyste</L>
<L N="774">Al so styllyche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="130" TYPE="stanza">
<L>For ine &thorn;e trowe dea&thorn; was kene,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at god made wel y-sene,</L>
<L N="777">&THORN;et hyt for-bead;</L>
<L>And he weste &thorn;at god hyt sede,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>For.&mdash;he</I>, MS. <I>&yogh;e.&mdash;weste</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>wete</I> (pres.).</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;ef man &thorn;rof ete he scholde awede,</L>
<L N="780">And eke be dead.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="131" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac lyf was al-so ine &thorn;e trowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ac</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>And</I>.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="219a" UNIT="folio"><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="164"></L>
<L>Ac &thorn;at ne my&yogh;te be nau&yogh;t y-knowe,</L>
<L N="783">For god hyt hedde;</L>
<L>For hyt was pryue for a wyle<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>For</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>And</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>A&yogh;e &thorn;e fendes priue gyle</L>
<L N="786">&THORN;e man for-ledde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="132" TYPE="stanza">
<L>For nau&yogh;t nas hyt ycleped ne hys<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ne hys</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>y-wis</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Trou of lyue in paradys,</L>
<L N="789">Ac wyste;<NOTE PLACE="foot">K&ouml;lbing <I>Ac [god hyt] wyste</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For, ase man was &thorn;or&yogh; trowe by-cou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>In trowe he scholde be for-bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="792">&THORN;at &thorn;e fende neste.
<PB REF="00000175.tif" N="157"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="133" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;at was ine &thorn;e holy rode,</L>
<L>&THORN;or&yogh; &thorn;e schedynge of &thorn;e blode<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>schedynge</I>, MS. <I>schewynge</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="795">Of godes sone,</L>
<L>Ase ich her-after telle may,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he tok of a clene may<NOTE PLACE="foot">K&ouml;lbing inserts <I>lyf</I>, or <I>body</I>, between <I>&thorn;at</I> and <I>he</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="798">A&yogh;eyns wone.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="134" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hedde he wyst &thorn;er hedde ybe</L>
<L>Lyf for-boute ine &thorn;e appeltre,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for-boute</I>, read <I>for-hole</I>? K&ouml;lbing <I>for-houle</I> (=<I>for-hole</I>).</NOTE></L>
<L N="801">He nedde assaylled</L>
<L>No&thorn;er adam ne non of hys;</L>
<L>Ac are &thorn;e worlde was al &thorn;ys<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>al &thorn;ys</I>, MS. <I>and hys</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="804">Was y-conseyled.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="135" TYPE="stanza">
<L>God wyste wel &thorn;at man schold erry,</L>
<L>And &thorn;or&yogh; on-boxamnesse uerry</L>
<L N="807">Fram alle heal&thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore &thorn;at consayl was wel trye<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="165"></L>
<L>A&yogh;eyns &thorn;e feendes foule enuie</L>
<L N="810">To abatye wel&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="136" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ys consayl, hou hyt scholde be,<MILESTONE N="219b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Al was y-consayled of &thorn;re<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of &thorn;re</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>of [hem] &thorn;re</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="813">Ere eny tyme,</L>
<L>Of fader and sone and holy gost,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich was embe, ase &thorn;ou wel wost,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ase</I> K&ouml;lbing, MS. <I>&thorn;at</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="816">Ferst in &thorn;yse ryme.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="137" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And was &thorn;at conseyl so ytayled,<NOTE PLACE="foot">K&ouml;lbing puts <I>was</I> after <I>conseyl</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at hyt ne my&yogh;te habbe faylled</L>
<L N="819">To bote of manne,</L>
<L>And certeyn tyme yset &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>And hou hyt scholde be y-do,</L>
<L N="822">And wer and wanne.
<PB REF="00000176.tif" N="158"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="138" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And her mankende swank and dalf</L>
<L>Fy&yogh;f &thorn;ousend wynter and an half,</L>
<L N="825">And &yogh;et wel mo,</L>
<L>Er &thorn;ane &thorn;e tyme of lyue come,</L>
<L>And dea&thorn; man hedde for hys dome</L>
<L N="828">And helle also.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="139" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;et go[d] so longe abod, &thorn;e skele<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>skele</I>, MS. <I>skyle</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel mey be &thorn;ys, &thorn;at on of uele:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I>, MS. <I>os</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="831">To mannes mende;</L>
<L>For dea&thorn; scholde hys meystryes ke&thorn;e,</L>
<L>And [man] forsopie and for-se&thorn;e</L>
<L N="834">In dea&thorn;es bende,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="140" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at [he] my&yogh;te ry&yogh;t wel y-knowe<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="166"></L>
<L>&THORN;at he was ry&yogh;t al oue[r]-&thorn;rowe<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>oue</I>[<I>r</I>-<I>&thorn;rowe</I>, MS. <I>oue &thorn;reawe</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="837">And harde y-nome;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e fend hy&yogh;t my&yogh;te wene</L>
<L>&THORN;et men out of so longe tene</L>
<L N="840">Ne my&yogh;te come.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="141" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac her aryst a questio[u]n:<MILESTONE N="220a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at adam was bro&yogh;t a-doun</L>
<L N="843">And eue al-so,</L>
<L>Wet gelt hedden hy &thorn;at &thorn;o nere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>&thorn;o nere</I>, MS. <I>&thorn;onere</I> (Wright corr.).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;et hy to de&thorn;e ischape were,</L>
<L N="846">And eke to wo?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="142" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou syxt, bro&thorn;er, by &thorn;an by-fore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at oure aldren were al for-lore,</L>
<L N="849">Adam and eue;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ar nas of ham no partye</L>
<L>&THORN;at nas torned to vylanye,</L>
<L N="852">So to by-leue.
<PB REF="00000177.tif" N="159"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="143" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ac now be wey of ham y-come,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>wey = we</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wy&thorn; flesch and blod of ham i-nome,</L>
<L N="855">&THORN;et was ablowe</L>
<L>&THORN;or&yogh; &thorn;e fenym of &thorn;e fende;</L>
<L>&THORN;anne fal&thorn; ous rewelyche by kende</L>
<L N="858">To soffry wowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="144" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;os &thorn;at chyld to ny&yogh;t y-bore,</L>
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; hyt deyde, hyt were for-lore</L>
<L N="861">&YOGH;ef crystnynge nere,</L>
<L>&THORN;or&yogh; &thorn;e flesch &thorn;at hyt nome<NOTE PLACE="foot">K&ouml;lbing would supply <I>ha&thorn;</I> after <I>hyt</I>.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="167"></L>
<L>Of hys eldren &thorn;at hyt of come,</L>
<L N="864">&THORN;at wykkede were.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="145" TYPE="stanza">
<L>And neades moste [hyt], leaue bro&thorn;er,<NOTE PLACE="foot">K&ouml;lbing connects this stanza with the preceding one, by putting a comma after <I>were</I>, l. 864.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t of ham come, and man of o&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="867">And be nature;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>And</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>All</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For elles nadde man y-be</L>
<L>Nau&yogh;t y-lych gode in trynyte</L>
<L N="870">&THORN;or&yogh; engendrure.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="146" TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;a&yogh; hy be &thorn;or&yogh; senne demeyned,<MILESTONE N="220b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So nas hyt nau&yogh;t ferst y-ordeyned,</L>
<L N="873">&THORN;y[s] engendrure;</L>
<L>For &thorn;o man senne&yogh;ed in paradys,</L>
<L>Al chaungede &thorn;at flesch a-mys</L>
<L N="876">To mysauenture.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="147" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Elles nedde hyt be no senne,</L>
<L>&THORN;y[s] engendrure of al mankenne</L>
<L N="879">In al &thorn;ys wone,</L>
<L>Ac senne-leas hyt hadde ybe,</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;e engendrure in trynyte</L>
<L N="882">Of fader and sone.
<PB REF="00000178.tif" N="160"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="148" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ase mannes ylyche ymad of tre</L>
<L>May nau&yogh;t be al ase man may be</L>
<L N="885">Inne alle &thorn;ynge,</L>
<L>Ne godes ylyche, man, y-wys,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Ne</I>, K&ouml;lbing <I>&thorn;os</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne may nau&yogh;t be al ase god ys,</L>
<L N="888">Of heuene kyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="149" TYPE="stanza">
<L>For god, &thorn;e fader, hys leue sone<MILESTONE UNIT="Wright page" N="168"></L>
<L>Engendrede out of alle wone,</L>
<L N="891">Wy&thorn;-oute tyde;</L>
<L>Ac man ha&thorn; certayn tyme of elde</L>
<L>Wanne he may engendrure &yogh;elde,</L>
<L N="894">And tyme abyde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
